(72, 'Improving customer service at Hull & East Yorkshire Credit Union ', 'Converting documents to electronic format and shredding the paper copies has saved money on file storage. Electronic document management (EDM) has also helped efficiency and security whilst customer service has been boosted by putting critical documents at the fingertips of staff.', '<p class="introduction">Finance Manager Eddie Hotham tells us; &ldquo;we couldn&rsquo;t operate without an electronic document management system as we work with such a lot of paperwork. We have stayed with Arena for several years because they understand what we need and they give us such good and reliable service. There is&nbsp;always someone at the end of the phone if we have a problem and they&rsquo;re always&nbsp;quick to respond.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Improved customer service and document security</h2>\r\n<p>Paperwork relating to each client, including the identification they provide to open an account and all subsequent withdrawal, deposit and loan documents, is scanned into mstore. To retrieve an item from the system a member of staff simply searches on customer name or document type. Eddie comments; &ldquo;mstore saves us the cost of document storage and makes the set-up of new accounts more efficient. It&rsquo;s quick and easy to file and retrieve documents so we can answer queries and work through processes speedily. The system also helps us with security and preventing filing errors because all our users must log in. Only I can delete or move files once they&rsquo;ve been electronically indexed and this prevents us from mis-filing or losing paperwork.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Compliance with regulations</h2>\r\n<p><strong>m</strong>store also helps Hull Credit Union to comply with industry regulations, Eddie explained; &ldquo;we are governed by the FSA which means we have to retain documents for up to 7 years and then securely destroy them. We also have to be careful about protecting confidential paperwork and limiting access to the system using passwords helps us to do that. We also work with some external agencies which penalise us for sending them paper documents. Using mstore we can share documents electronically which keeps them secure and means we don&rsquo;t spend on printing and postage.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Looking forward to mstore for accounts payable</h2>\r\n<p>As the business grows and takes on more members, mstore is developing. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re planning to move our back-up servers off site soon so we&rsquo;ll have a more robust disaster recovery system in case something like a fire or flood destroys our paper documents. Arena is also helping us to look at using mstore to automate other areas of the business such as accounts payable so that we won&rsquo;t need to process paper invoices anymore.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>More information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">Arena''s <strong>m</strong>store: software for electronic document management</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../case_studies">More case studies</a></p>', '2012-01-29', 'Hull_Credit_Union_Picture.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 132323, '2012-01-30 10:29:53', 'Hull and East Yorkshire Credit Union', '2012-01-30 10:29:54', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'improving-customer-service-at-hull-east-yorkshire-credit-union'),
(73, 'Arena Group''s Open Day: Demos, prizes and exclusive guest offers', 'Armitage House will open its doors on April 26th and 27th 2012. We’ll be showcasing the latest devices for efficient print and copy, and our mstore software for electronic document management. Refreshments and prize draws will also be on offer, plus an exclusive free iPad give-away on guest orders for a limited period (terms apply).', '<p class="introduction"><strong><span class="font_blue">Armitage House will open its doors on April 26th and 27th 2012</span></strong>.</p>\r\n<p class="introduction">We&rsquo;ll be showcasing the latest devices for efficient print and copy, and our mstore software for electronic document management. Refreshments and prize draws will also be on offer, plus an exclusive free iPad give-away on guest orders for a limited period (terms apply).</p>\r\n<p>We will be hosting sessions to demonstrate;</p>\r\n<h2>How you could save 30% on print and copy:</h2>\r\n<p>See how our print audit process can reveal areas for cost saving, efficiency building and productivity growth. Watch a typical MPS system in action and hear about our clients who are already benefiting.</p>\r\n<h2>How to reduce your reliance on paper and work smarter:</h2>\r\n<p>How combining paper with electronic document management can transform your organisation and save you thousands.</p>\r\n<h2>How to reduce your carbon footprint and reach your sustainability goals:</h2>\r\n<p>See the newest tools for monitoring and controlling print and copy output and check out the latest super-clean, carbon neutral devices in our showroom.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Exclusive Offers for Open Day Guests</h1>\r\n<h3><img src="../../assets/articles/73/contained_images/2d99f83684cf_130_iPadPicture.jpg?1333114411" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="90" align="right" />CONGRATULATIONS!</h3>\r\n<p><strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">David Lodge</span> &ndash; St Michael&rsquo;s High School</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">Salmah Kafiq</span> &ndash; Feversham College</strong></p>\r\n<p>On arrival, guests will be invited to enter our free prize draw to win one of two Toshiba AT-100 android tablets.</p>\r\n<p>In addition, we&rsquo;re offering a free iPad or Toshiba tablet device to open day visitors who sign an order with us up to three months following their visit to the show room.*&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This event and its associated offers are&nbsp;exclusively&nbsp;for open day guests. Food and drinks will be available throughout the day.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>How to book your place</h2>\r\n<p><br />To help us maintain our usual high service standards please RSVP via phone: 0844 863 8000 or email <a href="mailto:info@arenagroup.net">info@arenagroup.net</a> to book your demonstration.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h6>*Devices are available whilst stocks last. For eligibility orders must exceed the value of &pound;2,000&nbsp;exclusive of&nbsp;VAT and be signed by July 31st 2012. This offer is not valid on quotes submitted before April 26th. Guests must RSVP and attend one open event in the Arena show room on April 26th or 27th. Arena''s usual <a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/38_Competition Terms and Conditions Arena Group.pdf" target="_blank">competition terms and conditions</a>&nbsp;apply.</h6>', '2012-04-01', 'Open_Sign_1.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 16271, '2012-03-30 13:54:32', 'Open Day', '2012-03-30 13:37:48', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arena-groups-open-day-demos-prizes-and-exclusive-guest-offers'),
(74, 'Europe calls for Data Protection Act changes - What could this mean for British Businesses?', 'The European Commission has recently proposed new regulations designed to harmonise data protection rules across the EU. Arena’s Neil Maude shares key points from the official response of the CBI and considers the potential impact on business.', '<p class="introduction">The European Commission has recently proposed new regulations designed to harmonise data protection rules across the EU. The Ministry of Justice has issued a &lsquo;call for evidence&rsquo; and in response the Confederation of British Industry (CBI) has created a position paper based on comment from its members, including Arena. This asks the EC to reconsider the proposed legislation to avoid undue disadvantage to businesses.</p>\r\n<p class="indented">&ldquo;Data protection is an important duty for any business &ndash; your customers won&rsquo;t do business with you if they don&rsquo;t trust how you treat their data.&nbsp; Our comments to the CBI were based on our experiences of securing data and in helping companies with data discovery, so we were able to highlight issues around both intellectual property and the potential costs of compliance with the proposed legislation.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p class="indented"><strong><em>Neil Maude, General Manager of Arena Group</em></strong></p>\r\n<h2>The Proposal</h2>\r\n<p><br />The intention of the EC proposal is to bring together the diverse data protection legislation across its various member states, with the aim of creating a &lsquo;digital single market&rsquo; in Europe.&nbsp; With increasing business use of data and data portability there is a genuine need to clarify the legislation &ndash; even more so with the rise of &lsquo;Cloud&rsquo; computing.&nbsp; For example, it is quite possible for a UK to company to use 3rd party computing services located in another country and subject to non-UK legislation.&nbsp; This is compounded by user concerns regarding how their personal data might be used, as shown in media coverage of high-profile companies such as Facebook and Google.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The legislation attempts to resolve these issues, using concepts including the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A requirement for individuals to give <strong class="font_blue">explicit consent </strong>whenever their data is collected and used.</li>\r\n<li>Giving internet users a <strong><span class="font_blue">right to be forgotten </span></strong>when they would like their data to be deleted if they withdraw their consent and there are no legitimate grounds to retain it</li>\r\n<li>A right to <strong><span class="font_blue">data portability </span></strong>to obtain data from one organisation and move it to another </li>\r\n<li>A <strong><span class="font_blue">right to information </span></strong>which would ensure that individuals are fully informed about the way their information is handled</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The concern of the CBI is that the proposed legislation will actually cause more confusion in the mind of consumers and that businesses will incur excessive costs to comply.</p>\r\n<h2>What might this mean in practice?</h2>\r\n<p><br />The operational implications for businesses routinely using or retaining personal customer data could be significant and wide-ranging.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For example, the <strong><span class="font_blue">right to be forgotten </span></strong>rule could potentially require a company to trawl through all of its data archives to ensure that any relevant mention of that individual is erased.&nbsp; Arena&rsquo;s experience of legal discovery work - where the task is to locate all data related to a particular individual or case - shows that this can be a costly and time-consuming exercise.&nbsp; Potentially a company could be searching e-mail servers, file servers and even paper documents for any mention of an individual.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>However, the impact of the legislation could go far beyond immediate costs and the CBI paper includes examples of how the <strong><span class="font_blue">right to data portability </span></strong>could deter companies from innovation in data usage, if they know that a portability request would mean revealing their practices to competitors.</p>\r\n<p>Other elements of the proposal bring costly requirements for Data Protection Officers to be appointed, onerous disclosure timeframes and potentially crippling fines of up to 2% of company turnover.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>It is not hard to imagine the impact if legislation, which may be entirely appropriate when applied to Facebook, becomes an obligation on all sizes and types of business.</p>\r\n<h2>Summary</h2>\r\n<p><br />The new legislation was first proposed in 2011 and is now at first reading stage in the European Parliament.&nbsp; The CBI is asking for a rethink of the proposal to allow for a more &lsquo;proportionate, risk-based approach&rsquo; and reduce the scope of the new regulations.&nbsp; The proposal is clearly going to be subject to significant debate.</p>\r\n<p>These moves highlight the current issues and public concerns surrounding the use of data by companies. Protection of individual data is clearly an essential requirement in the modern business environment and compliance with existing Data Protection Act legislation is mandatory. All businesses should consider the advice already available here.&nbsp; These principles are good practice as it is unlikely that regulations will be loosened in the future.</p>\r\n<h2>More information:</h2>\r\n<p><br />CBI Position Paper: <br /><a href="http://www.cbi.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/2012/03/eu-data-protection-reforms-risk-strangling-innovation-cbi/">http://www.cbi.org.uk/media-centre/press-releases/2012/03/eu-data-protection-reforms-risk-strangling-innovation-cbi/</a></p>\r\n<p><br />European Commission proposal in full: <br /><a href="http://ec.europa.eu/justice/newsroom/data-protection/news/120125_en.htm">http://ec.europa.eu/justice/newsroom/data-protection/news/120125_en.htm</a></p>', '2012-03-05', 'legislation_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 90546, '2014-12-11 17:35:20', '', '2012-03-30 14:07:57', '2014-12-11 17:36:09', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'europe-calls-for-data-protection-act-changes-what-could-this-mean-for-british-businesses'),
(75, 'York High School on Document Security', 'We recently spoke to York High School to find out about their new strategy for managing pupil records securely in line with BS10008. They told us that it has delivered a host of other unexpected benefits including liberated storage space and speedier retrieval of documents.', '<p class="introduction">We recently spoke to York High School to find out about their new strategy for managing pupil records securely in line with BS10008. They told us that it has delivered a host of other unexpected benefits including liberated storage space and speedier retrieval of documents.</p>\r\n<p>York High School is the city&rsquo;s newest secondary school with approximately 800 pupils. Arena&rsquo;s software for electronic document management, <strong>m</strong>store, is used to manage pupil records and the school is getting on so well with it that plans are now underway to roll the system out to its finance and human resources teams too.</p>\r\n<h2>Creating a &lsquo;less paper office&rsquo; - Paper to pixels</h2>\r\n<p>Schools are legally required to keep specified document types for varying periods of time. Rules surrounding security of sensitive files mean that, if dealing with paper, filing and retrieval of documents can be very time consuming and archives can take up valuable storage space. These issues can be overcome by converting paper documents to electronic files and, as long as BS10008 is adhered to, those files retain the legal admissibility of their paper counterparts.</p>\r\n<p>Pastoral Administrator, Sarah Buglass, told us; &ldquo;the main reason we bought mstore was to make our documents more secure. We have to be really careful with safeguarding rules, managing who can access what and how long we keep documents for. mstore is much more secure than paper files locked in a room, it&rsquo;s quicker to find documents too and has made my job easier.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We had a special storage room for our paper pupil records. They were locked in cabinets and filed in alphabetical order - it could take a long time to find things. We have put all of those records into mstore and knocked down the wall where the storage room used to be which has given us lots more office space.</p>\r\n<h2>Security and audit trails</h2>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Only me and one other person can scan and index documents into the system and our admin manager is the only person who can delete documents. It&rsquo;s highly unlikely that we will lose a document once it&rsquo;s saved. Only a small number of authorised people can access documents so there is no chance of anyone wandering off with something they shouldn&rsquo;t have. The system also keeps a record of all activity so we know how and who is viewing, sharing and updating documents.</p>\r\n<h2>Document retention&nbsp;and crisis recovery</h2>\r\n<p>Whilst schools are legally obliged to keep some documents, they are also required to securely destroy them once the end of the retention period is reached.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;<strong>m</strong>store is set up to alert us when documents reach their retention deadlines so we can&rsquo;t keep them for longer than we&rsquo;re allowed to. This means we don&rsquo;t have to worry about archiving and shredding everything by hand and we have saved the time and cost associated with that. Our records would also be safe if we had a fire because they are all backed up on a server so we could recover them if we needed to.</p>\r\n<h2>Improved efficiency and productivity</h2>\r\n<p>Schools dealing with paper could have a mountain to climb in terms of finding all the relevant documents in preparation for an unexpected event such as a court case. A system such as mstore addresses this issue by linking documents by terms of common reference, and making them easily searchable.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Documents are easy and quick to find because we can search mstore using various terms like pupil names or document types. The task of scanning and indexing our archive into the system was fast and simple and now I take a new stack of documents to the scanner at the end of each day.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The training from Arena was really good and we&rsquo;ve only had a few problems with the system since it was installed. These were resolved on the same day we reported them and we&rsquo;ve had no bad service so we&rsquo;re really pleased. I&rsquo;d be happy to recommend Arena.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>More information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">Arena''s <strong>m</strong>store: software for electronic document management</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../case_studies">More case studies</a></p>', '2012-03-29', 'YHS_WS.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 93905, '2014-12-11 17:31:19', '', '2012-03-30 14:18:44', '2014-12-11 17:31:20', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'york-high-school-on-document-security'),
(76, 'Fresh approach to business records checks', 'HMRC recently released a review of the 2011 Business Records Checks (BRC) pilot programme. This was a check of business record keeping standards in SMEs.  The scheme checked the records of over 2,400 businesses and found issues in 39% of those examined. In 11% of cases – more than 1 in 10 – these issues were serious enough to warrant further investigations.  ', '<p><span class="introduction">In February of this year, HMRC released a review of the 2011 Business Records Checks (BRC) pilot programme. This was a check of business record keeping standards in SMEs.&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n<p>The scheme checked the records of over 2,400 businesses and found issues in 39% of those examined. In 11% of cases &ndash; more than 1 in 10 &ndash; these issues were serious enough to warrant further investigations by HMRC.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The HMRC definition of an &lsquo;SME&rsquo; is a business up to &pound;30M turnover and with up to 250 staff, so this programme clearly has a broad remit.&nbsp; HMRC had originally planned to visit some 20,000 businesses in 2012/13.&nbsp; However, the review suggested that HMRC would be better served by more targeted checks in future so the programme has been suspended pending a revamp and consultation with representative industry bodies.&nbsp; Following this, the programme will restart at some point in the 2012/12 tax year, with renewed focus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>HMRC guidance on record keeping is pragmatic and allows for the cases where people make mistakes.&nbsp; But it also <em><span class="font_blue">clearly requires businesses to show &lsquo;reasonable care&rsquo; in &lsquo;keeping full and accurate records which are regularly updated and saved securely&rsquo;</span></em>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Further, <em class="font_blue">if business records are lost, stolen or destroyed, the onus is on the business to do it&rsquo;s &lsquo;best to recreate them&rsquo;</em>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A well implemented electronic document management solution could go a long way to reducing the administrative burden of record keeping and reducing the risk &ndash; both of non-compliance due to missing records or information being lost due to fire, flood or theft.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Besides storage and security, <a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">electronic document management </a>systems also bring wider benefits in the processing of the transactions themselves, such as electronic purchase invoice approval.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information:</h2>\r\n<p>mstore &ndash; Arena&rsquo;s own software for electronic document management:<br /><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">http://www.arenagroup.net/page/electronic-document-management</a></p>\r\n<p>HMRC Business Records Check review: <a href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/businessrecordscheck/">http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/businessrecordscheck/</a></p>\r\n<p>HMRC Guidance on Electronic Invoices: <a href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/vat/managing/charging/e-invoices.htm">http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/vat/managing/charging/e-invoices.htm</a></p>\r\n<p>HMRC Guidance on PAYE record keeping:&nbsp; <a href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/paye/payroll/day-to-day/records.htm">http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/paye/payroll/day-to-day/records.htm</a></p>', '2012-03-06', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2012-03-30 14:57:52', '2014-12-11 17:29:30', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'fresh-approach-to-business-records-checks'),
(77, 'Arena Group and Guy Salmon Land Rover team-up in Support of Help The Heroes', 'Arena Group recently received generous support from Guy Salmon Land Rover, Wakefield to raise funds in Support of Help the Heroes.', '<p>The Arena Group Annual Conference brings all&nbsp;of our&nbsp;employees together to hear about how the business is performing and plans going forward. This year the event was hosted at the Forest Pines Hotel in Brigg, Lincolnshire.</p>\r\n<p>The evening of the event always involves a formal dinner and this year a few of our team members met-up for the first time and got chatting about <a href="http://www.helpforheroes.org.uk" target="_blank">Help&nbsp;For Heroes</a>, which is a cause they hold close to their hearts.</p>\r\n<p>Before long a plan was hatched to raise some cash for the charity and happily, one of our guests happened to be&nbsp;Guy Salmon''s Simon Mclean who was accompanying his wife Claire, a Customer Relationship Manager for Arena.</p>\r\n<h2>On a&nbsp;Fundraising Roll</h2>\r\n<p>Simon generously offered a half day off road driving experience, (a fantastic experience for 4x4 drivers interested in adventure) on behalf of Guy Salmon in Wakefield. This was auctioned to&nbsp;Arena''s Group Sales Manager for &pound;200.</p>\r\n<p>A collection raised a further &pound;200 and one of&nbsp;our account managers&nbsp;generously matched the sum to raise &pound;800.&nbsp;Arena''s policy&nbsp;of match funding charitable fundraising efforts undertaken by&nbsp;staff delivered an impressive total pledge.</p>\r\n<p>In total we raised&nbsp;&pound;1600 for&nbsp;<a href="http://www.helpforheroes.org.uk" target="_blank">Help&nbsp;For Heroes</a>, which is a fantastic result.</p>', '2012-03-12', 'help4heroes.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 108577, '2012-04-18 09:49:08', 'Help for Heroes logo', '2012-04-18 09:49:09', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arena-group-and-guy-salmon-land-rover-team-up-in-support-of-help-the-heroes'),
(78, 'Arena supports the Swallow Hill School Careers Event', 'Arena Group''s Martin Wright and Lisa Butterworth attended the Swallow Hill Community College Careers Day at Farnell Element14 on the 29th March. We are told that the event was a great success and the school and pupils learnt a lot from the day. Feedback from both volunteers at the event and students was extremely positive.', '<p>The school&rsquo;s aims for the day were to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Increase students&rsquo; working aspirations</li>\r\n<li>Increase the students&rsquo; confidence and self-belief</li>\r\n<li>Increase the students&rsquo; knowledge of what&rsquo;s available post-16, including higher and further education</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In the morning the students attended practice interviews alongside fun, interactive sessions around employability skills. The interview sessions proved invaluable and every student stated that they felt the session has helped prepare them for future interviews.</p>\r\n<p>The afternoon was dedicated to a Careers Marketplace Event. Eight businesses took part including Arena Group, providing the students with an opportunity to find out more about various careers. This gave the attendees an insight in the core skills and qualifications they will need for various industries, and an opportunity to discuss the real life academic, training and work expereinces of the business representatives in attendance.</p>\r\n<p>The school are very satisfied that these aims were met and believe that the activity has had a significant positive impact on 51 students who attended.</p>', '2012-04-19', 'Careers_swallowHill.png', 'image/x-png', 207222, '2012-04-19 15:24:30', 'Swallow Hill Picture', '2012-04-19 15:24:31', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arena-supports-the-swallow-hill-school-careers-event'),
(79, 'Cycle 80 miles in the rain? Anything for a good cause!', 'April marked 10 years since Jane Tomlinson ran the London marathon for the first time and the beginning of her endurance challenge milestones in aid of the Jane Tomlinson Appeal. In honor of this special anniversary, Mike and Rebecca Tomlinson took on an 8 day challenge.', '<p>April marked 10 years since Jane Tomlinson ran the London marathon for the first time and the beginning of her endurance challenge milestones in aid of the Jane Tomlinson Appeal. In honor of this special anniversary, Mike and Rebecca Tomlinson took on an 8 day challenge completing the Paris Marathon ahead of a 6 day cycle route to London ahead of the London Marathon via the Appeal&rsquo;s home turf of Yorkshire. Taking in the region&rsquo;s key landmarks Mike and Rebecca were joined by a team of cyclists as they pedaled up to 100 miles a day to the capital.</p>\r\n<p>Along the way the team was joined by a number of surprise guests taking part in the challenge, including our very own Nick Payne and Adrian Fitzpatrick who geared-up for a grueling 130km route from Hull to Leeds via York on April 18th.</p>\r\n<p>As if the distance were not challenge enough, the team&nbsp;had unfortunate weather - &nbsp;cold temperatures and&nbsp;torrential rain throughout the day!</p>', '2012-04-23', 'IMG-20120418-00103.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 102343, '2012-05-23 15:28:55', 'Cycle Challenge Photo', '2012-05-23 15:28:59', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'cycle-80-miles-in-the-rain-anything-for-a-good-cause'),
(80, 'On starter''s orders in Leeds!', 'On May 13th Leeds hosted the Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Runs which saw 1300 youngsters aged between 3 and 14 take on 1.5km and 2.5km courses in the city center. ', '<p>The event is now in its fourth year and, thanks to funding from Arena, it has become the region&rsquo;s biggest free mass participation event for children.</p>\r\n<p>Several staff from Arena attended the event on a beautiful sunny Sunday, to help out with marshaling and greeting children on the finish line. Our HR Manager, Martin Wright, was proud to help start the race and award prizes to winning schools and runners at the end of the race.</p>\r\n<p>Congratulations to the winners of the schools challenge, St Margaret&rsquo;s Primary School in Horsforth and Royds High School in Oulton. Royds pupils, Josh Brown [14] and William Collumb [13] were the two fastest boys while 14-year-old Jasmine Laidler was the fastest girl.</p>\r\n<p>Check out the video produced by Run for All at <a href="http://bit.ly/JFv0NU" target="_blank">http://bit.ly/JFv0NU</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Still to come &hellip;</h2>\r\n<p>The summer promises more activity in support of the Jane Tomlinson Appeal with Arena teams training to compete in 10k runs in Leeds (8th July) and York (5th August) or volunteering to help out with Junior and Mini events to be hosted in Hull (3rd June) and York (5th August).</p>', '2012-05-14', 'CrowdofChildren_Startline.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 135235, '2012-05-23 15:44:21', 'Starting crowd', '2012-05-23 15:38:42', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'on-starters-orders-in-leeds'),
(81, '5 top tips for selecting a Managed Print Service provider', 'There are so many different packages currently on the market under the guise of ‘Managed Print Service’ (MPS) that making a purchase can be complex and fraught with risk. We’ve set out a simple checklist of key pointers to help you ensure that you are getting the genuine article.', '<p class="introduction">There are so many different packages currently on the market under the guise of &lsquo;Managed Print Service&rsquo; (MPS) that making a purchase can be complex and fraught with risk. We&rsquo;ve set out a simple checklist of key pointers to help you ensure that you are getting the genuine article.</p>\r\n<h2>1.&nbsp;Clarify your current situation</h2>\r\n<p>A genuine managed print service provider will always carry out a print audit to assess how much output is coming from your current print/copy devices. This will include a cost and environmental impact assessment and will require a month&rsquo;s worth of data from your current machines.&nbsp; Expect a detailed report on your present situation and a proposed strategy to maintain or improve your costs, efficiencies and sustainability.</p>\r\n<p>A good MPS provider will propose a &lsquo;balanced deployment&rsquo; that considers your needs for document security, quality and convenience. Watch out for suppliers who show you a plan to consolidate all of your print and copy output through a small number of strategically placed devices. This will show you a dramatic cost reduction but is not necessarily the most beneficial set-up for you, especially if some of your staff will need to travel a long way to their nearest printer or if you are working with sensitive documents and need some desktop devices that can only be used by authorised employees.</p>\r\n<h2>2.&nbsp;Secrets in the software</h2>\r\n<p>Once you have implemented a managed print service you will never need to order toner again. Your devices will also be configured to alert your provider when a technical problem or routine service is needed. In theory, an engineer will call on you before you even know there is a problem.</p>\r\n<h2>3.&nbsp;Protect your balance sheet from nasty surprises</h2>\r\n<p>A major advantage of a managed print service is simplified billing. Over the course of a contractual period, lasting anything up to 6 years, expect one regular invoice (usually paid monthly) that combines all of your print/copy/imaging, servicing and toner costs into one, fixed price.</p>\r\n<h2>4.&nbsp;Be the boss and take control</h2>\r\n<p>An effective managed print service delivers devices integrated with <a href="../../../articles/112?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">specialist software (often referred to as &lsquo;rules based&rsquo;)</a> that, at a basic level, monitors and reports on activity and output. At a more complex level it can feature default settings and user authentication technologies to control output and minimise waste.</p>\r\n<h2>5.&nbsp;Read the small print</h2>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a sad fact that some unethical print/copy providers are passing off second hand, refurbished devices and remanufactured toner cartridges as brand new. Make sure you get what you pay for. Also, understand what your provider will require of you should you decide to exit your service agreement before it matures as there may be a buy-out fee or other penalties.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/112?tag=Expert+News">Putting the brakes on wasteful print and copy</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/print-the-hidden-costs">Print: The Hidden Costs</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/139?tag=Expert+News">INFOGRAHIC: Print control in pictures</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/130?tag=Expert+News">INFOGRAPHIC: The process behind Arena''s Managed Print Service</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2012-05-30', 'printersInHand_EDITED.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 172334, '2014-12-11 17:13:40', '', '2012-05-31 15:56:05', '2014-12-11 17:13:43', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, '5-top-tips-for-selecting-a-managed-print-service-provider'),
(82, 'Pushing pedals and pounding pavements in support of the Jane Tomlinson Appeal', 'Over recent months Arena staff have joined a special endurance challenge, supported the Arena Group Junior and Mini fun runs in Leeds and started to train for forthcoming 10k Corporate Team Challenges.', '<p class="introduction">Over recent months Arena staff have joined a special endurance challenge, supported the Arena Group Junior and Mini fun runs in Leeds and started to train for forthcoming 10k Corporate Team Challenges.</p>\r\n<h2>Pedal Power</h2>\r\n<p>April marked 10 years since Jane Tomlinson ran the London marathon for the first time and the beginning of her endurance challenge milestones in aid of the Jane Tomlinson Appeal. In honor of this special anniversary, Mike and Rebecca Tomlinson took on an 8 day challenge completing the Paris Marathon ahead of a 6 day cycle route to London ahead of the London Marathon via the Appeal&rsquo;s home turf of Yorkshire. Taking in the region&rsquo;s key landmarks Mike and Rebecca were joined by a team of cyclists as they pedaled up to 100 miles a day to the capital.</p>\r\n<p>Along the way the team was joined by a number of surprise guests taking part in the challenge, including our very own Nick Payne and Adrian Fitzpatrick who geared-up for a grueling 130km route from Hull to Leeds via York on April 18th.</p>\r\n<h2>Little Legs</h2>\r\n<p>On May 13th Leeds hosted the Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Runs which saw 1300 youngsters aged between 3 and 14 take on 1.5km and 2.5km courses in the city center. The event is now in its fourth year and, thanks to funding from Arena, it has become the region&rsquo;s biggest free mass participation event for children. Several staff from Arena attended the event on a beautiful sunny Sunday, to help out with marshaling and greeting children on the finish line.</p>\r\n<p>Congratulations to the winners of the schools challenge, St Margaret&rsquo;s Primary School in Horsforth and Royds High School in Oulton. Royds pupils, Josh Brown [14] and William Collumb [13] were the two fastest boys while 14-year-old Jasmine Laidler was the fastest girl.</p>\r\n<h2>Still to come &hellip;</h2>\r\n<p>The summer promises more activity in support of the Jane Tomlinson Appeal with Arena teams training to compete in 10k runs in Leeds (8th July) and York (5th August) or volunteering to help out with Junior and Mini events to be hosted in Hull (3rd June) and York (5th August).</p>\r\n<h2>Pledge your support</h2>\r\n<p>If you would like to support Arena Group&rsquo;s 10k Challenge Teams who are preparing to run in Leeds and York please visit <a href="http://www.justgiving.com/company/arenagroup">http://www.justgiving.com/company/arenagroup</a></p>', '2012-05-30', 'RFA Logo.png', 'image/x-png', 244458, '2012-05-31 16:07:04', 'RFA Logo', '2012-05-31 16:00:57', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'pushing-pedals-and-pounding-pavements-in-support-of-the-jane-tomlinson-appeal'),
(83, 'Help wanted? Give us a call!', 'We have volunteers with time to spare and enthusiasm galore to get involved with practical projects that support charity and community causes.   ', '<p class="introduction">We have volunteers with time to spare and enthusiasm galore to get involved with practical projects that support charity and community causes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Since 1991 Arena has expanded over&nbsp;6 sites across Yorkshire, Lincolnshire and Lancashire. It&rsquo;s important to us that we contribute to our local communities and therefore we encourage our employees to get out of the office for up to&nbsp;2 days each year to pledge their time and effort.</p>\r\n<h2>We would welcome your invitations, feedback and ideas.</h2>\r\n<p>Over the years our charitable and voluntary projects have supported children or young people as well as the elderly, disabled and infirm living and working in our local communities.</p>\r\n<p>Our staff have taken care of things like gardening and painting at schools and community centers, and helped to host events such as an annual Christmas celebration event for the elderly.</p>\r\n<p>Arena employees are also happy to contribute their specialist skills, so if you are hosting a careers day at your school and would like us to attend and talk about our jobs, or if you need help with a particular business task, we might be able to help you.</p>\r\n<p>In addition to this we enter teams to compete in running, swimming, rowing and walking events to raise funds for various charities.</p>\r\n<h2>Contact us to propose a project</h2>\r\n<p>If you work for, or know of, a worthy community group cause or charity based near us that would benefit from our support, time and practical efforts then please contact our Marketing Team: <a class="font_blue" href="mailto:lisab@arenagroup.net"></a><a href="mailto:marketing@arenagroup.net">marketing@arenagroup.net</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<p>Check out our CSR work on our <a href="../../../page/arena-in-the-community">Community Page</a>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2013-06-18', 'CSRgardener.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 118140, '2014-12-11 14:51:41', '', '2012-05-31 16:11:08', '2015-02-03 15:19:40', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'help-wanted-give-us-a-call'),
(84, 'Guidance on records management for schools', 'This month the IRMS published the fourth edition of its Records Management Toolkit for Schools. ', '<p class="introduction">The introduction from IRMS chair, Matthew Stephenson, states; &ldquo;This incredibly useful booklet is an absolute must for every head teacher and school administrator. In its few pages is virtually everything a school will need to manage its information and records effectively and professionally.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>We are very proud to note that Arena&rsquo;s own software for document management, <strong>m</strong>store for Education, provides all the necessary features to support the increasingly strict guidelines surrounding document management in schools.</p>\r\n<p>Whilst the IRMS provide this guidance for schools to use, they are unable to give one-to-one advice or take enquires.&nbsp; However, Arena would be pleased to provide assistance and further explanations, if you would like to get in touch.</p>\r\n<h2><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school" target="_blank">Download the toolkit document</a></h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank">More about mstore for Education</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2012-05-22', 'iStock_000003015755Small_Blackboard.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 365267, '2012-05-31 16:21:12', 'Blackboard', '2012-05-31 16:19:20', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'guidance-on-records-management-for-schools'),
(85, 'Arena''s Service Team is Toshiba’s official UK #1!', 'Our technicians ran away with this year’s Toshiba Tec UK Service Incentive competition, proving that when it comes to Toshiba hardware, software and networking, Arena Group is the manufacturer’s UK number one service provider. ', '<p class="introduction">Toshiba technicians representing dealerships across the UK were invited to take an online test to win 30 places up for grabs to top scorers. The 30 finalists came together to pitch their skills against each other to prove that their skills and knowledge of Toshiba products are accurate and up-to-date.</p>\r\n<p>Our technicians claimed <strong>13</strong> of those places, proving that Arena has at least 13 of the best Toshiba technicians in the country.</p>\r\n<h2>#1&nbsp;Toshiba Network Technician in the UK</h2>\r\n<p>Following a day of exams and practical challenges, Arena&rsquo;s Professional Services Technician, <strong class="font_blue">Richard Webb </strong>was named the best Toshiba Network Technician in the UK.</p>\r\n<h2>High calibre Field Service Technician</h2>\r\n<p>Field Service Technician, <strong class="font_blue">Kyle Arnold </strong>was awarded the 2nd Best Hardware Technician in the UK.</p>\r\n<p>Arena Group&rsquo;s service team was heralded as The Best Toshiba service team in the UK.</p>\r\n<p>So, this is further reassurance for those using a Toshiba machine from Arena Group, that you will be receiving tip-top service, plus up-to-the-minute knowledge and advice.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2012-05-07', '_DSC1524.JPG', 'image/pjpeg', 292711, '2012-05-31 16:28:59', 'Arena Techies', '2012-05-31 16:29:05', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arenas-service-team-is-toshiba’s-official-uk-1'),
(86, '190,000 invoices - managing the paper wave … ', 'When Arena began working with AtlasFram in 2003 the business was processing 125,000 paper invoices each year and looking to improve the efficiency of their accounts payable process. Now that AtlasFram is receiving almost 200,000 invoices annually, we checked in to see whether their technology has stood the tests of time and an ever-increasing workload.', '<p class="introduction">The AtlasFram Group is one of the UK&rsquo;s largest farmer-owned input purchasing and crop marketing groups for professional arable and livestock farmers. Owned by, and existing solely to serve and represent its significant membership base, it provides a range of schemes tailored to support individual farm businesses. <br />The challenge in 2003</p>\r\n<p>Ian Caley, Group Accountant for the cooperative, explains; &ldquo;our members prefer to receive their invoices on paper so we spent a lot of time processing and marking up supplier invoices to pass on to them. We would photocopy each document to file for our own records before manually typing key accounting information into our accounts system.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;If we wanted to retrieve an original photocopy it meant searching through lots of paper filed in cabinets, often stored off-site. We were dealing with around 125,000 invoices annually so the whole process was very tedious and slow.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>The solution</h2>\r\n<p><br />Following a consultation, Arena installed mstore, our own software for electronic document management. This enables AtlasFram to digitise their paper invoices, mark them up and share them electronically before destroying the paper copies.<br />&ldquo;We are not a conventional business in any sense. We had very specific requirements that the Arena advisor was able to understand very quickly and give us reassuring answers to. Arena worked closely with us to make sure our accounts software was properly integrated to work with mstore. The whole process was fast and straight-forward, with no interruption to the running of the business.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>The results</h2>\r\n<p><br />The number of invoices received by AtlasFram has increased to 190,000 per year and Ian is extremely pleased with mstore; &ldquo;at the press of a button the accounts team is able to retrieve any document. There is never a need to rifle through mountains of paper and queries can be resolved on the first phone call. This makes us more productive, frees-up time to get on with other tasks and has improved our customer service. After six months original paper invoices are destroyed so we have a lot more space and no need for external storage.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>New developments to date</h2>\r\n<p>Since the initial installation of mstore the system has been developed to manage the growing amount of paper received for processing. This has reduced the amount of manual data entry required to populate the accounts system and further digitised the accounts process.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s difficult to talk about return on investment in simple financial terms. mstore has made our lives so much easier and that is worth a great deal to us. Repetitive tasks that allowed for error have been removed and in every way mstore has delivered on Arena&rsquo;s promises.</p>\r\n<p>"We have a good relationship with Arena and the support issues we occasionally face are dealt with quickly. We definitely made the right move and we have no reason to regret what was, at the time, a fairly daunting and business-changing decision for us.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../case_studies">Read more case studies</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2012-05-16', 'paper_wave.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 356240, '2012-05-31 16:33:24', 'paper wave', '2012-05-31 16:32:06', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, '190000-invoices-managing-the-paper-wave-…'),
(87, 'Dizzy Heights for Arena''s Marcus Wallis ', 'Marcus Wallis, director of Arena''s Grantham site (also known as Fovia) recently undertook a mamouth climb to the top of Mount Kilimanjaro. We asked him to tell us all about it!', '<p class="introduction">Marcus Wallis, director of Arena''s Grantham site (also known as Fovia) recently undertook a mamouth climb to the top of Mount Kilimanjaro. We asked him to tell us all about it!</p>\r\n<h2>The team and the route</h2>\r\n<p>Marcus&nbsp;tackled the challenge with former Arena director <strong>Colin Grave</strong> and another good friend, <strong>Trevor Chapel.</strong>&nbsp;They were joined by 5 other climbers and a team of 37 guides and porters; "they&nbsp;astounded us with their tireless ability to scale the mountain very quickly whilst weighed down with kit and food."&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The group&nbsp;climbed the <strong>Lemosho trail</strong>, which is not the steepest and quickest but definitely the most strenuous walk&nbsp;Marcus has&nbsp;endured to date. &ndash; "Yorkshire&rsquo;s Three Peaks are nothing by comparison! The climb took us a total of 8 days with 6 nights under canvas on the route up, and 2 on our descent."</p>\r\n<h2>Challenging conditions</h2>\r\n<p>Being an avid and experienced fell walker and runner,&nbsp;Marcus is&nbsp;fairly fit, but Kilimanjaro was a real endurance test. "Our journey took us through 5 different climate zones, starting out with tropical equator heat around 30?C and rain forest terrain at the base of the mountain. Tundra came next, starting-out lush and green before getting sparser as we climbed higher. Finally, we were in ice deserts at high altitude where the weather is bitterly cold and temperatures dip way below 0?C. Evenings were particularly chilly so we wrapped up in loads of layers to keep warm!"&nbsp;The heroic porters had to carry masses of clothing and equipment to prepare&nbsp;the climbers&nbsp;for this dramatic variety of environments&nbsp;- "they&nbsp;still out-paced us and remained cheery throughout!"</p>\r\n<h2>Final push to the summit</h2>\r\n<p>The team reached base camp at <strong>16,000ft </strong>on the 6th day and waited until midnight to make a final push for the summit. Although&nbsp;they were taking advantage of calmer night-time weather on Kilimanjaro&rsquo;s peak, where conditions can be particularly erratic and dangerous,&nbsp;they set out in pitch black against a -10?C chill. Marcus says; "the climb was incredibly tough and steep but I&rsquo;ll never forget the feeling of pure exhilaration when I reached the peak to watch a beautiful sunrise, having fulfilled a massive personal goal."</p>\r\n<h2>Climbing for a cause</h2>\r\n<p>Thus far Marcus has raised <strong>&pound;1300</strong> for <a href="http://www.ambucopter.org.uk/" target="_blank">The Lincolnshire Air Ambulance</a> and <a href="http://www.willoughby.lincs.sch.uk/" target="_blank">The Willoughby School</a> in Bourne for severely handicapped children. He is still collecting funds and every penny is going to charity as he funded the entire cost of his own&nbsp;climb.</p>', '2012-05-28', 'kili3 (2).jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 49705, '2012-06-01 13:49:53', 'Kilimanjaro', '2012-06-01 13:49:56', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'dizzy-heights-for-arenas-marcus-wallis');
