(88, 'Visit us at PfH Live 2012!', 'We will be hosting stand P100 at next week''s Procurement for Housing Live exhibition at Manchester''s GMEX Center.', '<p class="introduction">PfH Live is the biggest procurement event ever held for the social housing sector, reflecting a growing need to create efficiencies and cost savings in a tough economic climate.</p>\r\n<h2>Visit Arena Group at stand P100, June 12th - 14th</h2>\r\n<p>We will be sharing&nbsp;information and demonstrations&nbsp;covering print/copy devices and&nbsp;management software,&nbsp;plus our very own&nbsp;<strong>m</strong>store software for electronic document management.</p>\r\n<p>Such is the strategic importance of procurement, it is now a constant feature of board level discussions across the public sector. In order to reflect this change, PfH along with its partners HouseMark, the Chartered Institute of Housing and the National Housing Federation decided that&nbsp;the sector''s&nbsp;national procurement consortium should host its annual event alongside the sector&rsquo;s largest housing event.</p>\r\n<p>PfH Live will be an essential event for everyone involved in driving efficiency from chief executives and finance directors to tenants, but it will focus particularly on the professionalisation of procurement for those who are charged with driving strategic efficiencies within their organisations.</p>\r\n<ul class="bullet_list">\r\n<li>\r\n<p>Suppliers, including Arena Group,&nbsp;will be showcasing their products and services, explaining how each framework agreement works and answering&nbsp;questions for delegates.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>The PfH Central Billing team will be in attendance to talk&nbsp;about how the additional management information provided by the system can reduce fraud risk and improve efficiency.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<p>PfH Live will also host a series of FREE masterclass seminars delivered by key speakers.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>More information about this exciting event can be found at <a href="http://www.procurementforhousing.co.uk/pfhlive" target="_blank">http://www.procurementforhousing.co.uk/pfhlive</a></p>', '2012-06-07', 'PFH-Live-RGB.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 27294, '2012-06-07 15:22:28', 'PfH Live Logo', '2012-06-07 15:22:29', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'visit-us-at-pfh-live-2012'),
(89, 'Arena Group Junior and Mini Run For All makes a splash in Hull', 'Despite the rain hundreds of children still ventured into Hull city center to do their bit for charity.', '<p>We were proud to join staff and volunteers supporting Jane Tomlinson''s For All Events team in Hull city center earlier this month.</p>\r\n<p>Despite&nbsp;persistent rain, hundreds of children aged from&nbsp;9&nbsp;to 14 years came together to run upto&nbsp; 2.5km for charity. Several staff from Arena attended the event to help out with marshaling and greeting children on the finish line. Our Marketing Executive, Lisa Butterworth, was proud to help start the race and award prizes to winning schools and runners at the end of the race.</p>\r\n<p>Thanks to funding from Arena,&nbsp;the Junior and Mini Run For All&nbsp;has become the region&rsquo;s biggest free mass participation event for children.</p>\r\n<p>Congratulations to the winners of the schools challenge, 14-year-olds Charlie Stead and Lauren Jones were the fastest boy and girl in the 2.5K junior run. St. Mary&rsquo;s Sports College was crowned Secondary School champions while the winning Primary School was Spring Cottage.</p>', '2012-06-04', 'HUKW20120117A-017_C.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 134500, '2012-06-11 14:01:55', '', '2012-06-11 14:02:00', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arena-group-junior-and-mini-run-for-all-makes-a-splash-in-hull'),
(90, 'Three cheers for Royds School!', 'We visited Royds School in Oulton last week, to congratulate them on their win at the Leeds Arena Group Junior and Mini Run For All. ', '<p class="introduction">We visited Royds School in Oulton last week, to congratulate their running team&nbsp;on&nbsp;winning the Leeds Arena Group Junior and Mini Run For All.</p>\r\n<p>Mike Tomlinson was with us, to give thanks to the young participants for their fundraising efforts.</p>\r\n<p>Our Marketing Executive, Lisa Butterworth, joined the celebration to present certificates to the team of runners, and a trophy and video camera to the school.</p>\r\n<p>Pictured: event mascot Tommo the Tourtoise,&nbsp;Lisa Butterworth, Mike Tomlinson and&nbsp;Royds pupils, Josh Brown [14] and William Collumb [13] -&nbsp;the two fastest boys&nbsp;and Jasmine Laidler [14]&nbsp;- the fastest girl.</p>\r\n<p>Check out the video produced by Run for All at <a href="http://bit.ly/JFv0NU" target="_blank">http://bit.ly/JFv0NU</a>.</p>', '2012-06-18', 'Royds School Presentation.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 130727, '2012-06-18 07:51:12', 'Royds Run For All Winners', '2012-06-18 07:51:22', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'three-cheers-for-royds-school'),
(91, 'Arena gets quizzy with Ikano Financial Services', 'Arena has donated a prize in support of Ikano Financial Services'' annual staff quiz event which, this year will raise funds for their chosen local charity, Rainbows Children''s Hospice.', '<p class="introduction">Arena has donated a prize in support of Ikano Financial Services'' annual staff quiz event which, this year will raise funds for their chosen local charity, <a href="http://www.rainbows.co.uk" target="_blank">Rainbows Children''s Hospice</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Vendor Manager, Sharne Brown, tells us; "This will be the third year that Ikano has hosted the event with each year proving to be more successful than the last! Last year we raised in excess of &pound;900 on the evening &ndash; most of that contribution was made up by the raffle and all money raised was by Ikano employees. We&rsquo;re hoping to raise even more this year and it&rsquo;s with the fantastic support from supplier&rsquo;s like Arena that make this possible."</p>', '2012-06-25', 'rainbows-logo-trans.png', 'image/x-png', 37871, '2012-06-25 12:38:08', 'Rainbows Childrens Hospice', '2012-06-25 12:38:09', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arena-gets-quizzy-with-ikano-financial-services'),
(92, 'Congratulations delivered in Hull', 'On Friday we visited two schools in Hull to congratulate them on winning the Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Run Schools Challenge Races.', '<p class="introduction">On Friday we visited two schools in Hull to congratulate them on winning the Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Run Schools Challenge. <strong>Spring Cottage Primary School </strong>and <strong>St Mary&rsquo;s Sports College </strong>were the overall winners of the event.</p>\r\n<p>St Mary&rsquo;s pupils, Robbie Croll, 12, Samuel Longlands, 12, and Sean O&rsquo;Brien, 13, were announced as the fastest runners from the college, qualifying it to be crowned the fastest secondary school. Twelve-year olds Alicia Pochin and Amy Greenacre were also awarded for being the two fastest girls.</p>\r\n<p>Hollie Verity, Isabelle Klein and Hollie Klein were presented with their awards for qualifying Spring Cottage as the overall Primary School winner.</p>\r\n<p>Lisa Butterworth, Marketing Executive of Arena Group, said: &ldquo;It has been an absolute pleasure to be involved with the Arena Mini and Junior Fun Run again this year.&nbsp; The turnout was great considering the horrible weather on the day and we are pleased that our sponsorship made it possible for all the children to have free entries.&nbsp;I am delighted to be able to recognise the achievements of the two schools and present them with their certificates and trophies.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Each school also received a special prize of a video camera from Arena Group for winning the challenge.</p>', '2012-07-02', 'run_hull_0061_SDP1547-1258.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 105581, '2012-07-03 09:02:44', 'Hull Run For All', '2012-07-03 09:02:45', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'congratulations-delivered-in-hull'),
(93, 'Arena Wins Top Spot On National Framework', 'Arena is celebrating this month, having achieved the kudos of being accredited as number 1 supplier to UK housing associations through a prestigious national framework after winning a place as the recommended supplier with the National Procurement for Housing Consortium (PfH), opening up new sales channels worth well over £1million.', '<p class="introduction">The 4 year contract saw Arena&nbsp;beat a number of competitors nationwide, placing&nbsp;us as PfH&rsquo;s number one supplier for the provision of Photocopiers, Printers, Multi-Functional Devices (MFDs) and Office Based Managed Print Services (MPS).</p>\r\n<p>PfH specialize in improving procurement practice for over 800 social housing providers throughout the UK. The national procurement consortium dedicated to the social housing sector, appointed Arena as their number one supplier after Arena scored the highest marks in the tender exercise. This sees&nbsp;us well placed to support clients on <a href="http://www.procurementforhousing.co.uk" target="_blank">PfH</a>&rsquo;s portfolio.</p>\r\n<p>Making use of technological advancements, Arena works to help clients be more efficient, cost effective and environmentally friendly. As a company we also commit heavily to sustainable business practices and CSR.</p>\r\n<p>Wendy Griffiths, Category Manager from PfH said: &ldquo;Arena impressed us very much with their tender submission. They answered questions to a very high standard and gave an excellent reflection of the company and its capabilities. I am looking forward to working with Arena and have every confidence they will provide an excellent service to PfH Members&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Steve Hobson, Arena&rsquo;s Managed Services Sales Manager said:&rdquo; We are delighted to be appointed as the Number 1 supplier to the Procurement for Housing (PfH) framework and we look forward to working with all members to reduce operational costs by providing the most cost effective print, copy, fax and scan solutions in what we recognise are testing economic times for the UK housing sector. We are confident that we can make a real difference in this area&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.procurementforhousing.co.uk/home" target="_blank">PfH website - www.procurementforhousing.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../web/contact_us">Contact us </a>to find out about how you could work with Arena and the PfH framework.</p>', '2013-01-14', 'arena_photo_shoot_09.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 435815, '2012-07-17 11:42:33', 'Steve PfH Photo', '2012-07-17 11:42:34', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'arena-wins-top-spot-on-national-framework'),
(94, 'Pushing The Envelope with Leeds Building Society ', 'Leeds Building Society handles thousands of incoming documents each day; the latest mailroom technology keeps them at the leading edge of customer service efficiency.', '<p class="introduction">Leeds Building Society is the UK&rsquo;s 5th largest building society with assets of &pound;9.9 billion, almost 700,000 members and 65 branches in the UK. The Society is always looking to enhance its procedures and systems and over recent years Arena&rsquo;s mstore, software for electronic document management, has provided tangibly successful results to help it match that ethos.</p>\r\n<p>Tim Lancelot, Software Solutions Manager, sets the scene regarding Arena&rsquo;s longstanding partnership with the Society: &ldquo;We have worked with Leeds Building Society since 2004, delivering projects in support of the in-house IT team. Our aims have always been to improve customer service, control information, reduce costs and ease compliance. Initially we focused on the mortgage application process, automating it to increase efficiency.</p>\r\n<p>Arena recently deployed the society&rsquo;s second generation digital mailroom solution. This brings scanning hardware from OPEX together with Arena&rsquo;s <strong>m</strong>store software to enable fast and accurate processing of incoming mail. Tim says; &ldquo;We wanted to provide the fastest possible mail bag to desk process through automating as much of the process as possible.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Integration of the system with the society&rsquo;s core database systems is a central part of the mailroom identification and routing system. Incoming mail is scanned directly into <strong>m</strong>store and attached to existing related data for quick reference on-screen by customer service operatives. &ldquo;This places accurate information at the fingertips of staff responding to customer queries much earlier than was previously possible. LBS have the peace of mind of knowing that all documents are securely stored and can be activity audited as required by FSA guidelines. It is this commitment to leading edge efficiency solutions which has helped The Leeds to maintain an enviable asset to cost ratio within their sector.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Tangible Results</h2>\r\n<p><br />Paul Thompson, Document Services Manager at LBS (pictured)&nbsp;is delighted with the system; &ldquo;We set a three phase plan to test and run the overall electronic capture process and we can already see tangible and significant results of major impact. We have uploaded some 75% of legacy files whilst streamlining the intake of new material which amounts to approximately 5000 units per day. This has been done with minimal prep time and saving the physical transport and damage aspects of hard copies.</p>\r\n<p>"It is truly fantastic technology with very few issues matched by easy operation and maintenance. I especially like the ability of the system to recognise document types and given that we have something like 700 different types, the potential for fast and smooth processing is enormous. I am confident we will achieve an 18 month return on investment, which represents an outstanding success in truly moving the envelope you might say!&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management"> </a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">mstore - software for electronic document managment</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management"> </a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2012-07-01', 'Leeds Bldg Soc 1.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 127379, '2012-07-18 14:49:18', 'Paul Thompson', '2012-07-18 14:49:19', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'pushing-the-envelope-with-leeds-building-society'),
(95, 'Join us for our Spring Open Day', 'We are preparing to open our Wakefield showroom and head office, Armitage House, to visitors on Thursday April 23rd. Guests will be in with a chance of winning a prize in our exclusive draw, hearing and seeing the latest technology in document management and grabbing a bite to eat with our team. Who''d miss it?\r\n', '<p class="introduction">Arena invites you to join us in our showroom at<strong> Armitage House on&nbsp;Thursday April 23rd</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong>. Guests will get a chance to enter our prize draw and hear about the latest document management technology.</p>\r\n<p>We will be offering tours of our facilities, including our newly relcoated electronic document management team in Armitage House and our showroom where we''ll be demonstrating; <strong><em>&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\r\n<h2><strong><em>&nbsp;</em></strong><span class="font_blue">How to erase your printed page and use it again:</span></h2>\r\n<p>Imagine being able to reduce paper consumption by re-using pages over and over. <a href="../../../articles/160">Eco-MFP</a> is a revolutionary new device &ndash; the first of its kind that prints with erasable toner!</p>\r\n<h2 class="font_blue">How to print from mobile devices whilst controlling output:</h2>\r\n<p>See how to print documents wirelessly from android tablets and phones, or Apple iOS devices such as the iPad and iPhone. We will also show you how to control output volumes, set print defaults and monitor activity to manage the related costs.</p>\r\n<p>Want to read more about this? <a href="../../../articles/106" target="_blank">Get our Professional Services Manager''s take on BYOD</a>.</p>\r\n<h2 class="font_blue">How you could save 30% on print and copy:</h2>\r\n<p>See how our print audit process can reveal areas for cost saving, efficiency building and productivity growth. Watch a typical managed print system in action and hear about our clients who are already benefiting.</p>\r\n<h2 class="font_blue">How to reduce your reliance on paper and work smarter:</h2>\r\n<p>How combining paper with electronic document management can transform your organisation and save you thousands. See our <strong>m</strong>store software which is already proving invaluable to many businesses for managing archiving and processes such as accounts payable.</p>\r\n<p><strong>m</strong>store for Education will also be on show &ndash; already proving invaluable to many schools for complying with BS10008, the Freedom of Information Act and rules surrounding document retention, safeguarding and security.</p>\r\n<p>Our brand new mstore package, <strong>m</strong>store for Purchasing, will also be showcasing at this event. Take an opportunity to find out how to securely digitise, streamline, track and audit your purchasing processes.</p>\r\n<h2 class="font_blue">How to control print and copy output, shrink your carbon footprint and reach your sustainability goals:</h2>\r\n<p>See how you can monitor and control print and copy output, allocate cost centres and report on user activity. Check out the latest super-clean, carbon neutral devices in our show room.</p>\r\n<p>Download: <a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/118_Flyer_April15.pdf" target="_blank">our Open Day Flyer</a></p>\r\n<h1>Exclusive Prize Draw</h1>\r\n<p>To enter simply book an open day appointment, and sign in on arrival.*</p>\r\n<h1><br />Book your place:</h1>\r\n<p>To ensure we maintain our high service levels on what is expected to be a busy event, we are asking guests to pre-book appointments.</p>\r\n<p>Please speak to your Arena account manager, RSVP via phone: <strong>0844 863 8000</strong> or email <a href="mailto:marketing@arenagroup.net">marketing@arenagroup.net</a> to book your visit.</p>\r\n<h2>Venue:</h2>\r\n<p>Armitage House, Thorpe Lower Lane, Robin Hood, Wakefield, WF3 3BQ. <a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/102_Directions_To_Arena_Armitage_House2013.pdf" target="_blank">Map.</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h4 style="text-align: left;"><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/38_Competition Terms and Conditions Arena Group.pdf" target="_blank">*Terms and conditions apply.</a></h4>', '2015-02-06', '157_open.png', 'image/png', 64938, '2013-01-16 11:07:04', 'Open Day', '2012-07-18 14:55:03', '2015-02-20 08:34:41', 3, 7, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'join-us-for-our-spring-open-day'),
(96, 'Delivering Peace of Mind to Go Outdoors', 'National retailer, Go Outdoors, wanted to improve the security of its business critical documents and protect them from damage in the event of a crisis like a fire or flood. Scanning Bureau Services provided a reliable answer.', '<p class="introduction">GO Outdoors was founded in 1969 as Sheffield''s ''Camping and Caravanning Centre''. The retailer has since expanded, opening stores across the UK, earning a strong reputation for excellent customer service and becoming a landmark within the nation&rsquo;s outdoor community.</p>\r\n<p>[Name], [job title here], explains his decision to appoint Arena&rsquo;s Bureau Services; &ldquo;Security is important to us so we needed peace of mind from a supplier we could trust. Arena has handled thousands of our business critical documents with care, checking each one in and efficiently scanning and indexing them before securely shredding and disposing of the paperwork. Every document is accounted for.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Previously our paper documents we''re stored on our site or in external facilities at cost. We wanted to improve security and protect our records from any crisis like a fire or flood. Digitising our files covers these key concerns and makes them easier to find and reference. We have also recovered space on-site and made financial savings on external storage.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Arena visited us and understood our needs straight away. They proposed a good solution and were flexible about collecting and digitally indexing our files in a way that suited us. The scanning bureau service has been secure, reliable and efficient - we would certainly recommend Arena to other businesses.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><br /><a href="../../page/edm-for-storing-protecting-and-retrieving-critical-documents">Arena&rsquo;s Scanning Bureau Services</a></p>', '2012-07-25', 'harlow_01.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 147781, '2012-07-18 14:59:58', '', '2012-07-18 14:58:49', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'delivering-peace-of-mind-to-go-outdoors'),
(97, 'What will you do when the worst happens?', 'Arena’s Operations Manager, Neil Maude, has been musing on crisis recovery of late, following recent news on banking failures and widespread UK floods. Here he provides his thoughts on how businesses can prepare for the failure of key suppliers and infrastructure.', '<p class="introduction">Arena&rsquo;s Operations Manager, Neil Maude, has been musing on crisis  recovery of late, following news of banking failures and  widespread UK floods. Here he provides his thoughts on how businesses  can prepare for the failure of key suppliers and infrastructure.</p>\r\n<h2>Background</h2>\r\n<p>In early 2012, Natwest, Royal Bank of Scotland and Ulster bank suffered a major crisis in the form of a technical crash that brought down cash machines across the country and prevented customers from accessing their accounts. Investec Securities banks analyst Ian Gordon estimated the final cost to the bank could be as much as &pound;100million, adding; &ldquo;This is one of the most widespread customer service &shy;failures we have had in recent memory.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>What&rsquo;s the worst that could happen?</h2>\r\n<p>Not all businesses are so reliant on IT and many could continue without some part of their systems.&nbsp; But technology is there for a reason &ndash; efficiency, customer service etc &ndash; and in today&rsquo;s &ldquo;hypercompetitive&rdquo; marketplace it&rsquo;s a sure thing that if you don&rsquo;t look after your customers really well, then there&rsquo;s someone else ready to take that business.&nbsp; So it&rsquo;s a wise move to make sure that you have disaster recovery plans in place and consider what you&rsquo;re going to do when a key system fails. <br /><br />Further, we&rsquo;re now all working in an increasingly interconnected world, whether we like it or not.&nbsp; This brings a reliance on systems that are outside our control.&nbsp; The failure of NatWest systems doesn&rsquo;t just affect their customers &ndash; it affects who those customers trade with at other banks. <br /><br />Outside of the obvious payments issue, interconnectedness of systems is something to think about in terms of the resilience of your business.&nbsp; If some other part of your environment fails or is unavailable; e.g. power, phones and travel infrastructure &ndash; then what impact does this have?&nbsp; It&rsquo;s really worth considering these wider aspects of disaster recovery.</p>\r\n<h2>What to do when life gives you lemons &ndash; A simple 5 Step Business Continuity Plan</h2>\r\n<p><br />The examples above cover a wide range of woes which might affect a business &ndash; human errors, system failures, natural disasters and so on. Clearly, not all risks can be mitigated at a practical cost &ndash; some are acknowledged and accepted. However, you can do a great deal to plan ahead.&nbsp; The following are some simple steps that any business can take to cover the basics.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; 1.&nbsp; <span class="font_blue">Nominate a senior manager to take ownership of business continuity and disaster planning.</span>&nbsp; This is not so you can point a finger at someone if it goes wrong &ndash; it&rsquo;s to make sure that the responsibility is clearly defined and that the issue has senior sponsorship</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; 2.&nbsp; <span class="font_blue">Conduct a risk analysis</span> to look at the following things. Determine which are critical and which you can live without:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<h3>Systems:&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p>What IT do you have in place and what would you do without it?</p>\r\n<h3>People:&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p>Who are your key employees and for each, what would you do if that person didn&rsquo;t arrive for work tomorrow?</p>\r\n<h3>Processes:&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<p>For each critical process undertaken by each business unit, where does it &lsquo;touch&rsquo; other organisations and what will you do if failure strikes?</p>\r\n<h3>Physical assets:</h3>\r\n<p>How would you cope without a particular building, piece of machinery, stock of paper records or other asset if you suffered a fire or flood, for example?</p>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp; 3.&nbsp; <span class="font_blue">Using the results of this analysis, write a disaster recovery plan</span> and publish it to the people who are likely to need it &ndash; the line managers in charge of each element.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; 4.&nbsp; <span class="font_blue">Consider your PR response to a public crisis</span>, what you will tell the media if they come knocking, who will be your spokesperson and do they need some specialist training?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp; 5.&nbsp; <span class="font_blue">Test your plan</span> &ndash; at least once annually and whenever there is a sufficiently large change in the business to warrant a review.<br /><br />Whilst the pervasive nature of IT brings with it a whole range of issues when it doesn&rsquo;t work, technology also brings the tools to work around many problems.&nbsp; Data can be secured for guaranteed availability even if a primary location is damaged, and remote working can address access issues or bad weather, whilst robust processes should mitigate the risk of human error.</p>\r\n<h2>Where did Stephen Hester go wrong?</h2>\r\n<p>The worst still can happen and it&rsquo;s inconceivable that a bank regulated by the FSA, such as NatWest, won&rsquo;t have considered the points above and many more besides (given that they&rsquo;ve been able to open their branches on a Sunday to recover, I expect that they are already going through their prepared plans).&nbsp; To me, this just highlights the need for business continuity planning. <br /><br />This time it&rsquo;s Stephen Hester who&rsquo;s on the end of an unlucky break - next time it could be your business. Would you be ready to cope?</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of   experience in the electronic document management industry, working with   both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board  of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM  business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing  solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support  services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Related Features</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/163">Confidential files left on trains, in the wrong hands, on the move?</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank"><strong>m</strong>store, software for document management</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../case_studies?service=Electronic+Document+Management" target="_blank">Case studies: <strong>m</strong>store in practice</a></p>', '2012-07-02', 'Flood_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 107622, '2014-12-11 15:42:35', '', '2012-07-19 10:27:32', '2014-12-11 15:42:35', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'what-will-you-do-when-the-worst-happens'),
(98, 'The Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Run Series reaches a winning finale in York', 'The streets of York were lined with over 6,000 runners for the Jane Tomlinson 10k earlier this month. Hundreds of children joined the fun, taking part in the final event of Yorkshire''s largest, free of charge, charity sports event for children. ', '<p class="introduction">The streets of York were lined with over 6,000 runners for the Jane Tomlinson 10k earlier this month. Hundreds of children joined the fun, taking part in the final event of Yorkshire''s largest, free of charge, charity sports event for children.</p>\r\n<p>Now in its 3rd year, the York Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Run saw youngsters, aged from 3 to 14, run, jog and walk upto 2.5km around the historic city to complete the charity challenge. The event marked the perfect end to the series and proved a great way to mark the city&rsquo;s 800th Royal Charter anniversary celebrations. Staff from Arena attended the event to help out with marshaling and greeting children on the finish line. <br /><br />Awards were presented to the three fastest male and female junior runners in the 2.5km race by Arena Group''s Managing Director, Adrian Fitzpatrick, who commented; <em><span class="font_blue">&ldquo;We are proud of our association with For All Events and the Jane Tomlinson Appeal, and we are delighted to be supporting Mike and the team in York again this year.&rdquo;</span></em><br /><br /><em class="font_blue">&ldquo;Mike Tomlinson has created a lasting legacy to his wife Jane with these runs for the whole family. Being part of the team is a natural fit for Arena as we work with a number of York schools and we believe that a focus on supporting and encouraging young people within our local communities is important - the Run For All is a great platform for this.&rdquo;</em><br /><br />This year almost 20,000 people have taken part in the Run For All 10k and Junior/Mini series in Hull, Leeds and York with over 50 different charities both nationally and locally benefitting from those taking part.<br /><br />Teams of business professionals, including runners from Arena, were amongst those taking part in the Morrison Utility Services York 10K Corporate Challenge alongside other local firms.<br /><br />Jane Tomlinson&rsquo;s York 10K is a not-for-profit event. The partner charities this year were: Jane&rsquo;s Appeal, the charity set up by Jane Tomlinson; Martin House Children&rsquo;s Hospice, Yorkshire&rsquo;s hospice for children and young people based near Wetherby; Macmillan Cancer Support; Bone Cancer Research Trust and St. Leonard&rsquo;s Hospice.</p>', '2012-08-13', 'York_Juniors_2012.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 111456, '2012-08-13 09:31:17', 'York Junior Run 2012', '2012-08-13 09:31:18', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'the-arena-group-junior-and-mini-fun-run-series-reaches-a-winning-finale-in-york'),
(99, 'Arena''s volunteers have been busy at Herd Farm', 'Arena Group has been helping out with maintenance at a local activity centre over the past few weeks as part of its CSR program which is run to support charity and community projects.', '<p class="introduction">Herd Farm Activity Centre is a residential education and activity facility in North  Leeds. It&rsquo;s a fantastic place providing great opportunities for young  people between the ages of 11 and 18. It also caters for adults,  particularly corporate groups, who bolster its funds by paying to use its facilities which can cater for a broad range of outdoor activities and indoor training.</p>\r\n<p>As with many places like this, money is in short supply and buying in  labour to complete some of the jobs that need doing at the centre is a  costly business. This is where Arena Group''s CSR days have proven helpful.</p>\r\n<p>Many areas of the farm, such as fences and paths, need regular  maintenance and the cost of outsourching labour to cary out this work is prohibitive. Help from local businesses is vital to  the continued running of the activity centre, which provides a valuable  resource for nurturing families and vulnerable people in the community,  including those with special needs and disabilities.</p>\r\n<p>Arena has sent groups of volunteers to help out for 3 days this month.  There are a variety of jobs going on including painting, fence  building, path clearing and laying down gravel. Last week''s  group did some very fine (but tough) work - digging a trench that will  be used to lay foundations for a fence to keep rabbits at bay.</p>\r\n<p>Arena''s Managing Director, Adrian Fitzpatrick, comments; "Contributing towards the wellbeing of our local community has always been important to Arena and for this reason we encourage our employees to take two annual days out to volunteer in support of local charity and community projects. Many of these help children and vulnerable groups and so Herd Farm is an ideal candidate."</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p>More about Herd Farm: <a href="http://www.herdfarm.co.uk/index.html" target="_blank">www.herdfarm.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/arena-in-the-community" target="_blank">Our CSR photo gallery</a></p>', '2012-08-23', '1_Welcome Volunteers 2.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 140002, '2012-08-23 14:08:50', 'Herd Farm CSR', '2012-08-23 14:08:51', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arenas-volunteers-have-been-busy-at-herd-farm'),
(100, 'Special Offer: Discounted Scanners for Education Clients', 'mstore for Education integrates with your existing scanner devices but some documents, such as HR and student records, are sufficiently confidential to require a dedicated\r\nscanner on the desk of an authorised staff member.\r\n\r\nUntil 28th September 2012 we''re offering Kodak scanners at special discounted prices - exclusively for education sector clients.\r\n', '<p class="introduction"><strong>m</strong>store for Education integrates with your existing scanner devices but some documents, such as HR and student records, are sufficiently confidential to require a dedicated scanner on the desk of an authorised staff member.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Scan sensitive documents into mstore without using a shared device in a busy office.</li>\r\n<li>Remove the risk of accidentally leaving originals on a shared device.</li>\r\n<li>Reduce the risk of accidentally exposing confidential information.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Special offer on selected Kodak devices*</h2>\r\n<p>In response to feedback from our <strong>m</strong>store customers and, to welcome you back to the new school year, we are pleased to offer the following discounted pricing on selected Kodak scanners - for a limited period only.</p>\r\n<h3>&bull; Kodak i1120 &ndash; &pound;280+VAT</h3>\r\n<p>A4, colour, duplex (double sided) scanning, 20 pages per minute, 50 page feeder.</p>\r\n<h3>&bull; Kodak i2400 &ndash; &pound;425+VAT</h3>\r\n<p>A4, colour, duplex (double sided) scanning, 30 pages per minute, 50 page feeder.</p>\r\n<p>Both scanners are ideal desktop companions for secure processing of confidential documents. Scanner installation is a straightforward process and can be undertaken by your IT manager. Alternatively, an Arena Group engineer can install your scanner during the annual visit included in your <strong>m</strong>store maintenance contract.</p>\r\n<h2>How to take advantage of this offer</h2>\r\n<p>Please contact us on 0844 863 8000 or email kodak@arenagroup.net quoting <strong class="font_blue">KODAK</strong>.<br /><br />*Pricing is valid for orders placed by educational organisations on or before Friday September 28th 2012.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../assets/stored_documents/original/39_Arena Kodak leafletA-W.pdf" target="_blank">Download a flyer</a></p>', '2012-09-03', 'website_picture.png', 'image/png', 150327, '2012-09-08 10:03:26', 'KODAK', '2012-09-08 09:57:40', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'special-offer-discounted-scanners-for-education-clients'),
(101, 'Join Arena at The Academies Show', 'Visit us at stand number 119 on November 28th, take our ''Golden File Challenge'' and meet our team!\r\n \r\n\r\n', '<p class="introduction">Visit us on November 28th at <strong>stand number 119</strong>. We will be showcasing our full portfolio of products and services, including technologies to help you implement:</p>\r\n<p>&bull; Safeguarding of information <br />&bull; Record keeping best practice<br />&bull; Liberated storage space<br />&bull; Print control</p>\r\n<p>Transitioning to academy status presents new challenges, in particular relating to document management. Further, increasingly rigorous regulation surrounding record governance creates new responsibilities for legal compliance.</p>\r\n<p>Arena has over 20 years of experience working with over 1,000 education sector clients. Our expertise is already helping academies nationwide to overcome these unique issues, making the transition simple and straightforward.</p>\r\n<p>The event will provide prospective and new academies with a wealth of relevant, valuable insights, discussions and practical advice.</p>\r\n<h2>Come and find us at stand number 119</h2>\r\n<p><span class="font_blue">Take our Golden File Challenge!</span><img src="../../../assets/articles/101/contained_images/ce9fdb365d51_168_top pnl.jpg?1349884579" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="150" align="right" /></p>\r\n<p>A chance to scoop a bottle of champagne!</p>\r\n<h2>We&rsquo;ll look forward to seeing you!</h2>\r\n<p>November 28th 2012, Birmingham NEC</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.academiesshowbirmingham.co.uk/" target="_blank">Secure your place - it''s free to attend!</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h6><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/40_Competition Terms and Conditions Arena Group.pdf" target="_blank">Competition terms</a></h6>', '2012-10-01', '169_WEBSITE_News.png', 'image/png', 270273, '2012-10-10 16:13:31', 'Academies Show', '2012-09-21 13:06:50', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 5, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'join-arena-at-the-academies-show'),
(105, 'Happy 21st Birthday Arena', 'Arena Group turned 21 in September and our Managing Director, Adrian Fitzpatrick, wanted to go right back to our roots to celebrate and reminisce 21 years of success. \r\n', '<p><span class="introduction">Arena Group turned 21 in September and our Managing Director, Adrian Fitzpatrick, wanted to go right back to our roots to celebrate and reminisce 21 years of success. </span></p>\r\n<p>"Having started out in 1991 we could not possibly have made our voyage to date without the help of literally hundreds of people &ndash; founder partners, colleagues, customers, suppliers, advisors, friends and family. As is often the way, it takes a special occasion to make you reflect, count your blessings and recognise the massive debt of gratitude you owe to so many for what they have all done to make Arena everything it is today."</p>\r\n<p>In light of that, we thought it would be fitting to go right back to our first ever customer; All Saints Primary School in Bradford. Adrian went back to celebrate and give thanks to Office Manager Margaret Heaton and former Head Teacher Audrey Barr and also to meet Sue Hart, the current Head Teacher.</p>\r\n<p>Margaret told us: &ldquo;We first had contact with Adrian (Arena''s MD) when he made a cold call to our school 21 years ago. It was great to see someone really passionate about their business and for doing things differently to the norm in their industry. &nbsp;We liked their &lsquo;style&rsquo; &ndash; small company, just starting out, not pushy, good product knowledge, so we signed up.&nbsp;As it happens, we were right and we still work with them to this day. I know we are not the only client that Arena has maintained since their early days, but it does feel special to be the first!</p>\r\n<p>Even though the company is much, much bigger today, their style still remains the same and we like that. I think that''s why they have continued to grow and enjoy great success. &nbsp;When we have any problems with machines, the service is prompt (usually same day which is very important in a school) with the engineers being efficient, knowledgeable, friendly and in most cases, correcting the problem without having to return another day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>John, our sales contact, doesn&rsquo;t hassle us to change our machines &ndash; seemingly knowing when it is time for that to happen. &nbsp;Finally, the accounts system works very well, the invoicing being clear and user friendly. &nbsp;They make our lives easier in so many different ways and this is what really stands out for us. We have always recommended Arena and will continue to do so.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Adrian thoroughly enjoyed reminiscing,&nbsp;Margaret&rsquo;s kind words of praise and the fact that the school remains a loyal customer to&nbsp;this day - it really&nbsp;is testament to Arena&rsquo;s hard work.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Thanks to everyone for choosing us to be your document expert for 21 years!</strong></p>\r\n<h3><em>Adults (left-right): </em>John Wall (current Arena Account Manager), Margaret Heaton (Office Manager), Sue Hart (current Head Teacher), Audrey Barr (former Head Teacher) and Adrian Fitzpatrick (Arena&rsquo;s Managing Director). <em>Children (left-right): </em>Estera Botosova, Harry McKenny-Cowley, Nefertiti Black and Khadija Khan.</h3>', '2012-10-18', 'ASPB Web.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 203865, '2012-10-18 08:34:33', '', '2012-10-18 08:32:01', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 5, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'happy-21st-birthday-arena'),
(106, 'Managing the ‘Bring your Own Device’ (BYOD) challenge', 'Use of mobile devices in the workplace is on the increase, offering countless business benefits from improved efficiency to a fully provisioned mobile workforce. However, it also presents new challenges in taking care of your business critical documents, data, IT network and print output.', '<p class="introduction">Use of mobile devices in the workplace is on the increase, offering countless business benefits from improved efficiency to a fully provisioned mobile workforce. However, it presents challenges in taking care of your business critical documents, data, IT network and print output. Our Professional Services Manager, <strong>Ian Fox</strong>, gives us his insight.</p>\r\n<p>Mobile technology is advancing at lightning speed and the majority of people can now get their hands on a shiny new gadget at relatively low cost. Likewise, many businesses are investing in mobile devices for their employees to reduce their need to print whilst boosting productivity - providing tools to engage whenever, wherever. However, some new challenges are presented when it comes to managing business critical documents and data that are accessed or created on the move.</p>\r\n<p>So, how will you support workforce desire to use personal apps and devices while allowing them to be productive in a secure environment that protects your data? Here&rsquo;s my whistle-stop tour of tips for building your BYOD strategy.</p>\r\n<h2>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How do we monitor BYOD on our network?</h2>\r\n<h5 class="indented"><span class="font_blue">37% of information workers are using technology before seeking formal permission</span> <sub><em>(Source: Forrester)</em></sub></h5>\r\n<p>You might have a policy that requires your employees to ask for permission before plugging any old device into your network but let&rsquo;s face it, they&rsquo;re doing it anyway. The better approach is to accept this and put technology in place to let you see exactly what&rsquo;s going on. Various software packages are available that can detect mobile access to your network and there is often a lot more going on than you would imagine. Dave Helm, Sales Director of <a href="http://www.bluelogic.co.uk/" target="_blank">Blue Logic</a>, agrees; &ldquo;With the right technology in place, no devices will sync with your systems without your IT department knowing about it. Just ensure you let your employees know that Big Brother is watching them!&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How do we print from our mobile devices?</h2>\r\n<p>Are your employees creating documents on the move but then getting frustrated when they can&rsquo;t print them? Sometimes we just need ink on paper and you could be seeing some fairly imaginative workarounds including people putting their iPads on the photocopier glass to try and get a snapshot of the screen (just in case you were wondering, that doesn&rsquo;t work!) The most common thing we see is emailing of documents to network accessible inboxes where they can be printed to networked machines. This is time consuming and can be overcome using new technology. (<a href="../../../articles/mobile-printing-made-easier?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">Check out our related article on mobile printing</a>.)</p>\r\n<h2>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Can we control print output from mobile devices?</h2>\r\n<p>The next natural question! Enabling printing on your network from mobile devices can create another problem in that you may find that you can&rsquo;t monitor and manage output volume, colour usage, paper consumption, specific user activity and so on, like you can on your networked machines. Print control software can be configured to help you with this, controlling and reporting on activity from iOS and other mobile gadgets in just the same way as on your networked machines.</p>\r\n<h2>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Can we manage data security on remote devices?</h2>\r\n<p>You may be concerned about employees accessing your business systems and data remotely, or even losing devices outside of the office. We&rsquo;ve all read chilling news stories about laptops left on trains and accidents do happen.</p>\r\n<p>Tools such as remote desktops can safeguard your intellectual property by ensuring that data remains on your server. Dave Helm comments; "As the corporate database grows, security of that data becomes increasingly important. Using Windows remote desktop can secure any data from being downloaded to local devices".</p>\r\n<p>In addition to this, electronic document management software can help by retaining files in digital format on your servers whilst monitoring what&rsquo;s happening to them and controlling user access.</p>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s still important to have strong password policies to prevent unauthorized users accessing your data and there are systems available that can remotely wipe mobile devices if they do get lost.</p>\r\n<h2>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Finally &hellip; Don&rsquo;t just ignore it!</h2>\r\n<p>My final tip is to embrace BYOD because it&rsquo;s happening regardless of your ability to manage it and it could be costing your organisation in terms of finance and efficiency. If you face it head on, get your strategy and systems in order and keep things simple then you simply can&rsquo;t go wrong!</p>\r\n<h3>About Ian Fox</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/106/contained_images/7ebde81a6a76_276_Ian Fox Jan15 large.jpg?1422352750" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="144" height="144" align="LEFT" />Professional Services Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:ianF@arenagroup.net">ianF@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Ian Fox joined the Arena Group as a Systems Engineer in 1995. During his time at Arena he has gained a wealth of experience in helping organisations with their document related workflows. He now heads up the Professional Services department, which was formed in January 2011 with the aim of ensuring that existing and future Arena clients receive the best possible advice, solutions and support to enable them to manage and control their documents effectively.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="mailto:news@arenagroup.net">Contact us</a> to find out more about printing from mobile devices, monitoring and controlling print and copy output, digitising your paper-driven processes or implementing an electronic document management system.</p>\r\n<p>Visit us to see a demonstration of mobile printing and output control in action. <a href="../../../articles/95">Our next open day</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Related Articles</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/mobile-printing-made-easier?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">Mobile printing made easy</a></p>', '2014-09-10', 'BYOD_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 82519, '2014-12-11 15:20:54', '', '2012-11-21 16:05:39', '2015-02-06 16:33:16', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'managing-the-‘bring-your-own-device’-byod-challenge');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `headline`, `summary`, `main_content`, `date`, `image_file_name`, `image_content_type`, `image_file_size`, `image_updated_at`, `image_alt`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `created_by`, `updated_by`, `recycled`, `recycled_at`, `display`, `position`, `highlight`, `cached_slug`) VALUES
(107, 'Printer ink that is pricier than champagne? ', 'For many households and businesses, inkjet cartridges are considered a necessary expense but research by consumer organisation Which? has found that they can be pricier than Dom Perignon champagne. Arena’s Group Sales Manager, Gary Putson, provides advice on steps you can take to get best value.', '<p class="introduction">For many households and businesses, inkjet cartridges are considered a necessary expense but research by consumer organisation <em>Which?</em> has found that they can be pricier than Dom Perignon champagne. Arena&rsquo;s Group Sales Manager, <strong>Gary Putson</strong>, provides advice on steps you can take to get best value.</p>\r\n<p>A replacement cartridge for an average inkjet printer costs &pound;45, far less than a bottle of Dom Perrignon champagne but drop for drop the ink becomes far more expensive. Inkjet printers are usually fairly cheap to purchase but this is where their appeal ends. A recent <em>Which?</em> report details the findings of an investigation that tested five inkjet printers from manufacturers including HP, Epson, Canon and Brother.</p>\r\n<h2>Paying for ink that never hits paper</h2>\r\n<p>The study found huge differences in the cost of printing 50 pages in one go, compared with printing the same number of pages over eight weeks. This is due to automatic cleaning between print runs. <br /><br />The report from <em>Which?</em> notes: &ldquo;Inkjet printers seem to have a fascination with keeping themselves clean. Switch one on, or finish printing some documents, and often a printer will initiate a cleaning cycle. This involves spitting ink into an ink absorber with the aim of keeping the ink nozzles in tip-top condition.&rdquo; <br /><br />Manufacturers insist that this is essential to maintain print quality but arguably, the waste is good news for them, as they place sizable profit margins on replacement cartridges.</p>\r\n<h2>What is the answer for home inkjet users?</h2>\r\n<p>If you must choose an inkjet printer then the simple solution is to shop around for a less wasteful model that uses low cost ink. It&rsquo;s worth comparing retailers and considering un-branded cartridges to save the pennies. <em>Which?</em> Is a good source of reviews to help you check-up on value for money.</p>\r\n<h2>Is there an inkjet printer in your office?</h2>\r\n<p>Take a look around and it&rsquo;s likely that you will spot at least one. Despite the growing number of businesses taking up managed print services and working with specialist providers to reduce and control the related costs, it is not uncommon for us to see inkjet printers creeping back onto the scene. This often happens when a senior manager wants a printer close by, when a printer breaks down or when a machine is needed on the desk of an employee who prints sensitive documents.</p>\r\n<h2>Only need one printer?</h2>\r\n<p>Even if you are a small business owner, opting for an inkjet printer is a waste of good champagne. Explore your options with a reliable provider so that you can agree on costs up-front, including regular servicing for peace of mind that your machine will remain in perfect working order.</p>\r\n<h2>What is the option for bigger businesses?</h2>\r\n<p>Businesses with multiple devices can engage a provider to assess their print and copy infrastructure &ndash; audited free of charge without obligation. Request a solution to reduce your costs, building in technology to let you control output. Usually, you will receive brand new devices from a single manufacturer to simplify maintenance and keep things easy for your users and IT team. A <a href="../../../page/print---the-hidden-costs" target="_blank">managed print service (MPS)</a> will also feature automatic toner replenishment and service calls.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Interested in FREE champagne?</h1>\r\n<h2><span class="font_blue">A managed print service could save you up to 30% on your print and copy costs - enough to buy a monthly case of champagne and toast your economic prowess!</span></h2>\r\n<p><span class="font_blue"><br /></span></p>\r\n<h3>BUT ... A Managed <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Document</span> Service delivers more</h3>\r\n<p>We are very confident that you can make significant savings through implementing Arena''s managed print service but this is just the tip of the iceberg.</p>\r\n<p>Several research studies have confirmed that <span class="font_blue">organisations spend between 5 and 15% of their annual revenues on producing, sharing, distributing, processing, storing and retrieving business critical documents and information</span>. Arena has proved that more substantial savings can be made through addressing the way you work with documents as a whole instead of looking at print and copy in isolation. For this reason it''s advisable to engage a managed document service provider.</p>\r\n<h2>Beware of &lsquo;consolidators&rsquo;</h2>\r\n<p>Any provider who simply proposes reducing the number of devices on your premises by pushing all of your output through a small number of multi-functional devices should set your alarm bells ringing. <br /><br />Your budget may be a high priority but it will not be your only requirement. A good provider will consider many factors including the types of documents you print, the nature of your business, your likely maintenance requirements and how you use documents across the board before they make a recommendation. They will look to balance deployment of your print and copy volume across the most appropriate hardware infrastructure to suit your needs. This is sometimes achieved through strategically placed MFDs but often combines them with desktop devices, print room equipment and software to help you manage output.</p>\r\n<h3>About Gary Putson</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../..//assets/articles/107/contained_images/4c9a085c27a5_266_Gary Putson 0613.JPG?1404137254" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="108" height="148" align="LEFT" /></p>\r\n<p>Group Sales Director<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:garyP@arenagroup.net">garyP@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Gary has worked with Arena for 11 years and has a long background in sales, originating in the telecoms sector. Gary sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of directors and manages Arena&rsquo;s growing Sales team of over thirty account managers and telesellers. His team members spend their days consulting with businesses across the country to deliver cost reduction, efficiency savings and sustainability in all areas of document management.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="mailto:news@arenagroup.net">Contact us</a> for information about getting best value from the way you print and manage documents.</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.which.co.uk/technology/computing/guides/how-we-test-printers/" target="_blank">More about the <em>Which?</em> report</a></p>\r\n<h2>Related articles</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/133">The scandal of ever-shrinking inkjet cartridges</a></p>', '2012-10-15', 'Champagne_WS.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 110862, '2014-12-11 16:04:56', '', '2012-11-21 16:44:06', '2015-06-17 08:08:32', 3, 7, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'printer-ink-that-is-pricier-than-champagne'),
(108, 'Wrapping up for Christmas', 'Arena has teamed up with The Abundant Life Church in Bradford to help wrap Christmas presents for poverty-sticken families. ', '<p class="introduction">Arena has teamed up with The Abundant Life Church in Bradford to help wrap Chistmas presents for poverty-sticken families.</p>\r\n<p>Our client, The Abundant Life Church, has taken up THE BIG GIVE challenge, which aims to help alleviate the hardship of poverty-stricken families over Christmas time. Bradford has some of the worst child poverty problems in the UK and The Campaign to End Child Poverty reports that 75% of children living in the Bradford West constituency are living in, or close to, poverty. Many families that benefit from THE BIG GIVE are quite simply unable to afford gifts for their own children, Christmas decorations or Christmas dinner due to other more essential items that need to be paid for such as food and heating.</p>\r\n<p>Esther Nixon, Children''s Pastor at The Abundant Life Church explained; &ldquo;We need help to wrap several thousand Christmas presents of various shapes and sizes for children aged 0-11 living under the poverty line in Bradford. Brand new presents are chosen with care, considering the age of the child; with different gifts for boys and girls and each one is attractively wrapped.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Fifteen Arena volunteers were raring to get wrapping, Arena&rsquo;s Sam Taylor&nbsp;said; &ldquo;I think it&rsquo;s such a great cause, an opportunity to make families feel special and a chance to help put a smile on a child&rsquo;s face this Christmas - not to mention a fun day of festivity for us too!&rdquo; Esther praised Arena volunteers; &ldquo;We have never finished wrapping all of the gifts this early before and we honestly can&rsquo;t thank Arena enough for helping us.&rdquo;</p>', '2012-12-13', '11.jpg', 'image/pjpeg', 44820, '2012-12-18 13:47:17', '', '2012-12-17 11:57:50', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 5, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'wrapping-up-for-christmas'),
(109, 'Helping Holbeck Elderly Aid Celebrate Christmas', 'Christmas can be an especially lonely time for the elderly so our volunteers went out this week to help with Holbeck Elderly Aid’s Christmas Party. This was the 4th time we had attended the event in support of the charity, helping to set-up tables, serve food and drinks and sell raffle tickets. Our volunteers also had some fun playing games, joining in with a festive sing-along and chatting with the elderly guests. ', '<p class="introduction">Christmas can be an especially lonely time for the elderly so our volunteers went out this week to help with Holbeck Elderly Aid&rsquo;s Christmas Party. This was the 4<sup>th</sup> time we had attended the event in support of the charity, helping to set-up tables, serve food and drinks and sell raffle tickets. Our volunteers also had some fun playing games, joining in with a festive sing-along and chatting with the elderly guests.</p>\r\n<p>Arena&rsquo;s Dylan Hayes, commented; &ldquo;The event was both humbling and very satisfying - to feel you have made a difference and brightened the day of people who really don&rsquo;t have much to look forward to at this time of the year. Although the Arena employees all got stuck in and enjoyed helping out, I think we were all aware that what was just an afternoon out of the office for us might have been one of the high points of the Christmas season for some of the guests at the party. It made me feel very proud to be part of a company that does this!&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Holbeck Elderly Aid&rsquo;s Trustee, Ann Hepburn, tells us; &ldquo;Arena has been supporting our Christmas party for four years now and they are always a massive help. We couldn&rsquo;t pull off such a brilliant event without our volunteers and we are very grateful to them &ndash; we hope to see them again next year!&rdquo; Project Manager, Lesley Thornton, adds &ldquo;We are very much used to Arena coming and helping us out at our Christmas Party now, which is nice because they understand what we do; they put lots of effort into it and are very consistent... Thanks to everyone from Arena who helped make the party a success.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><strong>About Holbeck Elderly Aid:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Holbeck Elderly Aid provides a range of services to support and enhance the life of people aged 60 and over. The charity aims to make life easier for elderly people by helping them with difficulties, improving the environment in which they live and enabling them to live independently in the community if they wish to; relieving the isolation and loneliness experienced by many.&nbsp;</p>', '2012-12-18', 'PICT0026.JPG', 'image/pjpeg', 126329, '2012-12-18 16:56:18', '', '2012-12-18 13:39:58', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 5, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'helping-holbeck-elderly-aid-celebrate-christmas'),
(110, 'Questioning the Cost of Purchasing', 'Arena’s Neil Maude explains how to spot some commonly unrecognised and costly pitfalls in the way organisations source, purchase and pay for goods and services.', '<p><span class="introduction">Arena&rsquo;s Neil Maude explains how to spot some commonly unrecognised and costly pitfalls in the way organisations source, purchase and pay for goods and services.</span><br /><br />The tough economic climate has forced businesses of all sizes and types to identify savings. Sensible business leaders are taking a strategic approach, considering their processes and culture rather than implementing ad hoc cost-cutting campaigns that deliver little long term benefit to the bottom line.</p>\r\n<p>The process of sourcing, buying and paying for goods (commonly referred to as &lsquo;purchase-to-pay&rsquo; or &lsquo;P2P&rsquo;) is a good starting point. Often costly, onerous, paper-driven and lacking in transparency it can be difficult to control and use for informed decision making. Significant savings can often be made through combining a cost-conscious culture with an efficient P2P process that is supported by smart technology.</p>\r\n<p>Below I''ve explained a few warning signs that could reveal some, possibly unexpected, problems.</p>\r\n<h2>Authority</h2>\r\n<p>Reviewing and authorising expenditure before costs are committed is essential in making sure that money is not spent unnecessarily, incorrectly or even fraudulently. Whilst you do not want to burden your workforce with excessive controls over routine and low value purchasing, you do want to know that management has reviewed and approved high value items.</p>\r\n<h3>Tell-tale signs that your authorisation process is not robust enough:<br /><br /></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Invoices are received from suppliers without purchase order numbers or reference of authority</li>\r\n<li>Your finance team frequently needs to seek approval for items that are already purchased ("spent control")</li>\r\n<li>Managers are frequently surprised and unaware of items in the purchasing pipeline </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Conversely, beware of over-controlling your purchasing policy. Regulation is good but a straight jacket is bad!</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Transparency</h2>\r\n<p>Making sure that the right people have access to financial information is vital. Managers must be able to easily review committed costs to support budgeting, accountability and maintain healthy cashflow. This should not be restricted to last month&rsquo;s paid invoices but include pending (approved but not yet placed) and open purchase orders plus outstanding purchase requests. Providing your managers with a detailed picture helps them to make quick and informed financial decisions, keeps projects running to schedule and maintains productivity by placing data at their fingertips - giving you a real competitive advantage.</p>\r\n<h3>Tell-tale signs that financial information is not accessible enough for your management team:<br /><br /></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Behaviour:</strong> Look out for managers who often over spend; alternatively, those who seem over cautious and reticent about buying necessary resources to finish or start projects </li>\r\n<li><strong>Stalled projects:</strong> Often smaller items will have been purchased and the project will have started but problems arise when larger purchases cannot be afforded within the allocated budget</li>\r\n<li><strong>Management feedback:</strong> Finding out that managers are working on instinct, spending lots of time gathering data, guessing or roughly estimating their committed budget is a warning sign</li>\r\n<li><strong>What can you see?</strong> Can you access detailed information about your organisation&rsquo;s entire cost pipeline - beyond last month&rsquo;s financial statements?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Accounts Payable</h2>\r\n<p>Accounts payable is a key element in the P2P process but it is very dependent on the initial P2P steps - errors here can incur large costs. The crucial thing is to ensure your team can access sufficient information about what&rsquo;s been purchased in order to do to a good job when an invoice arrives.</p>\r\n<h3>Tell-tale signs that you need to review your accounts payable procedures:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Large numbers of invoices are received without purchase order numbers</strong>. Costly time is spent verifying details and seeking retrospective management approval</li>\r\n<li><strong>Your team is manually matching the details of hundreds of invoices to purchase orders</strong>. This is time consuming, repetitive (especially when working with paper) and prone to errors</li>\r\n<li><strong>You are frequently losing discounts for early payment of invoices</strong>. This could be due to slow processes, poor visibility of cashflow and a lack of management resources for forward planning</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>In conclusion</h2>\r\n<p>No matter how well controlled your P2P process is, it is worthwhile questioning its efficiency and related costs. How easy is it for your employees to buy the resources they need? How long is spent filing and retrieving documents, searching for information and validating invoices? How easily can your managers budget, plan, forecast and authorise spending? Are your purchasing controls being circumvented or is buying delegated because the process is too cumbersome? How much does a transaction cost your business? These are all worthwhile questions to ask and you may be surprised by what you find.</p>\r\n<h3>Top signs that your P2P process is costly and inefficient:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Reliance on paper or electronic forms that are not linked to a database: </strong>Does your finance team spend a lot of time chasing approvals and recreating, filing and retrieving paper documents?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Frustrated employees:</strong> Are employees struggling to get what they need to do their jobs productively or to find information for accurate budgeting?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Supplier enquiries:</strong> Do you receive high numbers of calls from suppliers about incorrect or late payments? </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Non-specialist purchasers: </strong>Are there people outside of your finance team who spend a disproportionate amount of time buying things for people?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Invoice volumes:</strong> How many invoices are received and processed each month by your accounts payable team? Could you reduce the average cost per invoice?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Payment lead times:</strong> Once an invoice is received, how long does it take to authorise? </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Asking these basic questions can result in multiple outcomes, and most organisations find areas for improvement. Armed with this understanding, the introduction of technology can simplify P2P and help you to nurture a culture where employees recognise and buy into the need to follow correct procedures.</p>\r\n<h2>Next steps</h2>\r\n<p>There are several software applications currently available that can help with addressing these challenges. On the market there are some very sophisticated and expensive systems that can cover stock control and supplier management (SAP and Oracle for example) in addition to more basic day-to-day purchasing processes. These are commonly used by businesses such as large retailers, manufacturers and distributors. At the other end of the spectrum we find organisations working with costly, inefficient and paper driven finance processes that lack the support of a document management system. Middle ground options, developed for non-stock purchasing organisations - in particular those in the service sector - are noticeably absent.</p>\r\n<p>For this reason, Arena has developed its own <strong>m</strong>store for Purchasing software to provide a straight-forward and cost-effective solution that is quick to implement for rapid returns in the form of efficiency, productivity, visibility and cost reduction. Our experiences in indexing, archiving, storing and retrieving millions of purchasing documents at organisations such as <a href="../../case_studies/26?service=Electronic+Document+Management" target="_blank">151 Products Ltd</a> and <a href="../../case_studies/35?service=Electronic+Document+Management" target="_blank">AtlasFram Group</a> has given us a unique insight into the challenges of developing efficient and practical workflows.</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of   experience in the electronic document management industry, working with   both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board  of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM  business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing  solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support  services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../page/edm-for-accounts-payable" target="_blank">Arena&rsquo;s mstore for Purchasing software</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../case_studies?page=2&amp;service=Electronic+Document+Management" target="_blank">Read about organisations using Arena&rsquo;s EDM solution</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/95" target="_blank">Join our next open day to see a demonstration of <strong>m</strong>store,</a> Arena''s own software for electronic document management</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-01-29', 'iStock_000018867956_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 124338, '2013-01-29 14:24:58', 'Purchasing', '2013-01-29 14:22:20', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'questioning-the-cost-of-purchasing'),
(111, 'Visit us on Stand P66 at PfH Live / CIH Housing 2014', 'The Chartered Institute of Housing’s Annual Exhibition is the UK’s ultimate housing experience focusing on the provision of affordable housing and the development of sustainable communities. Procurement for Housing’s PfH Live exhibition will once again be co-locating their annual event under the same roof. ', '<p class="introduction">Visit Arena Group at CIH Housing / PfH Live 2014. We will be exhibiting on the Procurement For Housing (PfH) Pavillion, <strong>stand P66</strong>, on 24th &ndash; 26th June 2014, Manchester Central.</p>\r\n<p>We will be showcasing our hardware and software for print management, and our managed print service (MPS). Our experts will also be on hand to discuss electronic document management and how you can combine technology to reduce costs, improve efficiency and improve sustainability.</p>\r\n<h2>WIN!</h2>\r\n<p><em class="font_blue">Visit our stand for your chance to win Toshiba goodies including tablets and bluetooth speakers!</em></p>\r\n<p>The Chartered Institute of Housing&rsquo;s Annual Exhibition is the UK&rsquo;s&nbsp; ultimate housing experience focusing on the provision of affordable housing and the development of sustainable communities. For the&nbsp;third year running, Procurement For Housing has partnered with CIH to host PfH Live under the same roof.</p>\r\n<p>Arena will be exhibiting alongside over 300 of the sector&rsquo;s leading providers, partners and suppliers as they showcase the latest products and services in the housing and regeneration sector. Free seminars will give delegates an opportunity to share best practice and solutions to current and future sector challenges.</p>\r\n<h2>Did You Know?</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1 class="font_blue">Arena Group is<img style="float: right;" src="../../../assets/articles/111/contained_images/9b065acc6d05_235_pfh - Nominated Suppiler.jpg?1378119904" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" width="100" /> PfH&rsquo;s number 1 nominated supplier for the provision of Photocopiers, Printers, Multi-Functional Devices (MFDs) and Office Based Managed Print Services (MPS).</h1>\r\n<p>PfH specialises in improving procurement practice for over 800 social housing providers throughout the UK.</p>\r\n<p>Arena is PfH&rsquo;s number 1 nominated supplier for the provision of Photocopiers, Printers, Multi-Functional Devices (MFDs) and Office Based Managed Print Services (MPS).</p>\r\n<p>The significance of our priority position is the fact that we have been put to the test by CEL Group, coming out at the top of a long list of competitors who were all put through a stringent tender process.</p>\r\n<p>Our no. 1 position confirms that our products and services are of the highest standard and we offer exceptional value to our clients.</p>\r\n<h2>More information: <a href="http://www.cihhousing.com/" target="_blank"></a></h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/framework-agreements">About the PfH Framework Agreement</a></p>\r\n<p>About PfH Live 2014: <a href="http://www.procurementforhousing.co.uk/insight-and-opinion/pfh-live-2014/" target="_blank">www.procurementforhousing.co.uk/insight-and-opinion/pfh-live-2014/ </a></p>\r\n<p>About CIH Housing 2014: <a href="http://www.cihhousing.com/" target="_blank">http://www.cihhousing.com/</a></p>\r\n<h2>Join The Discussion</h2>\r\n<p>Twitter: <span class="font_blue">@PfhLive2014</span> | <span class="font_blue">#PfHLive</span> |&nbsp; <span class="font_blue">@CIH_Housing2014 </span>|<span class="font_blue"> #Housing2014</span></p>', '2013-08-12', 'pfhlive2014.gif', 'image/gif', 6769, '2014-01-28 15:52:46', '', '2013-01-30 09:39:34', '2014-10-08 11:56:27', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'visit-us-on-stand-p66-at-pfh-live-cih-housing-2014'),
(112, 'Putting the Brakes on Wasteful Printing', 'Our Professional Services Manager, Ian Fox, explains how technology can be used to reduce wasteful, insecure and unnecessary printing', '<p class="introduction">Our Professional Services Manager, <strong>Ian Fox</strong>, explains how technology can be used to reduce wasteful, insecure and unnecessary printing</p>\r\n<p>Take a look around you &ndash; what do you see? I would bet that many readers will spot overflowing recycling bins and pages sitting uncollected on printers, forgotten or unwanted. Delve into those recycling bins and it&rsquo;s likely you would find documents printed several times in error, multi-page documents printed on one-sided pages (simplex). Perhaps webpages and emails printed in full, possibly in colour and over several pages including replies, Cc&rsquo;s and forwarded messages. There is also a frightening possibility that you might stumble upon a confidential document that was accidentally left on a printer and eventually binned (if indeed it remained in the building).</p>\r\n<p>The problem of uncontrolled printing raises various concerns;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The increasing cost of printing and paper places a heavy burden on budgets</li>\r\n<li>Activity within Arena&rsquo;s own customer base indicates that colour printing is on the rise, and this pushes up the cost of consumables</li>\r\n<li>Wasteful printing obviously has a negative environmental impact</li>\r\n<li>Sensitive documents printed on devices far away from the originating computer or device and/or subsequently forgotten about, pose a serious security risk.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>The right foundations for lower costs</h2>\r\n<p>Intelligent print management is becoming increasingly vital in addressing these issues and usually forms the foundation of a managed print service. Combining tools that monitor, archive and control output with the right mix of hardware, simplified maintenance, &ldquo;just in time&rdquo; toner supplies and transparent billing, will naturally push costs down. Not only this; a more print aware culture is nurtured, within which employees are far more considerate about what they print.</p>\r\n<p>Despite this evidence that print control delivers significant benefits, recent research from Quocirca suggests that adoption lags behind in the SMB market, where only 20% of businesses with 250-500 staff have centralised print management that can track output across all devices. Even more worryingly, 70% of respondents indicated that they had suffered at least one accidental data breach as a result of unsecured printing.</p>\r\n<p>With this in mind, I&rsquo;ve listed some of the features you might want to consider introducing to your print infrastructure if you have not done so already.</p>\r\n<h3>Rules-based printing:</h3>\r\n<p>Defaults can be applied based on job attributes such as colour, number of pages, single or double-sided (duplex) or the applications used to print from. For example, you may set a rule that defaults emails to print duplex and in black. Printing can then be directed to the most appropriate device in the network. This lets you control output from more expensive machines.</p>\r\n<h3>Secure pull printing:</h3>\r\n<p>Users send documents to a secure virtual &lsquo;queue&rsquo; and must go to a device (printer, MFD or other hardware) to access them. Authentication at the device is necessary to review documents in the queue; this can be managed using mechanisms including password login, PIN number, proximity card/fob or biometrics. Pull printing has obvious security benefits and ensures only required items are printed.</p>\r\n<h3>Quotas and permissions:</h3>\r\n<p>You may want to restrict certain functionality, colour printing or output from your most expensive devices for certain users. It is also possible to enforce quotas; this is increasingly done by education organisations to control student print volumes and manage budgets.</p>\r\n<h3>Cost recovery:</h3>\r\n<p>Consider whether you need to charge print, scan, copy and fax costs to internal users or teams. It is also possible to allocate costs to specific clients, divisions or cost centres. This is useful for businesses such as legal practices who charge individual clients and educational establishments that charge students.</p>\r\n<h3>Reporting:</h3>\r\n<p>It is possible to capture comprehensive information about overall activity on your network. Detailed reports enable analysis by user, device, server or client/cost centre.</p>\r\n<h3>Mobile printing:</h3>\r\n<p>Some print control applications enable you to send documents from mobile devices such as tablets and phones to the virtual print queue for release at a printer. Crucially, this output can be reported on in just the same way as activity from computers that are linked to your network. Read more about this in my recent <a href="../../../articles/106" target="_blank">BYOD article</a>.</p>\r\n<h2 class="introduction">It&rsquo;s impossible to manage what you cannot measure</h2>\r\n<p>Printing is here to stay, even though volumes may decline, so put the tools in place to let you proactively govern your print infrastructure. Print control provides cost transparency, improved document security and greener practices by ensuring that the right documents are printed by the right people at the right time.</p>\r\n<h3>About Ian Fox</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../..//assets/articles/112/contained_images/a222e4929534_276_Ian Fox Jan15 large.jpg?1422352750" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="130" height="130" align="LEFT" />Professional Services Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:ianF@arenagroup.net">ianF@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Ian Fox joined the Arena Group as a Systems Engineer in 1995. During his time at Arena he has gained a wealth of experience in helping organisations with their document related workflows. He now heads up the Professional Services department, which was formed in January 2011 with the aim of ensuring that existing and future Arena clients receive the best possible advice, solutions and support to enable them to manage and control their documents effectively.</p>\r\n<h2>More information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../web/contact_us" target="_blank">Contact us</a> to find out more about monitoring and controlling print, printing from mobile devices, digitising your paper-driven processes or implementing an electronic document management system.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/95" target="_blank">Visit us</a> to see a demonstration of our super-clean carbon zero printers and MFDs, mobile printing and print control in action.</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../case_studies" target="_blank">Read about how other businesses are benefiting from Arena''s document management services</a></p>', '2013-10-16', 'iStock_000014108701Small.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 241003, '2013-01-30 14:06:20', 'Cluttered Desk', '2013-01-30 13:29:48', '2015-02-02 10:15:41', 3, 7, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'putting-the-brakes-on-wasteful-printing'),
(113, 'Records Management in Schools #1: Developing a Records Management Policy', 'In a series of articles, Arena’s Neil Maude looks at the practical application of the rules surrounding records management in schools. In this first edition, Neil explains the requirements surrounding a records management policy and how you might approach its creation.', '<p class="introduction">The Information and Records Management Society (IRMS) curates a regularly updated &ldquo;Records Management Toolkit&rdquo; written specifically to assist UK public sector schools in their compliance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000. In a series of articles, Arena&rsquo;s Neil Maude looks at the practical application of the principles described in this toolkit, using Arena&rsquo;s 20+ years of experience in the provision of document management solutions within and outside of the education sector.</p>\r\n<h1><br />Part 1: Getting started - creating a records management policy</h1>\r\n<h2>Is there really a need?</h2>\r\n<p><br />Before we get into the detail of records management and the practical elements of implementing a policy, there is a fairly obvious first question to ask.&nbsp; Most schools have been around for a while &ndash; some for a very long while &ndash; and already have processes in place to manage documents in line with legislation and sector best practice.&nbsp; So is there really a need to change?&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>We believe there are 3 compelling reasons for a school to take a good look at the way it manages records and information:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Legislation</strong> &ndash; there&rsquo;s plenty of it and it&rsquo;s increasingly vigorous. Schools are subject to Freedom of Information and Data Protection rules, just like any other public organisation. In the event of a breach, the Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office (ICO) can, and sometimes does, impose fines or require organisations to sign undertakings to improve processes. Clearly it is better to be proactive and prepared.</li>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<li><strong>Retention requirements</strong> - The amount of information being retained is ever growing, increasingly time-consuming and expensive to deal with.&nbsp; As well as cost, this might lead to problems with storage &ndash; especially for schools in a new building with limited space to store paper files.&nbsp; Academies may be required to retain even more records - those previously held by the LEA - creating another new problem.</li>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<li><strong>Continued improvement</strong> - There is an expectation of continual improvement in every organisation. Record keeping should be no exception.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>With these points in mind, the IRMS toolkit becomes a very useful framework within which to revise or refresh your procedures.</p>\r\n<h2>What is a record?</h2>\r\n<p>The IRMS defines a record as <em class="font_blue">"all those documents which facilitate the business carried out by the school and which are thereafter retained &hellip; to provide evidence of its transactions or activities.&nbsp; These records may be created or received, and then stored, in hard copy or electronically.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>This definition pretty much means that every item of data you create is a record &ndash; from formal typed documents to handwritten permission slips and every single e-mail.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s a pretty daunting list. Clearly some records are more valuable than others and there are various pieces of legislation and guidance as to how long each record should be retained. All of which adds complexity.</p>\r\n<h2>Starting Point: Developing a formal Records Management Policy</h2>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/2b9f31c9bb0e_182_policy_image.jpg?1359558984" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="150" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>The IRMS toolkit recommends starting with a formal written records management policy or code of practice that sets out the scope, responsibilities and links to other existing policies.</p>\r\n<p>This policy needs to be endorsed by senior management and readily available to staff at all levels. The document should provide a mandate for records and information management and a framework for supporting standards, procedures and guidelines.</p>\r\n<p>The precise contents of the policy should, as a minimum:<br /><br /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Set out a commitment to create, keep and manage records which document the principal activities of the school</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Outline the role of records management, identifying and making appropriate connections to related policies, such as those dealing with email, information security and data protection</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Delegate roles and responsibilities for creating and using records appropriately</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Indicate how compliance with the policy and the supporting standards, procedures and guidelines will be monitored </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Outline how the policy will be reviewed and updated. This should be done at regular intervals and following any significant changes that may affect records management.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The toolkit includes a template which needs only the school name to be inserted and the document is then signed as a formal record of the school&rsquo;s commitment to its implementation.</p>\r\n<p>This is a good starting point because it clearly demonstrates and allocates responsibility. With the legislative implications, it&rsquo;s hardly surprising that the IRMS suggests that the one senior representative for the school (e.g. Head teacher) should take overall responsibility for implementing the policy.&nbsp; A second important point to note is that this person should also be responsible for providing guidance and promoting good practice.&nbsp; This is a little more contentious, as there is a time implication so it may be that this task is delegated and then audited.</p>\r\n<h2>Homework</h2>\r\n<p>Once this high level policy is in place, the next step is an information audit that looks at the information being held by the school. A sensible starting point for your information audit is to think about the types of information you hold, it may fall into categories, like these:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Current pupil records</li>\r\n<li>Former pupil records</li>\r\n<li>Finance records</li>\r\n<li>Human resources/staff records</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Considerations:</h3>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Your classifications may be unique to your school, and you may be storing more or less information within each category. For example, an academy may have buildings and facilities management records to hold and these could be considered either a subset of Finance or an entirely separate category</li>\r\n<li>Each category will have its own set of retention rules, governing how long each type of document should be stored</li>\r\n<li>Each category should consider security &ndash; who needs to see particular information and who should not. This is a big topic and will be considered in our next issue.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>A proper classification of information, with defined security and disposal timelines, introduces a number of rules-based &lsquo;housekeeping&rsquo; tasks and there are various ways in which you can handle these. An electronic document management system (EDMS) can easily automate the process and is well worth consideration. Retrieval of documents on a computer can take a matter of seconds, improving speed of access and responsiveness to enquiries and requests for information. Also, documents stored within a suitable EDMS (compliant with BSi standards for <a href="../../../page/edm-for-legal-and-professional-services">legal admissibility of electronic documents</a>) will allow the original paper to be destroyed &ndash; removing the need for large physical filing areas, better protecting your records and releasing physical space for other uses.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>For these reasons, the IRMS toolkit can be viewed not only as a best practice guide for records management, but a route forward to electronic record keeping.</p>\r\n<h2>Coming Up in Issue #2 &hellip; Conducting an Information Audit</h2>\r\n<p>The Information Audit is a critical first step in reviewing and understanding the information you hold, the format you currently hold it in, how and why it should be used and who should have access to it.</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of experience in the electronic document management industry, working with both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp; His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school" target="_blank">Records Management Toolkit for Schools Version 4</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">Electronic document management software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../case_studies?tag=Education" target="_blank">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/63_Papers on Rec Mment Education 102013v1_WebsiteVersion.pdf" target="_blank">Complete compliance guide: records management in schools</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Other papers in this series:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">#2: Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">#3: Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/136">#4: Information disposal</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/147?tag=Expert+News">#5: Email management</a></li>\r\n<a href="../../../articles/150">\r\n<li>#6: Risk and disaster recovery</li>\r\n</a> \r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-01-07', 'school_WS.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 72801, '2014-12-11 15:11:07', '', '2013-01-30 14:41:57', '2014-12-11 15:11:08', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'records-management-in-schools-1-developing-a-records-management-policy');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `headline`, `summary`, `main_content`, `date`, `image_file_name`, `image_content_type`, `image_file_size`, `image_updated_at`, `image_alt`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `created_by`, `updated_by`, `recycled`, `recycled_at`, `display`, `position`, `highlight`, `cached_slug`) VALUES
(114, 'Is paperless the answer to being a more sustainable business?', 'Very recently, Jeremy Hunt stated that going paperless “would save NHS billions”. It’s a bold statement and particularly topical in this economy – Arena''s Neil Maude gives us his top tips on taking the paper out of your office.', '<p class="introduction">Arena''s Neil Maude gives us his top tips on taking the paper out of your office.</p>\r\n<p>Going paperless &ldquo;would save NHS billions&rdquo; &hellip;. so says Jeremy Hunt. This was so bold a statement that I started getting phone calls as early as 7:30am that morning.&nbsp; Hardly surprising, given that we provide consultancy to NHS Trusts on how to deploy a range of solutions and some of our electronic document management (EDM) solutions have been in place in NHS Trusts since 1998.</p>\r\n<h1><br />So, it&rsquo;s a hot topic. Everyone wants to know if it&rsquo;s possible, and whether going paperless is really the answer to running a more sustainable business.</h1>\r\n<p>Over the last 15 years, we&rsquo;ve seen the good, the bad and the plain ugly of deploying EDM solutions to organisations of the scale of an NHS Trust and we&rsquo;ve learnt a lot. Turning a business into a more sustainable operation (for whatever reason, be it to create savings or to live brand values) is a huge challenge and requires a substantial culture shift.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The trigger for the <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-21033984" target="_blank">BBC headline</a> was on the publication of a PwC report and a ministerial speech by Jeremy Hunt, recommending &lsquo;better use of technology in patient care&rsquo;.&nbsp; Just to set right an initial confusion, much of the &pound;9Bn+ proposed savings are linked to better use of data systems and not just &ldquo;going paperless&rdquo;.&nbsp; This is an important point to make. The two are naturally connected and there is no magic formula to just &lsquo;going paperless&rsquo; &ndash; there&rsquo;s a quite complex process required to make this actually work. The huge savings figure actually covers a broad spread of efficiency gains &ndash; mainly from information sharing between different components of the NHS but also in patient self-service (access your own data, make choices, report on outcomes) and reduction in areas of risk/liabilities.&nbsp; The actual &ldquo;paperless&rdquo; bit &ndash; which I read as &ldquo;removing a large chunk of paper filing and providing that information to be used electronically&rdquo; - is based on a number of case studies and anticipated results.</p>\r\n<p>What struck me as very good in the PwC study was the inclusion of best practices from a wide group of organisations outside healthcare.&nbsp; There is also a detailed analysis of the challenges involved in this kind of organisational change &ndash; winning support, nurturing the &lsquo;early adopters&rsquo; and measuring the benefits.&nbsp; This again is fitting for organisations in all sectors and there are many useful insights here.</p>\r\n<p>Clearly, the report is talking about a very large piece of work&nbsp; but leaving aside the peculiar challenges which come from that scale, these challenges mirror those which we see time and again in organisations big and small.&nbsp; And whilst the NHS doesn&rsquo;t have the best track record of IT implementation, the &ldquo;on the ground&rdquo; problems of system implementation are little different to those encountered elsewhere.</p>\r\n<h1>Understanding how to make our businesses more sustainable, more productive and more efficient is a challenge many of us face. It is not an overnight transition but there are some simple steps which can often get you started on the right tracks.</h1>\r\n<h2>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Get end users involved early, or they will not come along for the ride</h2>\r\n<p>Ideally in the decision making and how the system will be used.&nbsp; It sounds obvious, but even just a few end users who will &lsquo;champion&rsquo; the system can make all the difference.&nbsp; With any process change there will be a learning period and your users should want the system to be a success rather than a failure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Be pragmatic</h2>\r\n<p>paper is still the best tool for some jobs and overall &ldquo;usability&rdquo; is the aim of the system. Involving users will highlight some areas where 100% &ldquo;paperless&rdquo; just won&rsquo;t work.&nbsp; Sometimes a piece of paper is the best way to capture or share information &ndash; accept this and look at complimentary technologies to produce documents and capture the data from paper.&nbsp; This isn&rsquo;t failing to &ldquo;go paperless&rdquo;, it&rsquo;s just providing a solution which is fit-for-purpose!</p>\r\n<h2>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Select key short-term goals to win support for the initiative</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; Pick the low hanging fruit&rdquo;.&nbsp; Having a particular team or business area&nbsp; lauding the benefits they&rsquo;ve had from document management will create interest from everyone else.&nbsp; Even if you want to have a &ldquo;big bang&rdquo; change, someone has to go first and this should be managed carefully.</p>\r\n<h2>4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Set realistic measurement parameters and make sure they are used to appraise progress against the plan</h2>\r\n<p>Ideally these measures should be quantitative &ndash; which can sometimes require a creative way to define &lsquo;softer&rsquo; benefits.&nbsp; There is nothing quite like a number to prove the benefit of the system.&nbsp; It&rsquo;ll also tell you how well your project is progressing.</p>\r\n<h2>5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Get management buy-in across the organisation</h2>\r\n<p>This is important even in the areas who aren&rsquo;t going to be paperless straight away.&nbsp; Sharing a vision creates &ldquo;pull&rdquo; and energy &ndash; it also avoids pockets of naysayers.</p>\r\n<h2>6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Be aware that information is used for many purposes</h2>\r\n<p>As well as allowing for efficient retrieval, think about how information is created/collected/modified (forms, updates and extra notes added to existing pages).&nbsp; What are the appropriate tools for each situation and what technology is already in place?</p>\r\n<h2>7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Think of who needs to see the information and where</h2>\r\n<p>Accessibility is vital to a successful implementation, without it you&rsquo;ll just have printouts. Ensure you are making it easy for those who need to, to access it otherwise you will have failed before you&rsquo;ve begun.</p>\r\n<h2>8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The flip side to accessibility is security</h2>\r\n<p>Make sure yours is upgraded. Paper can be lost, but electronic data can be lost (or stolen) in vast amounts and many board directors are nervous of this.&nbsp; So build in appropriate security from the start.</p>\r\n<h2>9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Think about the structure of what you&rsquo;re storing</h2>\r\n<p>(A taxonomy, in the jargon). Consider what indexes are required to allow the information to be retrieved quickly &ndash; once you start storing information you will be locked into a structure which can be hard to change.</p>\r\n<h2>10.&nbsp; Consider the different ways that information comes into the organisation</h2>\r\n<p>(i.e paper, e-mail, electronic data). Aim to consolidate this to a single path based on purpose rather than managing by where it came from &ndash; this is the next step towards managing your processes as well as controlling your paper.</p>\r\n<p>These all seem obvious things to do but we&rsquo;ve seen plenty of examples where one or more has been missing &ndash; always to the detriment of the overall initiative.&nbsp; It is possible to reduce your paper usage in a large organisation, and improve your business processes at the same time &ndash; but only if you have a clear plan.<br />Taking these points on board, the NHS may have a better chance of realising those billions of pounds they have earmarked in savings&hellip;and other businesses of all shapes and sizes can also look forward to a &lsquo;greener&rsquo; 2013.</p>\r\n<h3><br />About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of experience in the electronic document management industry, working with both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp; His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank"></a><a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">Electronic document management from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../case_studies?service=Electronic+Document+Management" target="_blank">Case Studies: Clients using EDM</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-21033984" target="_blank">BBC News feature on this topic</a></li>\r\n</ul>', '2013-02-19', 'RecyclingBin_WS.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 103431, '2014-12-11 15:04:29', '', '2013-02-12 11:27:25', '2014-12-11 15:04:30', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'is-paperless-the-answer-to-being-a-more-sustainable-business'),
(115, 'Join us at Social Housing Procurement', 'Arena will be exhibiting on stand no. 14 at Social Housing Procurement North, March 19th in Manchester''s Midland Hotel. We will be showcasing the latest technology in document management to deliver cost savings, improve efficiencies and introduce greener ways of working.', '<p class="introduction">Meet us at SHP, Manchester on March 19th. Stand No. 14</p>\r\n<p>Arena Group will be showcasing the latest technology for document management  to  deliver cost savings, improved efficiencies and greener ways of   working.</p>\r\n<h2>Arena is the No. 1 approved supplier on the Procurement For Housing Framework.<a href="../../../page/framework-agreements" target="_blank"></a></h2>\r\n<p>PfH specialises in improving procurement practice for over 800 social housing providers throughout the UK.</p>\r\n<p>Arena is PfH&rsquo;s number 1 nominated supplier for the provision of  Photocopiers, Printers, Multi-Functional Devices (MFDs) and Office Based  Managed Print Services (MPS).</p>\r\n<p>The significance of our priority position is the fact that we have been put to the test, coming out at the top of a long list of competitors who were all put through a stringent tender process. Our no. 1 position confirms that our products and services are of the highest standard and we offer exceptional value to our clients.</p>\r\n<h2>About this event</h2>\r\n<p>With increased demand for affordable housing and pressure on budgets in a tough economic climate,   housing associations, arm&rsquo;s length management organisations (ALMOS)  and  local government must seek value for money across all areas  of  acquisition.</p>\r\n<p>While the challenges of reform are great, organisations that   prioritise procurement, seek to reduce costs and harness efficiencies   will be able to maximise efficiencies across areas of supply, reduce the impact of funding cuts by securing value for money, control and manage risk in the supply chain and apply innovation in procurement to deliver creative outcomes.</p>\r\n<p>With over 3,000 housing associations, local authority landlords and  arm&rsquo;s length management organisations (ALMOs) in the UK, managing  approximately 4.5 million homes, the social housing sector has  significant buying power and procurement innovation could revolutionise  service delivery.</p>\r\n<h2>Event features:</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Keynote arena welcoming industry experts, policy makers and leading authorities on procurement and supply chain management</li>\r\n<li>Networking with social housing practitioners operating across the UK</li>\r\n<li>Procurement  training workshops offering CPD Certified interactive, practical  training on procurement and supply chain management, regulatory reform  and the challenges/opportunities post implementation</li>\r\n<li>Supplier exhibition showcasing innovative solutions designed to enable you to capture efficiencies and deliver improved services</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Who is attending?</h2>\r\n<p>Social Housing Procurement invites key decision  makers, policy makers, procurement practitioners and Housing Managers  spanning Housing Associations, ALMOs, local authorities and the supplier  community to explore and discuss the latest developments in  social housing procurement.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.shprocurement.co.uk/north/home/" target="_blank">Information about this event - www.shprocurement.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.shprocurement.co.uk/register/" target="_blank">Register to attend this event</a></p>', '2013-02-21', 'SHP_Image.png', 'image/png', 25032, '2013-02-12 15:54:36', '', '2013-02-12 14:54:44', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'join-us-at-social-housing-procurement'),
(116, 'Arena Helps Age UK Spread The Warmth', 'On Friday 8th February, Arena employees dug out their woolly jumpers, scarves and gloves and donned their wackiest woolly hats in aid of Age UK’s “Bobble Day”, which aims to make winter an easier season for older people.', '<p class="introduction">On Friday 8<sup>th</sup> February, Arena employees dug out their woolly jumpers, scarves and gloves and donned their wackiest woolly hats in aid of Age UK&rsquo;s &ldquo;Bobble Day&rdquo;, which aims to make winter an easier season for older people.</p>\r\n<p>By working our woollies, we raised a total of &pound;152.00 for the charity. This could help them to fund the cost of befriender visits to 30 isolated elderly people, or provide 15 older people with a vital winter pack of clothing, food, information and thermometers to keep them warm and well. As well as supporting a great cause, the day was a lot of fun&hellip; A big thank you to everyone who donated and got involved!</p>\r\n<p><strong>Find out more:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Age UK&rsquo;s Bobble Day: <a href="http://www.ageuk.org.uk/get-involved/spread-the-warmth/bobble-day/">http://www.ageuk.org.uk/get-involved/spread-the-warmth/bobble-day/</a></p>', '2013-02-14', 'Woolies.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 46740, '2013-02-14 14:30:15', '', '2013-02-14 14:27:32', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 5, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arena-helps-age-uk-spread-the-warmth'),
(117, 'Records management and the BSF storage conundrum', 'BSF buildings take learning to a new height but sometimes neglect critical support functions and the paperwork they curate. Arena''s Lisa Butterworth explores the options for schools that need to manage the reduction of a large paper document archive.', '<p><span class="introduction">The spread of new academies across the country has brought with it an array of stunning new BSF buildings. Academy status also often bestows a qualified business manager to take control of budgets. However, with every possible learning resource granted to them, some new academies appear to be under-resourced when it comes to handling the legal requirements surrounding records management.</span><br /><br />The Building Schools for the Future (BSF) program is spreading, inspiring new buildings across the UK designed to maximise the sustainable education experience. Many boast the newest technology and usually academy status that shifts budgets and decision-making responsibility to senior management teams. It seems that almost every resource is dedicated to the learning environment and, looking from the outside in, it&rsquo;s difficult to see a down side.</p>\r\n<p>However, many of these multi-million pound facilities mirror the same design features: large atriums and expansive, minimally furnished communal spaces. This sometimes contrasts with a distinct absence of space for business support functions and critical documents that go hand-in-hand with renewed management responsibility.</p>\r\n<h2>The legal landscape</h2>\r\n<p><br />The Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office is <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-19424197" target="_blank">ever-more strict regarding data breaches in education.</a> Schools are under the spotlight and feeling the pressure of increasingly stringent rules.<br /><br />It&rsquo;s a fact that schools are legally obliged to keep sensitive records, such as child protection files, locked away for access only by authorised staff (ie; a child protection officer) for the lifetime of the children concerned. With modern medicine moving on in leaps and bounds, we are talking about upwards of 90 years. Other documents must be retained for 7 years before they are securely destroyed &ndash; and keeping a file for too long can be just as troublesome as letting go too soon. <br /><br />Freedom of Information requests add a further headache in the form of short notice demands for records that may be buried in an archive of paper files. Add to this the requirement to audit who looks at documents, when and exactly what they do; and you are presented with a challenge to the scale of literally thousands upon thousands of pages. In SEN schools the issue is exploded with head teachers managing around 10 times the number of records held by a regular secondary school.</p>\r\n<h2>Ticking paper time bombs</h2>\r\n<p><br />With all of this to contend with, some head teachers are sitting in older buildings with vast paper archives stacked up in basements, offices and store rooms.</p>\r\n<p>It''s no surprise that almost every school - gifted academy status or not &ndash; is being forced to consider what to do with all of that paper. Landing a new BSF building that promises practically no storage space simply adds the pressure of a deadline. <br /><br />This issue is widespread but only seen in the press when a school falls foul of the regulations, having failed to produce files for a legal case, suffered a security breach or lost records in a crisis such as a fire.</p>\r\n<h1>So, what options are there?</h1>\r\n<h3>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Manage the paper in-house</h3>\r\n<p>This means taking on the associated risks of loss, damage and legal cases.</p>\r\n<h3>2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; External storage</h3>\r\n<p>This can be expensive and problematic when it comes to data security and retrieval.</p>\r\n<h3>3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Digitise your archive and paper-driven processes.</h3>\r\n<p>A good electronic document and records management system (or, EDRMS) and processes in place including a <a href="../../../articles/113" target="_blank">sound records management policy</a>, can retain the legal admissibility of your documents. You are also afforded greater control over security and you can shred the paper.</p>\r\n<p>Many schools are opting for the this third measure, scanning documents in-house to a central database. This is a step in the right direction but throwing every document into one central, un-structured, electronic space presents problems with security and retrieval. For this reason it''s wise to consider specialist software.</p>\r\n<h2>Whichever option you choose, there are some key considerations worth making;</h2>\r\n<h3>Security</h3>\r\n<p>Think about how you store your paper files and look for a software package that will replicate it. Remember, you must be able to evidence that sensitive documents are secure and accessible only to authorised personnel.</p>\r\n<h3>Audits</h3>\r\n<p>Make sure your system enables you to track who is accessing which data, when and why.</p>\r\n<h3>Retrieval</h3>\r\n<p>Consider how you want to search for documents once they are digitally stored.</p>\r\n<h3>Integration</h3>\r\n<p>A good EDRMS package will work with your existing software, including common databases such as SIMS, or function-specific software, like SAGE. Think carefully before replacing anything - it could be a lengthy and stressful task.</p>\r\n<h3>Experience and Support</h3>\r\n<p>Choose an established application that&rsquo;s made for schools, buy directly from the developer to ensure you get top notch support and always ask for references.</p>\r\n<h3>A phased approach</h3>\r\n<p>The task can appear daunting so most good EDRMS software providers will be happy to advise and help you to create a plan based around your needs.</p>\r\n<p>Breaking the task into chunks will make it easier to manage, so decide whether to tackle current or archive documents first and then consider which document types to start with. For example, you may begin by training your staff to digitise current student records whilst outsourcing the scanning of your paper archive to a specialist with the expertise and staff resources.</p>\r\n<h3>About Lisa Butterworth</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/117/contained_images/e8e4b79c673a_186_Photo_Dec2012.jpg?1361468993" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Marketing Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">LisaB@arenagroup.net</a> | Twitter: @MrsButterwth</p>\r\n<p>Lisa Butterworth is a Chartered Marketer  with over 10 years of B2B and B2C experience in sectors including  education, packaging and software. Currently Lisa is the Marketing  Manager for Arena Group, never ceasing to be fascinated by technology made to make paperwork more efficient and simple to deal with.</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> <a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">mstore: EDRMS software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/edm-for-storing-protecting-and-retrieving-critical-documents" target="_blank">Arena''s Scanning Bureau - Digitise your paper archive</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/63_Papers on Rec Mment Education 102013v1_WebsiteVersion.pdf" target="_blank">Complete compliance guide: records management in schools</a> </li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.ico.gov.uk/what_we_cover/taking_action/dp_pecr.aspx" target="_blank">Recent ICO Data Breaches</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school">IRMS Records Management Toolkit for Schools </a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Related Articles</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">#1: Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">#2: Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">#3: Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/136">#4: Information disposal</a></li>\r\n<a href="../../../articles/150"> </a>\r\n<li> <a href="../../../articles/150"> </a><a href="../../../articles/records-management-in-schools-5-email-management" target="_blank">#5: Email management</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/150">#6: Risk and disaster recovery</a></li>\r\n<a href="../../../articles/150"> </a> \r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2013-01-08', 'BSF_School.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 64362, '2013-02-22 09:04:51', 'BSF School Building', '2013-02-21 17:43:38', '2015-03-31 14:08:02', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'records-management-and-the-bsf-storage-conundrum'),
(118, 'Arena Group: Proud Sponsor of Jane Tomlinson''s Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Run Series', 'Two of the stars of our sponsored Jane Tomlinson Junior and Mini Fun Run series were honoured at an awards ceremony hosted in Leeds during February. Eight-year-old James Driver, from Rothwell, and six-year-old Noah Banks, from Selby, were given a special honour for embodying Jane’s ‘Never Give In’ attitude.', '<p class="introduction">Two of the stars of our sponsored Jane Tomlinson Junior and Mini Fun Run series were honoured at an awards ceremony hosted in Leeds during February.</p>\r\n<p>Eight-year-old James Driver, from Rothwell, and six-year-old Noah Banks, from Selby, were given a special honour for embodying Jane&rsquo;s &lsquo;Never Give In&rsquo; attitude.</p>\r\n<p>Noah completed a children&rsquo;s run and helped raise &pound;20,000. James took part in two children&rsquo;s runs to raise funds for surgery to help him walk unaided. Both have cerebral palsy.</p>\r\n<p>Arena''s MD, Adrian Fitzpatrick, who was at the awards ceremony said: "It was an honour watching Noah and James accept their awards - they embody such great values and are so inspirational. At Arena we really enjoy&nbsp;sponsoring these runs every year as we meet some amazing young people and it''s humbling to see what they achieve. We''re really looking forward to this year''s run, which is soon to be launched."</p>\r\n<p>Please visit <a href="http://www.forallevents.co.uk" target="_blank">www.forallevents.co.uk</a> for more details</p>', '2013-03-01', 'james_and_noah.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 20026, '2013-03-13 09:34:26', 'James and Noah', '2013-03-11 14:05:02', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'arena-group-proud-sponsor-of-jane-tomlinsons-arena-group-junior-and-mini-fun-run-series'),
(119, 'New Arena Group Premises in Bolton: Foundations for North West Expansion', 'Arena Group has good cause to celebrate this month having just purchased a new property and acquiring a new customer base through local business PGL Graphics Ltd.', '<p class="introduction">Arena Group has good cause to celebrate this month having just purchased a new property and acquiring a new customer base through local business PGL Graphics Ltd.</p>\r\n<p>The new site purchase sees Arena&rsquo;s workforce in the region move from Chorley New Road, into The Quad on Atherleigh Business Park. &nbsp;The new 190 square meter facility houses a sales office, workshop and more accessible storage space than the previous site. The Sales Team has also been provided with a brand new, state-of-the-art showroom to showcase the latest technology in print and document management. Logistics Director, Harry Wells, comments; &ldquo;the open plan layout of the building will encourage greater collaborative working and the renewed facilities strongly position the business for continued expansion in the North West.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>As the business continues to expand in the North West, Arena&rsquo;s rapidly growing customer base was boosted this week with the addition of over 100 service contracts from long-established local business PGL Graphics Ltd. Arena is now to provide maintenance and support for all PGL Graphics previous print clients. Recruitment is also underway for several sales account managers to double the size of the business&rsquo;s Lancashire-based workforce.</p>\r\n<p>Arena is an award winning team spread across 6 UK sites and working with local clients including Bolton St Catherine&rsquo;s Academy, Manchester Rusk and &nbsp;AFG Law LLP, helping them to manage their print strategy and documents in a more efficient, less costly and greener way.</p>\r\n<p>The Group has an ambitious 5 year plan which sets targets of &pound;20million turnover and 7 UK sites to be reached by 2015. September saw Arena close its financial year on an all-time high with a record turnover that comfortably out-stretched annual targets. This has placed the business onto a winning trajectory for successful performance against its 5 year plan.</p>\r\n<p>MD Adrian Fitzpatrick said: &ldquo;Arena has grown over the past 21 years through sheer hard work and determination to make our industry better. We have always focused on providing a first class service and investing in this new site signifies our long term commitment to the North West. &rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This site is a significant investment that delivers improved facilities with the addition of a brand new showroom and a workshop for our service team &ndash; it also gives us the space we need to grow. Having had such a strong year we&rsquo;re in a great position to continue to push the business forward; improving our facilities is of benefit to both staff and customers alike.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Committed to the long term, Arena also runs a very successful Apprenticeship Academy which has seen 21 staff members trained up over a 5 year program. This new site introduces new workshop space that will allow for the expansion of the scheme into the North West.</p>\r\n<p>As a provider of print and document solutions, Arena works with clients operating in many sectors including schools, housing associations, automotive suppliers and building societies; making use of technological advancements to increase efficiencies and reduce costs through effective document and print management.</p>\r\n<h6><em>Pictured: Richard Slingsby (left) and Michael Wallington (right) at the new Arena site in Bolton.</em></h6>', '2013-03-11', 'richard_and_michael.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 96054, '2013-03-13 09:38:34', '', '2013-03-11 14:17:40', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'new-arena-group-premises-in-bolton-foundations-for-north-west-expansion'),
(120, 'Records Management in Schools #2: Conducting an Information Audit', 'Information is generally accepted as a key asset in any organisation and should be managed with the same care as more tangible assets such as money, buildings and classroom equipment.  Effective information management is all about security and getting data to the right people at the right time.  The IRMS toolkit rightly states that an information audit is a key step to achieving these aims.', '<p class="introduction">The Information and Records Management Society (IRMS) curates a regularly updated &ldquo;Records Management Toolkit&rdquo; written specifically to assist UK public sector schools in their compliance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000. In a series of articles, Arena&rsquo;s Neil Maude looks at the practical application of the principles described in this toolkit, using Arena&rsquo;s 20+ years of experience in the provision of document management solutions within and outside of the education sector.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h1>Part 2: Conducting an Information Audit</h1>\r\n<p>Information is generally accepted to be a key asset in any organisation and should be managed with the same care as more tangible assets such as money, buildings and classroom equipment.&nbsp; Effective information management is all about keeping information secure and getting it to the right people at the right time.&nbsp; The IRMS toolkit rightly states that an information audit is a key step to achieving these aims.</p>\r\n<h2>What is an Information Audit?</h2>\r\n<p>Simply put, the information audit is a survey of the records being used and held by the organisation.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s a structured process of finding out what you have, where it is kept and how it is used. The IRMS toolkit suggests a step-by-step process which encompasses the same principles that Arena has used extensively in both the education and wider public/commercial sectors.</p>\r\n<h2>Step one: Secure a senior sponsor</h2>\r\n<p>The audit process requires a lot of in-depth access to information and discussions with key staff so it&rsquo;s important to have good senior backing. Make sure you also clearly explain the purpose behind the audit process to those involved, so everyone understands the aim of the exercise.</p>\r\n<h2>Step two: Identify key personnel</h2>\r\n<p>The information audit begins with the assumption that records are created for a particular purpose. Therefore, the ideal starting point is an organisational diagram or similar chart, showing the key functions.&nbsp; From this, we can identify the key staff to interview with regard to what information assets they manage.&nbsp; The IRMS suggests that the survey work could be via interview or questionnaires &ndash; from experience I would strongly recommend the face-to-face approach, as the quality and detail of feedback is invariably much better.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Step three: Map your document pathways</h2>\r\n<p>Once key people are identified, work with them to make a list of records being created. It often helps to think of the work being done as a chain of actions &ndash; often the document will go to other areas of the business and it is important to capture this journey.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Step four: Ask pertinent and insightful questions</h2>\r\n<p>The IRMS toolkit contains an excellent checklist of questions to ask about each record type to cover areas such as key points of access, security and retention/disposal. Look out for the next features in this series which will explore these points in more detail.</p>\r\n<p>There are two additional key areas for consideration which can draw significant insight and additional benefit from the audit process, so it&rsquo;s well worth making to effort to include them in your agenda when you are speaking to your information curators:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Room for improvement:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The audit is an opportunity to identify potential process improvements.&nbsp; Although it will need to be handled sensitively, a certain amount of &ldquo;and why do you do it that way?&rdquo; analysis can be undertaken.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Continuity planning:</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Another good question to ask is &ldquo;what if you lost all of the information of this type &ndash; maybe in a fire &ndash; how would this affect you and what would you have to do about it?&rdquo;&nbsp; This will help to determine the importance of records (operationally, if not legislatively) and give a head-start for disaster and risk-reduction planning.</p>\r\n<ol> </ol>\r\n<h2>Step five: Review, update, repeat &hellip;</h2>\r\n<p>Finally, the audit should be considered a snapshot in time.&nbsp; Like any other audit, there should be a clear plan as to how the findings will be refreshed and kept current.&nbsp; Any process changes arising from the audit should also be subject to a &lsquo;plan-do-check-act&rsquo; cycle of implementation and verification.</p>\r\n<p>A complete and comprehensive information audit also puts the organisation in a state of readiness to update, or indeed create, a meaningful records management policy &ndash; <a href="../../../articles/113">covered in part one of this series</a>.</p>\r\n<p>The information audit is an important early step to implementation of an electronic document management (EDM) solution.&nbsp; It is difficult to see any organisation achieving a successful records management policy without a complete and regularly updated information audit.</p>\r\n<h2>Homework</h2>\r\n<p>The next issue in this series looks at the rules surrounding the safeguarding and security of your documents and critical information. The following considerations are a good starting point:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>How you currently ensure that only authorised people have access to sensitive files, and how you would evidence this if asked to do so by the Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office (ICO). </li>\r\n<li>The number and frequency of Freedom of Information Act requests you receive and how quickly and completely you are able to respond to them.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<h2>Coming Up in Issue #3 &hellip; Information access and security</h2>\r\n<p>Protection of information relating to children is clearly a key responsibility and it&rsquo;s an obligation that is shrouded in layers of legislation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>It is tempting to think that locking away your information and restricting access is the best way forward but this can slow down day-to-day work.&nbsp; Some information &ndash; such as medical records &ndash; must be both quickly available, restricted only to those who need to see it and monitored in terms of who has accessed it, when and why.</p>\r\n<p>So, information access and security should be considered together and in balance. My next article will give you some practical advice to tackle this issue.</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of  experience in the electronic document management industry, working with  both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school" target="_blank">Records Management Toolkit for Schools Version 4 (IRMS)</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">Electronic document management software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../case_studies?tag=Education" target="_blank">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a> </li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/63_Papers on Rec Mment Education 102013v1_WebsiteVersion.pdf" target="_blank">Complete compliance guide: records management in schools</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Other papers in this series:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">#1: Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">#3: Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/136">#4: Information disposal</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/147?tag=Expert+News">#5: Email management</a></li>\r\n<a href="../../../articles/150">\r\n<li>#6: Risk and disaster recovery</li>\r\n</a> \r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-03-12', 'iStock_000002831046Small.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 257162, '2013-03-12 10:04:51', 'Clip Board Man', '2013-03-12 09:40:30', '2014-12-11 16:00:10', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'records-management-in-schools-2-conducting-an-information-audit'),
(121, 'Arena Scoops Employer of The Year Award', 'Arena Group is very proud to have accepted the Employer of The Year accolade at this year''s Leeds Apprenticeship Awards.', '<p class="introduction">During National Apprenticeship Week 2013 we joined guests at Leeds Civic Hall for the Leeds Apprenticeship Awards ceremony. We were delighted to pick up the Employer of The Year award!</p>\r\n<p>There are 3 awards in this category, for small, medium and large  employers. The award showcases the business  benefits gained through a commitment to Apprenticeships and is for  employers who have demonstrated an embedded training culture and a  dynamic delivery model which is achieving outstanding results.</p>\r\n<p><span class="share-body">On accepting the award Arena''s Head of HR, Martin Wright, commented; "this is fantastic recognition for everyone involved with our very  successful <a href="../../../page/apprenticeship-programme" target="_blank">Apprentice Academy</a>. It''s great to receive acknowledgement for  the hard work that goes into the recruitment and development of our apprentices. We see huge value in this effort as the majority of our apprentices will complete their programs and become uniquely skilled, loyal and valued members of the Arena Team." </span></p>\r\n<p><span class="share-body">On presenting the award, ceremony host JoJo of the region''s Capital FM breakfast show, said; "</span>Arena Group&rsquo;s commitment to recruiting for attitude and investing in  training provides long term career prospects for its employees whilst  retaining a highly skilled workforce. It is clear from their nomination  that they have ambitious development plans for each individual that  joins the organisation. They&rsquo;ve recognised the potential for  apprentices to have a bigger impact to their business and are looking to  expand their Apprenticeship Academy."</p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/apprenticeship-programme" target="_blank">Find out more about Arena''s Apprenticeship Academy</a></p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/121/contained_images/c203501d3bdc_198_DSC_9606.JPG?1363349111" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="250" /></p>\r\n<h6><em>Pictured Top: Arena Apprentices celebrate success with Group Service Manager Mick Harrison and Workshop Manager Peter Maskill. Pictured above: Martin Wright of Arena (Left) and Ben Williams of SMG Europe (Right)</em></h6>', '2013-03-19', 'DSCN1843.JPG', 'image/jpeg', 127494, '2013-03-15 12:03:39', '', '2013-03-13 15:04:44', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'arena-scoops-employer-of-the-year-award'),
(122, 'Junior runners supporting children with learning disabilities ', 'Around 1,500 children are set to cut a dash this Spring when they take part in this year’s Arena Group Leeds Mini and Junior Run. The biggest FREE mass participation children’s event of its kind in Yorkshire will raise funds this year for children''s charity, Leeds Mencap.', '<p class="introduction">Around 1,500 children are set to cut a dash this Spring &ndash; when they take part in this year&rsquo;s Arena Group Leeds Mini and Junior Run. The popular annual event is back for a fifth year and this year will raise funds for Leeds Mencap, which provides vital advice, help and support for children with learning disabilities and their families across the city.</p>\r\n<p>The Arena Group Leeds Mini and Junior Run is organised by Jane Tomlinson&rsquo;s Run For All. Sponsorship from Arena makes it the biggest FREE to enter mass participation children&rsquo;s event of its kind in Yorkshire.</p>\r\n<p>Staged on <strong>Sunday 12<sup>th</sup> May</strong>, it comprises two runs &ndash; a 1.5km mini course for 3 to 8-year-olds and a 2.5km route for 9 to 14 year olds. Both start and finish in Leeds&rsquo; showpiece Millennium Square.</p>\r\n<p>Youngsters are simply asked to raise a small amount of money for a charity of their choice. This year they are encouraged to raise sponsorship for Leeds Mencap, to help fund its family centre and support groups.</p>\r\n<p>Arena''s Managing Director, Adrian Fitzpatrick, said the company was excited to be on board, adding; &ldquo;We are thrilled to be sponsoring the Arena Group Junior and Mini Run series for the fifth consecutive year; allowing every child to take part for free. We&rsquo;re also really pleased to be working with Mencap in support of the invaluable services they provide to local children and their families.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Cath Lee, the CEO of Leeds Mencap said: &ldquo;We are delighted to be able to work alongside the Arena Group and Jane Tomlinson&rsquo;s Run For All as their chosen charity for the Junior and Mini run this year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;All the monies raised from this fun sporting event will help support our children and young people&rsquo;s projects from our Hawthorn Family Support Centre for very young children with a learning disability helping their early development right through to the Friday Club which is for 18 &ndash; 25 year olds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We would encourage each runner to try to raise as much as they can to help young people in Leeds with learning disabilities who need that extra support to learn new skills, conquer boundaries and take part in activities all children and young people like to do!&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Mini and Junior Run event lead Tristan Batley-Kyle said: &ldquo;The mini and junior runs are just brilliant for kids. It&rsquo;s a great way for them to get involved in sport in a safe and fun environment.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This year, they&rsquo;ll be raising money for a great cause, too. Leeds Mencap does amazing work and we&rsquo;re proud that our little runners will be helping children with learning disabilities.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Entries are now open for the Leeds Mini and Junior Runs. To sign up, go to <a href="http://www.forallevents.co.uk/run-for-all"></a><a href="http://http//www.forallevents.co.uk/run-for-all" target="_blank">www.forallevents.co.uk/run-for-all</a></p>\r\n<h6><em>Photo courtesy of Yorkshire Evening Post.<br /></em></h6>', '2013-03-15', 'Website_LeedsLaunch_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 31630, '2013-04-09 10:16:43', '', '2013-03-15 13:20:24', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'junior-runners-supporting-children-with-learning-disabilities'),
(123, 'Pyjama Day Fun for Comic Relief', 'Arena Group employees wore their pyjamas to work on Friday 15th March to raise cash for Comic Relief.', '<p class="introduction">Our staff were in the mood for fun on Friday 15th March when our ''Little and Often'' day for Comic Relief raised a tremendous &pound;142.76 for the charity!</p>\r\n<p>Staff came to work wearing their pyjamas and the styles on show included onesies, cotton PJs - some even accessorized with teddy bears and sleeping caps!</p>\r\n<p>All-in-all a fun day was had by all, and in aid of a great cause. Staff dug deep to raise &pound;71.38 which was doubled by Arena which has a policy of match-funding any charitable funds raised by its staff.</p>\r\n<p>This far, Comic Relief has raised over &pound;75m for global causes. To donate or to find out more please visit <a href="http://www.comicrelief.com" target="_blank">www.comicrelief.com</a>.</p>', '2013-03-18', 'Comic Relief.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 42280, '2013-03-21 10:34:58', 'Comic Relief PJ Day', '2013-03-21 10:35:00', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'pyjama-day-fun-for-comic-relief'),
(124, 'VIDEO: Records Management in Schools: Shrinking the Paper Mountain', 'Did you miss our webinar? If you did then don''t fear, we recorded it so you can watch it online. Expert advice on reducing paper records, putting information at the fingertips of staff and supporting compliance with increasingly rigorous regulations surrounding records management in schools. ', '<p class="introduction">Our recent webinar provided expert advice on shrinking your school''s paper mountain, putting information at the fingertips of staff and supporting compliance with increasingly rigorous regulations surrounding records management in schools.</p>\r\n<p>Document management expert and education sector specialist, <strong>Curtis Mariani</strong> chatted with our host, <strong>Mike Starkings</strong>, during a 20 minute session that may change the way you work with  documents forever. - Liberate storage space, increase document security,  save money and drive efficiencies.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/U7Px5aY2cUg" width="420" height="315"></iframe></p>\r\n<h2>Didn''t make it?</h2>\r\n<p>Look out for details about forthcoming webinars on the <a href="../../../articles?tag=Events" target="_blank">events news pages of the Arena website</a>.</p>\r\n<h3>Catch-up using the links below.</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank">mstore for Education: EDM Software for schools</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Related articles</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">Conducting an information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/industry-expert-articles/item/553-the-importance-of-information-access-and-security.html" target="_blank">The importance of information access and security</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Contact Curtis</h3>\r\n<p>If you would like to discuss records management with Curtis please email a request to <a href="mailto:webinar@arenagroup.net">webinar@arenagroup.net</a>.</p>', '2013-07-10', 'iStock_000001541504_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 158092, '2013-04-08 14:00:40', 'Paper records stacked in corridor', '2013-04-08 13:38:37', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'video-records-management-in-schools-shrinking-the-paper-mountain');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `headline`, `summary`, `main_content`, `date`, `image_file_name`, `image_content_type`, `image_file_size`, `image_updated_at`, `image_alt`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `created_by`, `updated_by`, `recycled`, `recycled_at`, `display`, `position`, `highlight`, `cached_slug`) VALUES
(125, 'Junior runners on starter''s orders in York', 'Hundreds of young runners are limbering up to secure a cash injection for poorly children. The popular annual Arena Group York Mini and Junior Run is back on August 4th for a fourth year – and this year will raise money for the children’s ward at York Hospital which provides vital care for youngsters and support for their families. ', '<p class="introduction">Hundreds of young runners are limbering up to secure a cash injection for poorly children. The popular annual Arena Group York Mini and Junior Run is back for a fourth year &ndash; and this year will raise money for the children&rsquo;s ward at York Hospital which provides vital care for youngsters and support for their families.</p>\r\n<p>The Arena Group Mini and Junior Run is organised by Jane Tomlinson&rsquo;s Run For All and takes place annually in York and Leeds.&nbsp;&nbsp; Arena pays for every young runner to take part in the events, making the series one of the biggest FREE mass participation children&rsquo;s event of its kind in Yorkshire. <br /><br />Setting off on <strong>August 4th</strong> from York&rsquo;s Knavesmire, the event comprises two runs &ndash; a 1.5km course for 3 to 8-year-olds and a 2.5km route for 9 to 14-year olds &ndash; and is entirely FREE to enter for all youngsters. <br /><br />Children are simply asked to raise a small amount of money for a charity of their choice. This year they are encouraged to raise sponsorship for ward 17 &ndash; the children&rsquo;s ward &ndash; at York Hospital. <br /><br />Fundraisers at the hospital plan to spend the money specifically on replacing the ward&rsquo;s out-dated nurses&rsquo; station &ndash; the first point of call for distressed youngsters and their parents. The station dates back to the 1970s; it has not been refurbished since and is now in desperate need of replacement. <br /><br />Using money raised from the Arena Group York Mini and Junior Run, staff on the ward aim to revamp the station to create a new warm, welcoming environment for children and their families. Patients on the ward will be encouraged to have a say in how they want the new area to look. <br /><br />York Teaching Hospital Charity Fundraising Manager Lucy Lowthian said she hoped the improvements would help make an often very stressful hospital visit just that bit easier. <br /><br />Lucy said: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re really thrilled to have been chosen as the beneficiary for this year&rsquo;s Arena Group York Mini and Junior Run. It&rsquo;s a great event and we&rsquo;re really happy to be a part of it.<br /><br />&ldquo;To be able to refurbish the nurses&rsquo; station would be fantastic. We really want to make it more child-friendly, just to be able to make things a tiny bit easier for our patients and their families. <br /><br />&ldquo;We&rsquo;ll be asking the children for their input &ndash; we want it to be really appealing for them and to be quite striking and welcoming.<br /><br />&ldquo;We&rsquo;ve wanted to complete this project for quite some time but we have never had the funding before so it has always had to stay on the &lsquo;wish list&rsquo;.&rdquo;<br /><br />Arena''s Managing Director, Adrian Fitzpatrick, said: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re really excited to be sponsoring the Arena Group York Mini and Junior Run for the fourth year running; our support allows every one of the hundreds of children involved to take part for free.<br /><br />&ldquo;It&rsquo;s fitting that, this year, they will be encouraged to raise sponsorship for the children&rsquo;s ward at York Hospital and will be helping make a very distressing time just that bit more bearable.<br /><br />&ldquo;We&rsquo;re really looking forward to race day &ndash; the smiles on the kids&rsquo; faces remind us exactly why we sponsor the event.&rdquo;<br /><br />Arena Group York Mini and Junior Run event lead Tristan Batley-Kyle said: &ldquo;The mini and junior run is a great way for youngsters to get involved in sport in a really fun and safe way.<br /><br />&ldquo;Seeing them all cross the finishing line is a really special experience.&nbsp; This year they will be supporting children in hospital, helping to make their ordeals just that little bit easier.&rdquo;<br /><br />Entries are now open for the Arena Group York Mini and Junior Runs on August 4th. To sign up go to <a href="http://www.forallevents.co.uk/run-for-all/" target="_blank">www.forallevents.co.uk/run-for-all.</a></p>\r\n<h6>Pictured: Arena''s Marketing Manager, Lisa Butterworth, poses with For All Events mascot, Tommo The Toirtoise on Ward 17.</h6>', '2013-04-10', 'York_Launch_Photo_1.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 25597, '2013-04-10 12:21:09', '', '2013-04-10 12:21:10', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'junior-runners-on-starters-orders-in-york'),
(126, 'Join Arena at Gloucestershire''s Premier Conference for Schools', 'We will be showcasing our mstore for Education software for electronic document management at this year''s Gloucestershire Association of School Business Management Conference - 14th June. ', '<p class="introduction">Arena Group will be hosting stand E7 at Cheltenham Race Course during this year''s GASBM Conference. Join us on June 14th.</p>\r\n<p>Our experts will be available for the day to discuss records management in schools. Visit us on stand E7 for advice on the increasingly rigorous rules surrounding the safeguarding and security of school documents. We can help you with challenges surrounding storage, retrieval, security and archiving of paper and digital documents within your school, showcasing Arena''s own <a href="../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank">mstore for Education</a> software for electronic document management.</p>\r\n<p>Gloucestershire Association of School Business Management (GASBM)  membership is open to all serving Business Managers, Bursars, School  Administrators and Finance Officers in the<br />area. GASBM is a thriving group providing information, training, advice and guideance to a membership of over 170 schools. Meetings  are held three times a year and feature a combination of exhibitions, presentations and workshops.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Following the very successful GASBM 2012 Conference, this year''s event is pitched to be even more exciting with over 60 sponsors and exhibitors joined by more than  200 delegates from across Gloucestershire and further afield  including London, Yorkshire, Cornwall, Somerset, Wiltshire and  Worcestershire.</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.gasbm.org/default.asp?id=2160" target="_blank">Registration and information: GASBM 2013 Conference</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank">Arena''s mstore for Education software</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">Records Management in Schools: Expert articles</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2013-04-18', 'Presentation1.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 17218, '2013-04-18 08:43:27', 'GASBM Banner', '2013-04-18 08:40:23', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'join-arena-at-gloucestershires-premier-conference-for-schools'),
(128, 'Innovation speed dating for schools: May 3rd 2013', 'Looking for something a bit different this term? Look no further than Innovate My School LIVE - a free innovation speed dating session between school leaders and innovative education suppliers!', '<p class="introduction">Designed specifically for local school cluster groups, <a href="http://tinyurl.com/avyssol" target="_blank">Innovate My School LIVE</a> is an opportunity to be inspired, have fun and to procure, as a group, some of the most exciting products on the market today.</p>\r\n<p>Arena will be pitching <strong>m</strong>store for education, our very own software for electronic document management, at the Liverpool Association of Secondary Headteachers'' speed date on the 3rd May.</p>\r\n<p>The event will take place between 10.30am and 12.30pm on May 3rd at Formby Hall Golf Resport and Spa in Merseyside.</p>\r\n<p>We look forward to seeing you there!</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/live" target="_blank">Innovate My School Live</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f0oRh4HQlHA" target="_blank">IMS Live 2012 - Video</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank">mstore for Education</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2013-04-25', 'ims_live_logo_300.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 52474, '2013-04-25 10:47:20', 'InnovateMySchoolLIVE', '2013-04-25 09:59:31', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'innovation-speed-dating-for-schools-may-3rd-2013'),
(129, 'Arena''s expansion is underway', 'We have begun to lay the foundations for our ambitious growth plans this month having completed the extensive expansion of our Garforth training and distribution center, purchased a new property in Bolton and got underway with an upgrade to the sales and board room wing of Armitage House.', '<p class="introduction">A recently completed extension of our training and distribution center in Leeds has increased square footage by over 50%. The site is home to Arena&rsquo;s Apprentice Academy and workshop for service technicians, customer service call centre, logistics team and warehouse.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">M.D Adrian Fitzpatrick explains: &ldquo;It is essential we continue to invest in bricks and mortar as our facilities have a direct impact on the service we provide. As we forge ahead with our growth plans, we need to have the very best facilities to enable us to deliver on our promises and maintain our high service levels.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">We also invest a lot in training our staff and our Apprenticeship Academy is a valued part of that effort. In 2012 our Garforth based service team undertook 251 days of training &nbsp;and this commitment is only going to increase as we continue to grow, so expansion really was just a matter of time&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">The Armitage House refurbishment will see office space re-arranged to make way for an additional 12 members of staff to join us this year. Following the successful refurbishment of the admin wing, showroom and first floor Sales wing, work is due to start on an upgrade of the board room and surrounding offices. This will open up the space to make way for our rapidly growing sales team. Investment is also being made into telephony and electronics technology to ensure that larger call volumes and staff numbers can be seamlessly accommodated.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The new site purchase at Bolton sees our North West workforce move into The Quad on Atherleigh Business Park. The new 190 square meter facility represents a significant investment and provides the sales team with a brand new, state-of-the-art showroom to showcase the latest technology in print and <a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">document management</a>. Logistics Director, Harry Wells said: &ldquo;The open plan layout of the building will encourage greater collaborative working and the renewed facilities strongly position the business for continued expansion in the region.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">Arena&rsquo;s rapidly growing North West customer base was also boosted this month with the addition of over 100 service contracts from long-established local business PGL Graphics Ltd.</p>\r\n<p>Committed to the long term development of talent, Arena&rsquo;s Apprenticeship Academy has recently been recognised with the <a href="../../../articles/121" target="_blank">Employer of The Year</a> accolade from the Leeds Apprenticeship Awards. The new Bolton site introduces new workshop space that will allow for the extension of the business&rsquo;s 5 year apprenticeship scheme for service technicians.</p>\r\n<p>MD Adrian Fitzpatrick said: &ldquo;Arena has grown over the past 21 years through sheer hard work and determination to make our industry better. We have always focused on providing a first class service and investing in our buildings is a smart business decision on many levels. It&rsquo;s also imperative that we continue to invest in getting the very best staff, and keeping them. Improving our facilities most definitely plays a part in this.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Recruitment is currently underway for several sales account managers, a telesales executive and a Marketing Assistant.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../page/careers" target="_blank">Join our team! Recruitment opportunities</a></p>', '2013-04-01', '170D4897.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 226084, '2013-04-25 13:43:52', 'Arena Sign', '2013-04-25 13:44:00', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'arenas-expansion-is-underway'),
(130, 'INFOGRAPHIC: The process behind Arena''s tailored Managed Print Service.', 'An infographic that explains the process and benefits behind Arena Group''s Managed Print Service (MPS), proven to reduce print and copy costs by up to 30%.', '<p class="introduction">Proven to reduce print and copy  costs by up to 30% whilst taking the hassle out of maintenance and procurement of consumables. The <a href="../../../images/MPS-infographic-620w.jpg" target="_blank">infographic</a> below explains the process and benefits behind Arena  Group''s Managed Print Service (MPS).</p>\r\n<h5><em>Click the image below to enlarge it.</em></h5>\r\n<h3>Related Pages:<a href="../../../page/copy-and-print" target="_blank"></a></h3>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/copy-and-print" target="_blank">More about MPS from Arena</a> | <a href="../../../page/managed-document-service" target="_blank">Arena''s Managed Document Service (MDS)<em>&nbsp;</em></a><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<p><a style="padding-left: 0; background: none;" href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/55_MPS infographic.pdf" target="_blank"><img src="../../../images/MPS-infographic-620w.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="620" /></a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/55_MPS infographic.pdf" target="_blank">Download this Managed Print Service Infographic as a PDF</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/bVMfr-DiuSg" width="560" height="315"></iframe></p>', '2013-05-03', 'Infographic.png', 'image/png', 1633608, '2014-02-03 09:28:31', 'The Document Expertise', '2013-05-03 15:30:11', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 6, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'infographic-the-process-behind-arenas-tailored-managed-print-service'),
(131, 'Records Management in Schools #3: Information Access and Security', 'The protection of information relating to children is clearly a key responsibility and it is an obligation that is shrouded in layers of legislation. It is tempting to think that locking away your information and restricting access is the best way forward but this can slow down and frustrate day-to-day work. Neil Maude gives us his advice for schools on information access and security.', '<h1 class="introduction">The Information and Records Management Society (IRMS) curates a regularly updated &ldquo;Records Management Toolkit&rdquo; written specifically to assist UK public sector schools in their compliance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000. In a series of articles, Arena&rsquo;s Neil Maude looks at the practical application of the principles described in this toolkit, using Arena&rsquo;s 20+ years of experience in the provision of document management solutions within and outside of the education sector.</h1>\r\n<h1>Part 3: Information Access and Security</h1>\r\n<p>The protection of information relating to children is clearly a key responsibility and it is an obligation that is shrouded in layers of legislation. It is tempting to think that locking away your information and restricting access is the best way forward but this can slow down and frustrate day-to-day work. Some information, such as medical records, must be both quickly available and restricted only to those who need to see it; so information access and security should be considered together and in balance.</p>\r\n<h2>Two particular pieces of legal guidance to be aware of</h2>\r\n<p>The Freedom of Information Act states that schools must respond to requests for information pertaining to individual pupils in a timely fashion. Failure to meet FoIA requests can and does lead to action by the Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office (ICO). Changes to Special Education Needs (SEN) legislation are expected to deliver increased numbers of requests.</p>\r\n<p>Compliance with BS10008 enables you to destroy paper files, whilst ensuring that the electronic copies remain legally admissible. Schools are required to produce a full audit trail to prove the veracity of their documentation. They must also implement a mechanism to prove that documents have not been tampered with and employ a retention policy.</p>\r\n<h2>Practical steps towards compliance</h2>\r\n<p><br />Having developed a records management policy and conducted an information audit you are in a good position to decide how to implement access controls for your documents.</p>\r\n<p>Compliance can be complex and problematic if you are working with scattered documents that are stored in several different ways. For example, you may have some paper child protection documents in a locked cabinet accessible only by your child protection officer. Other documents relating to the same pupil may be stored in your admin office or held in your SIMS database, computer files and applications (such as email inboxes) or digital storage devices. A sensible first step is to minimise variations in document formats and locations. A good <a href="../../../page/edm-for-education">electronic document management system</a> (EDMS) can assist this by bringing documents and storage systems together for access via one reference point.</p>\r\n<p>Whether you are working with paper or digital files &ndash; or a mix of both, there are some important legal compliance questions to address, these are explained below.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Storage</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4 class="indented"><span class="font_blue">"Pupil records should be kept securely at all times. Paper records should be kept in lockable storage areas with restricted access, and the contents should be secure within the file. Equally, electronic records should have appropriate security."</span> &ndash; IRMS Toolkit.</h4>\r\n<p><strong>Question:</strong> How do you store your records? How do you guarantee that they are never left unattended and seen by unauthorised people?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Paper: </strong>The IRMS suggests a clear desk policy involving the removal of physical records to locked storage facilities whilst they are not in use, whilst restricting access to offices where confidential files are being stored or worked on. It is likely that you will need to split records in order to store sensitive documents separately, for access only by authorised people.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EDMS: </strong>Allocate login details and access rights to individual users so that they can only access file types that they are authorised to see. For example, your child protection officer will be able to see sensitive records that a secretary working in your admin office will not be able to see. You can prevent sensitive documents from being shared, printed, deleted and/or over-written. Computer monitors can be set to switch to stand-by after a set period of inactivity, requiring the user to enter a password to re-activate the screen. This means documents left on-screen at unattended desks will be protected.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Completeness</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4 class="indented"><span class="font_blue">"A pupil or their nominated representative have the legal right to see their file at any point during their education and even until the record is destroyed. This is their right of subject access under the Data Protection Act 1998." </span> &ndash; IRMS Toolkit.</h4>\r\n<p><strong>Question:</strong> ICO judgements against schools falling foul of the FoIA have, to date, been largely for failure to comply with requests in a timely or complete fashion. If you were asked to provide a copy of every document you have ever stored on an individual pupil, how easily could you respond and could you be absolutely certain that you had a complete file with not a single document missing?<br /><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Paper: </strong>With the ICO list in mind, the location of information is paramount.&nbsp; Physical filing can be a problem in that files can only be in the hands of one person at any one time, are often not replaced and are at risk of being lost. Your storage and archiving system is critical. The way you log where physical files are placed, and your strategies for avoiding filing errors, are fundamental to ensuring that you can rapidly bring together comprehensive information.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EDMS: </strong>Search facilities provide immediate and comprehensive access to documents that can be accessed via the system. This simplifies preparation for audits and FoIA requests whilst reducing the risk of missing information &ndash; providing the EDMS is a central document store.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Movement</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4 class="indented"><span class="font_blue">"Staff should be encouraged not to take personal data on staff or students out of the school.</span> &ndash; IRMS Toolkit.</h4>\r\n<p><strong>Question: </strong>Does paperwork ever leave your premises? If so, how do you keep it secure?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Paper: </strong>The IRMS guidance here is to check paper files out from a central system and log details of the borrower to create an audit trail. This does require an element of trust as you cannot control what happens to documents once they leave your building. There is also a risk of human error when it comes to logging - and document theft or loss outside of school.<br /><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>EDMS: </strong>Data that is held on your servers may be accessed remotely, negating any need to ever transfer data onto a portable device such as a laptop. This mitigates several risks that arise from allowing documents to leave your premises &ndash; including theft, damage and loss.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Confidentiality</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4 class="indented"><span class="font_blue">"Access arrangements for pupil records should ensure that confidentiality is maintained, whilst equally enabling information to be shared lawfully and appropriately, and to be accessible for those authorised to see it.</span> &ndash; IRMS Toolkit.</h4>\r\n<p><strong>Question: </strong>How do you ensure that only authorised personnel can access confidential information? How do you monitor and evidence this? How quick and easy is the process?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Paper:</strong> Documents can only be held in one location, so ensure that only authorised people can access them using lockable storage. In addition, consider placing record sheets into sensitive files to log access information.</p>\r\n<p><strong>EDMS:</strong> In addition to the security functionality detailed above (logins and permissions), an EDMS system has the benefits of an audit trail of user activity.&nbsp; This allows the adoption of much more of a &lsquo;trusted&rsquo; approach to security, as well as being a key component of ensuring that your electronic records remain legally admissible. Unlike files saved on disks or similar media, an EDMS compliant with BS10008 allows you to use electronic documents as evidence. Clearly, you should only consider disposing of your paper records if your EDMS holds legally admissible information.</p>\r\n<p>Approaching access and security with a view to making information available quickly to those who need it is a great aid to both implementing the policies developed from your information audit and ensuring that you are well placed to cope with the demands of prevailing legislation.</p>\r\n<h2>Homework</h2>\r\n<p>Consider how you currently manage retention schedules. Look at how much time is spent archiving documents in order to isolate those that have reached their retention deadline and must be securely destroyed. Think about the measures you have in place to ensure that this is done accurately and comprehensively, without errors.</p>\r\n<h2>Coming Up in Issue #4 &hellip; Information Disposal</h2>\r\n<p>Schools are legally obliged to keep some types of records for in excess of 25 years. Other documents must be retained for shorter periods before they are securely destroyed. Just like failing to keep a record for long enough, retaining a document for too long can breach compliance regulations and disposal guidelines are equally important.&nbsp; My next article provides guidance to help you glide over various document retention hurdles.</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of  experience in the electronic document management industry, working with  both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.ico.gov.uk/what_we_cover/taking_action/dp_pecr.aspx" target="_blank">ICO list: Prosecutions, penalties and formal undertakings</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=6092125" target="_blank">Times Education Supplement: SEN-appeal parents keep legal aid</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=6071806" target="_blank">Times Education Supplement: Parent power predicted to see surge in SEN appeals</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school" target="_blank">IRMS Records Management Toolkit for Schools Version 4</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">Electronic document management software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../case_studies?tag=Education" target="_blank">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a> </li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/63_Papers on Rec Mment Education 102013v1_WebsiteVersion.pdf" target="_blank">Complete compliance guide: records management in schools</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Other papers in this series:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">#1: Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">#2: Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/136">#4: Information disposal</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/147?tag=Expert+News">#5: Email management</a></li>\r\n<a href="../../../articles/150">\r\n<li>#6: Risk and disaster recovery</li>\r\n</a> \r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-04-08', 'iStock_000015150766Small.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 286274, '2013-05-08 09:54:11', 'Confidential', '2013-05-08 09:40:15', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'records-management-in-schools-3-information-access-and-security'),
(132, 'National Association of School Business Management Conference', 'Arena will be attending the National Conference of the NASBM on November 19th and 20th at Birmingham''s Hilton Metropole Hotel. Join us on stand no. 28.\r\n\r\n', '<p class="introduction">Arena will be attending the National Conference of the National Association of School Business Management (NASBM), in Birmingham on November 19th and 20th.</p>\r\n<h2>Join us on stand no. 28</h2>\r\n<p>We will be showcasing our <a href="../../../page/print-the-hidden-costs" target="_blank">managed document service (MDS) </a>and <a href="../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank">mstore for Education</a>, Arena Group''s very own software for electronic document management in schools.</p>\r\n<h2 style="text-align: justify;">The&nbsp;event will be hosted from 19-20 November at the Hilton Birmingham Metropole Hotel.<span class="TitleNavy"> <br /></span></h2>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The two-day National Conference attracts&nbsp;around 200 delegates,&nbsp;the  majority being&nbsp;School Business Managers representing both primary and  secondary phases of education.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">An exhibition runs alongside the  conference featuring over 70 exhibitor stands and each year delegate and  exhibitor space is&nbsp;oversubscribed.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">The conference offers a balanced mix between, keynote speakers from relevant organisations and government bodies,  dedicated workshop sessions and time to network with colleagues and  exhibitors. The Gala Dinner is always a popular feature and will take place again this year.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">Delegates will choose from a selection of&nbsp;participatory workshops with practical tools to take back to school.</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;">This year NASBM will be raising money for the <a href="http://www.cysticfibrosis.org.uk/" target="_blank">Cystic Fibrosis Trust</a>. This charity funds research into the disease and provides information and support for patients and their families.</p>\r\n<h3>Further Information</h3>\r\n<p><a href="http://http//www.nasbm.co.uk/Home/Conferences/National-Conference/National-Conference-2014-Exhibition.aspx" target="_blank">NASBM National Conference 2014</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.birminghammetropole.com/?WT.srch=1" target="_blank">Birmingham Metropole Hotel</a></p>\r\n<h2>Join the discussion</h2>\r\n<p>The official Twitter hastag for this event is <a href="http://twitter.com/search?f=realtime&amp;q=#NASBM14&amp;src=typd" target="_blank">#NASBM14</a>, mention us using the handle <a href="http://https//twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank">@ArenaGroup</a></p>', '2014-07-07', 'Logo.gif', 'image/gif', 4055, '2013-05-09 09:05:08', 'NASBM Logo', '2013-05-09 09:05:08', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'national-association-of-school-business-management-conference'),
(133, 'VIDEO: BBC Watchdog on shrinking Inkjet Cartridges', 'BBC watchdog recently reported that some inket printer manufacturers have reduced the size and capacity of their ink cartridges over the past decade, whilst maintaining sky-high prices. ', '<p><span class="introduction">BBC watchdog recently reported that some inket printer manufacturers  have reduced the size and capacity of their ink cartridges over the past  decade, whilst maintaining sky-high prices. </span></p>\r\n<p>You can watch the video  clip below.</p>\r\n<p><iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/K5hH3xC6W2s" width="420" height="315"></iframe></p>\r\n<p>The BBC Watchdog report found 1 litre of inkjet printer ink to be:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>1800 times pricer than 1 litre of petrol</li>\r\n<li>4000 times pricer than 1 litre of crude oil</li>\r\n<li>Equal to the cost of 68 bottles of premium whiskey</li>\r\n<li>Equal to the cost of 21 bottles of vintage champagne</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Related articles: <a href="../107?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank"></a></h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/107">Which? report: Inkjet ink pricier than Champagne</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/107" target="_blank">Arena''s top tips on economical printing</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../articles/112" target="_blank">Putting the brakes on wasteful printing</a></p>', '2013-05-15', 'cartridges.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 14210, '2013-05-15 12:03:58', 'Cartridges', '2013-05-15 11:49:34', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'video-bbc-watchdog-on-shrinking-inkjet-cartridges'),
(134, 'Over 1,300 Youngsters join in support of local charity', 'The Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Runs are always well attended in Leeds, and this year was no exception, with more than 1,300 youngsters taking part in support of Leeds Mencap.', '<p class="introduction">The Arena Group Junior and Mini Fun Runs are always well attended in Leeds; this year was no exception, with more than 1,300 youngsters taking part in support of Leeds Mencap.</p>\r\n<p>Amongst the happy throng was England Rugby  coach Stuart Lancaster who ran with his daughter. Stuart said: &ldquo;It was great, the kids loved it &ndash; you could see them really putting their hearts and souls into it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Other runners included James Driver, 8, from Rothwell, Leeds, who is  still battling to walk unaided after undergoing pioneering surgery.  James finished the 1.5km course in 58 mins &ndash; beating his target time of 1  hour.</p>\r\n<p>Arena funds entry fees so that every child  in the Mini and Junior Run &ndash; aged between 3 and 14 &ndash; can join in for FREE. Many  were also raising funds for a favourite cause; this year&rsquo;s chosen  charity was <a href="http://www.leedsmencap.org.uk/" target="_blank">Leeds Mencap</a> which provides vital support to children and  adults with learning disabilities.</p>\r\n<p>Arena''s Group Service Manager, Mick Harrison, was at the event. Mick congratulated the fastest runners and winning Schools Challenge Teams, and presented them with their medals. Well done to our winners!</p>\r\n<h2>Fastest Boys</h2>\r\n<p>1<sup>st</sup> Male &ndash; William Collumb<br />2<sup>nd</sup> Male &ndash; Alex Pagdin<br />3<sup>rd</sup> Male &ndash; Alexander Booth</p>\r\n<h2>Fastest Girls</h2>\r\n<p>1<sup>st</sup> Female - Flo Straughan<br />2<sup>nd</sup> Female &ndash; Molly Garbutt<br />3<sup>rd</sup> Female &ndash; Alisha Laidler</p>\r\n<h2>Schools Challenge Winners</h2>\r\n<p>High School (Junior Runners) - Cockburn High School<br />Primary School (Mini runners) - St Margaret&rsquo;s Primary School</p>\r\n<p>Arena Group Managing Director Adrian Fitzpatrick said: &ldquo;The Arena Group  Leeds Mini and Junior Run is always a brilliant event. We&rsquo;re really  pleased to be able to support it again this year. We hope everyone had a great time and have raised lots of money for Leeds  Mencap, which provides a really important service for the city.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Running in York?</h2>\r\n<p>Entries are now open for the Arena Group York Mini and Junior Runs on August 4th. To sign up go to <a href="http://www.forallevents.co.uk/run-for-all/" target="_blank">www.forallevents.co.uk/run-for-all.</a></p>\r\n<h6>Pictured: Mick Harrison presents awards to the fastest runners and winning School Challenge teams.</h6>', '2013-05-13', 'Photo_MickH_Leeds_JunrMini_May2013.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 66052, '2013-05-24 16:19:02', 'Mick Harrison', '2013-05-24 16:19:03', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'over-1300-youngsters-join-in-support-of-local-charity'),
(135, 'Maintaining Excellence through Innovation', 'Arena has maintained a fantastic level of customer service, from the day the company was started in 1991 to the present.  Arena’s Operations Director Harry Wells and General Manager Neil Maude discuss how structured innovation helps Arena continue to improve service levels whilst the company continues to grow.', '<p class="introduction">Arena has maintained a fantastic level of customer service, from the day the company was started in 1991 to the present.&nbsp; Arena&rsquo;s Operations Director Harry Wells and General Manager Neil Maude discuss how structured innovation helps Arena continue to improve service levels whilst the company continues to grow.</p>\r\n<h2>A culture of service excellence</h2>\r\n<p>Arena&rsquo;s most recent customer survey showed some key metrics which prove the high standard of our customer service. 97% of our customers would recommend Arena and 90% rated our service quality at &ldquo;4/5&rdquo; or &ldquo;5/5&rdquo;.&nbsp; This feedback from our customers is tangible proof of all the hard work put in by colleagues across the different areas of the business.&nbsp; The company was founded on the principle that excellence in customers service will attract and retain customers, and this culture remains to this day.</p>\r\n<h2>Maintaining &ndash; and bettering &ndash; with growth</h2>\r\n<p>However, the challenge is to continue &ndash; and even improve upon &ndash; this trend, as the company grows.&nbsp; Clearly, as Arena has expanded from 10 to over 150 staff, there have been many changes to working practices and processes.&nbsp;&nbsp; In the &ldquo;early days&rdquo;, everyone knew everyone else very well.&nbsp; But it is no longer the case that people working in one area of the business will regularly meet their counterparts in other areas &ndash; that a field service engineer will meet a credit controller, for example.&nbsp; In many businesses, this can lead to islands of information or processes which aren&rsquo;t quite &ldquo;joined up&rdquo;.&nbsp; A task may be done a particular way for efficiency in one area, but cause problems in another area &ndash; all with the best intentions, but on an individual level.&nbsp; However, our customers judge our services on the whole process &ndash; from sales to installation to service, including administration and billing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Whilst this has never been a big issue at Arena, it was identified by the Management Team as an area where the company could seek improvement.&nbsp;&nbsp; It was decided that we needed to give everyone in the company a &ldquo;voice&rdquo;, where their ideas for better service could be both heard and considered in the light of the whole process from the perspective of a customer.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Embedded innovation</h2>\r\n<p>To achieve this, Arena created an &ldquo;Innovation Group&rdquo; with the express purpose of acting as a focus&nbsp; group for ideas - ensuring that efficiency improvements could be identified and acted upon.</p>\r\n<p>Launched at the company Annual Conference, the innovation initiative is based upon the concept of an innovation value chain<a href="#_edn1">[i]</a> &ndash; which comprises the initial idea, the development of that idea into a process change and, crucially, the publicising of that change across the business.&nbsp; The &ldquo;heavy lifting&rdquo; is done by an Innovation Team of volunteers from across the business &nbsp;who are &ldquo;the people you speak to when you have a good idea&rdquo;.&nbsp; This team collate and develop ideas, then secure management sponsorship for business change.&nbsp; This process ensures that great ideas are recognised and put into practice &ndash; but only when the customer value has been proven.<a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a></p>\r\n<h2>The outcomes</h2>\r\n<p>The fruits of this initiative have seen over 130 actionable ideas, with 65% taken forward to business process efficiencies &ndash; typically within the areas of customer communication and interaction, such as clearer billing processes. &nbsp;This has helped Arena not only to maintain standards, but to improve and to achieve a 98.7% &ldquo;overall satisfaction&rdquo; rating in the most recent customer satisfaction survey, along with the measures mentioned previously.&nbsp; Of course, the innovation ideas are only the start and the real work is done by the Arena team who deliver daily on the promise of excellence.</p>\r\n<h3>About Harry Wells and Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/135/contained_images/619a4b5103e0_212_Harry_ws.jpg?1370002710" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" />Harry Wells: Operations Director<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:HarryW@arenagroup.net">HarryW@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Harry is one of the two remaining founding partners of Arena. His team looks after everything relating to purchasing, distribution, installation, collection and maintenance of products.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" />Neil Maude: Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:NeilM@arenagroup.net">NeilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil sits on Arena''s board of directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business. His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div><br /> \r\n<hr size="1" />\r\n<div>\r\n<h6><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a> The Innovation Value Chain concept is original academic work by Morten Hansen and Julian Birkinshaw, as published in Harvard Business Review, June 2007.&nbsp;</h6>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h6><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a> Arena&rsquo;s innovation processes have been benchmarked against other company innovation practices in a number of ways, including membership of the Bradford University School of Management &ldquo;Innovation Club&rdquo; (<a href="http://www.bradford.ac.uk/management/cme/news/">http://www.bradford.ac.uk/management/cme/news/</a>).&nbsp;</h6>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', '2013-05-30', 'Ideas_WS.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 128671, '2014-12-11 15:48:08', '', '2013-05-31 12:10:40', '2014-12-11 15:48:08', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'maintaining-excellence-through-innovation');
