(136, 'Records Management in Schools #4: Information Disposal', 'Neil Maude gives us his advice for schools on the disposal of information in line with current legislation. This feature is based on guidance from the regularly updated IRMS Records Management Toolkit; written specifically to assist UK public sector schools in their compliance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000.', '<p class="introduction">The Information and Records Management Society (IRMS) curates a regularly updated &ldquo;Records Management Toolkit&rdquo; written specifically to assist UK public sector schools in their compliance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000. In a series of articles, Arena&rsquo;s Neil Maude looks at the practical application of the principles described in this toolkit, using Arena&rsquo;s 20+ years of experience in the provision of document management solutions within and outside of the education sector.</p>\r\n<h1>Part 4: Information Disposal</h1>\r\n<p>Information stored by schools has a fairly fixed working life - but relevant data may be required to be held for a considerable period after a particular student has left the school.&nbsp; This can be for all sorts of purposes, including confirmation of attainment and a whole host of legal matters.&nbsp; Obviously, this means that there is a considerable storage burden which is borne by the final school which a given student has attended &ndash; a burden which may persist for many years, in some cases until the former student has reached 30 years of age.</p>\r\n<h2>What the law says</h2>\r\n<p>Two key pieces of legislation come into play with regard to the long term retention of student files (and any other information generated by the school).</p>\r\n<p>Firstly, there is the Data Protection Act (1998), one of the central principles of which is that: <em><span class="font_blue">&ldquo;Information shall not be kept longer than is necessary&rdquo;</span></em></p>\r\n<p>This is a clear call to dispose of information when it is no longer required.&nbsp; Indeed, roughly half of the IRMS Toolkit is an extensive list of how long to keep records of a particular type.</p>\r\n<p>The second relevant piece of legislation is the Freedom of Information Act (2000), which provisions for subject data access requests (SARs) by individuals who wish to see any and all personal information which may be held regarding them.</p>\r\n<p>When considered alongside the longer term storage requirement, these pieces of legislation create a complex picture for information retention and disposal.</p>\r\n<h2>Typical problems surrounding Information Retention and Disposal</h2>\r\n<p>There are obvious issues of space if paper documents are simply stored long term in a file room.&nbsp; It is likely that at some point you will run out of space or &ndash; as in the case of many new-build schools &ndash; there may simply be no space (Arena&rsquo;s Lisa Butterworth has written a separate piece on physical storage in BSF schools, which can be found via the links below).</p>\r\n<p>Regardless of space, simply placing documents in deep storage has 3 key problems:<br /><br />1) <span class="font_blue">Finding a given record</span> &ndash; in an increasingly cluttered store &ndash; is going to be a challenge that no-one wants to tackle. Certainly, this is unlikely to be done quickly and there may be some doubt about whether it could be done comprehensively in the event of a subject data access request (SAR).<br /><br />2) <span class="font_blue">By law, a school cannot retain documents beyond their set retention periods. </span>Older files will need to be removed at some point &ndash; even if this is by whole years of filing at a time. A store full of paper represents a future archiving challenge and there are costs for bulk destruction services.<br /><br />3) <span class="font_blue">Storing documents in this way is not legally compliant </span>with the Data Protection Act. A school adopting this approach will also be hard pressed to prove compliance with Freedom of Information requests. <br /><br />It&rsquo;s worth remembering that the same principles, problems and legislation apply to documents related to pupils, staff, governors and the financial management of the school. Whilst points 1 and 2 may be something that a school could live with, accepting the associated costs, point 3 is a major compliance issue that cannot be ignored.</p>\r\n<h2>Options for managing paper</h2>\r\n<p>A potential solution could be to periodically remove and destroy paper documents in the archive which are no-longer required under retention laws.&nbsp; However, faced with potentially thousands of files containing millions of pages, this is likely to be massively time consuming. <br /><br />For example, if it takes 5 minutes to retrieve a file and manually search through the contents for a particular type of document (a not unreasonable time for a 200+ page file) then repeating the process for a full year group of 500 students would take one person more than a week.&nbsp; This multiplies out for larger schools, manually archiving many years&rsquo; worth of files (remember - all kept until the former student is 25) and taking care to retain or remove file types with varying retention dates.<br /><br />Safeguarding must be a consideration if you choose to manually archive paper files. Sensitive files, for example those pertaining to child protection, must be handled only by authorised employees. (Read more about this in issue 3 of this series &ndash; link below).<br /><br />Also, manual sorting of numerous files can be fraught with human errors, so frequent rest breaks are advisable in the interest of refreshing tired eyes.</p>\r\n<h2>An alternative solution</h2>\r\n<p>Space issues can be addressed by scanning paper files and storing them electronically. Provided you have a system that enables compliance with BSi10008 (a standard and code of practice which ensures the evidential weight of documents stored electronically), you can destroy the original paper documents.<br /><br />A good electronic document management system (EDMS) will apply retention rules to each part of a classification of documents stored in the system. Documents are stored against the appropriate classification (eg; attendance, admission, parental permission forms, SEN statements). The system can then apply rules to dispose of documents or present them for review on a set date &ndash; possibly with reference to pupil specific information, such as date of birth.&nbsp; This approach dramatically reduces the management time associated with retention and completely eliminates the issues associated with large physical paper archives. <br /><br />It&rsquo;s important to note that simple scanning of documents into folders on the school&rsquo;s network, or other internal databases, does not provide adequate functionality to properly manage the retention and disposal of documents. This approach is not compliant with BSi10008 and is often fraught with problems relating to document retrieval and network capacity, making a specialist EDMS a much more practical solution.<br /><br />Of course, success also depends on an appropriate records management policy being enforced within the school, routine information audits (as explained in my previous articles) and matching the outcome of these audits to the retention guidance provided in the IRMS Toolkit. If all of this works as it should, the school can confidently place documents into an electronic store and destroy the original paper documents.</p>\r\n<h2>Things to consider</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Legal admissibility of electronic documents</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Following the destruction of paper records, it is important that a school can rely on electronic information if called upon to provide evidence for a legal case.&nbsp; Assurance on this matter is provided by an EDMS that complies with the guidance in BSi10008, the code of practice for legal admissibility of documents stored electronically. This standard requires that the EDMS has sufficient auditing to demonstrate the provenance of a given document, including who created the document and when.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Freedom of Information (FoI)</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>In the event of a request under FoI, it may be necessary to evidence that a full and complete response has been provided to a subject data access request (SAR).&nbsp; For this reason, the IRMS Toolkit states that the school should maintain a list of records which have been destroyed and how this was authorised. Thereby, the school can protect itself from any allegation of failing to provide the requested information.&nbsp; A good EDMS will automate this.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Hardware and backup media disposal</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>An EDMS will be part of data backup processes, typically meaning that copies of the system will be stored on magnetic backup tapes. For complete compliance, it is necessary that these tapes are subject to a destruction plan; otherwise the school may be retaining information unlawfully.<br /><br />Further, the school should consider disposal processes for obsolete computer equipment. The IRMS Toolkit suggests that hard drives should be &ldquo;dismantled and sanded&rdquo;, which is the ultimate way of ensuring that data cannot be recovered (in fact, Google crush and shred hard drives that are no-longer required).&nbsp; However, this does seem a little excessive and commercial software is available to over-write disks, ensuring that data cannot realistically be recovered from them, after which the disks can be recycled rather than sent to land-fill.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Evolution of the rules</h2>\r\n<p>One final point to note is that retention requirements are evolving. The IRMS toolkit was last updated in May 2012, but already we are seeing customers with emerging needs that post-date this document. This evolution is often stimulated by developments in technology and processes adopted by schools; for example, we recently worked with a school that needed a new document classification and retention rule for biometric data permission slips.</p>\r\n<h2>In Conclusion &hellip;</h2>\r\n<p>Whether you choose to work with paper or electronic files, it is essential to keep on top of the information retention and disposal issue as rules continue to change. A school is required to nominate someone to update its policies and processes in line with changing legislation. In the eyes of the law, the headteacher maintains overall responsibility for the records and information held. Installing an EDMS gives you the support and expertise of an external provider, and a practical, automated means to manage the increasing burden.</p>\r\n<h2>Homework</h2>\r\n<p>How does your school currently manage emails to ensure compliance with the rules and guidelines surrounding records management? What unique problems and challenges do emails present?</p>\r\n<h2>Coming up in Issue #5 &hellip; Email Management</h2>\r\n<p>An email is a formal record, just like any other piece of written communication and is therefore subject to the same obligations, duties of care, controls and legislation. However, emails tend to create their own unique issues when it comes to records management. Our next article will explore these with reference to the guidelines in the email section of the IRMS Toolkit.<br /><br /></p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of  experience in the electronic document management industry, working with  both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/117">BSF Schools and the storage space conundrum</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school">IRMS Records Management Toolkit for Schools Version 4</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">Electronic document management software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../case_studies?tag=Education">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/63_Papers on Rec Mment Education 102013v1_WebsiteVersion.pdf" target="_blank">Complete compliance guide: records management in schools</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Other papers in this series:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">#1: Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">#2: Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">#3: Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/147?tag=Expert+News">#5: Email management</a></li>\r\n<a href="../../../articles/150">\r\n<li>#6: Risk and disaster recovery</li>\r\n</a> \r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-05-29', 'Shreddings_WS.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 122411, '2014-12-11 14:58:19', '', '2013-05-31 12:54:08', '2014-12-11 14:58:19', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'records-management-in-schools-4-information-disposal'),
(137, 'Innovate My School Live in Kent: July 2nd 2013', 'This FREE one-day innovation event brings together some of the industry’s most established thought-leaders and bright up-and-coming future stars to Homewood School in Kent, giving schools an insight into the hottest innovations and vital technological trends and developments that will define education for years to come.', '<p class="introduction">This <strong>FREE one-day innovation event</strong> brings together some of the  industry&rsquo;s most established thought-leaders and bright up-and-coming  future stars to Homewood School in Kent, giving schools an insight into  the hottest innovations and vital technological trends and developments  that will define education for years to come.</p>\r\n<p>Arena''s <strong>John Sheard</strong> will be showcasing our software for electronic document management; <strong>m</strong>store for Education.</p>\r\n<p>There will be an exclusive <strong>live case study</strong>, delivered by <strong>Homewood School''s senior management</strong>, on how they have successfully flipped their classrooms using technology.</p>\r\n<p>Headteachers, deputy headteachers, assistant headteachers, ICT  coordinators, heads of ICT, business managers and curriculum  coordinators from primary and secondary schools are invited to attend. There is even a chance of winning a brand new iPad Mini in a free prize  draw!</p>\r\n<h2>Register for FREE, visit: <br /><a href="http://innovatemyschool-homewoodschool.eventbrite.co.uk" target="_blank">http://innovatemyschool-homewoodschool.eventbrite.co.uk</a></h2>\r\n<h2>Venue and Date:</h2>\r\n<div class="cparam event-location">\r\n<div id="community-event-data-location" class="cdata">Homewood School and Sixth Form Centre,</div>\r\n<div class="cdata">Ashford Rd, Tenterden, TN30 6LT</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="cparam event-created">\r\n<div class="cdata small">2 July 2013, 09:00am - 3.15pm</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h2>Agenda</h2>\r\n<p><br />9:00am<br /><strong>Welcome refreshments</strong><br /><br />9:30am<br /><strong>Introduction / &ldquo;Tech Trends 2013&rdquo;</strong><br /><br />10:00am<br /><strong>Case study: &ldquo;Raising student engagement using technology&rdquo; </strong>by Homewood School &amp; <a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/directory/educational-resources/Internet%20Online%20curriculum%20content/learnerscloud-gcse-resource.html" target="_blank">LearnersCloud</a><br /><br />11:00am<br /><strong>Refreshments</strong><br /><br />11:15am<br /><strong><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/live.html">Innovation speed dating</a> &ndash; 15 minutes with 6 innovative suppliers</strong><br /><br />1:15pm<br /><strong>Networking lunch</strong><br /><br />2:00pm<br /><strong>&ldquo;Innovation on a budget&rdquo;</strong> by <a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/industry-expert-articles/itemlist/user/2390-rachelgordon.html" target="_blank">Rachel Gordon</a><br /><br />2:30pm<br /><strong>Prize Draw for iPad Mini - 1 in 40 chance of winning!</strong><br /><br />2:45pm<br /><strong>&ldquo;Bring Your Own Device - friend or foe?&rdquo;</strong><br /><br />3:15pm<br /><strong>Finish</strong><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p>Places are limited to 40 delegates, with a maximum of 2 per school, so please register ASAP!</p>\r\n<h2>Register for FREE, visit: <br /><a href="http://innovatemyschool-homewoodschool.eventbrite.co.uk" target="_blank">http://innovatemyschool-homewoodschool.eventbrite.co.uk</a></h2>', '2013-05-27', '205_ims_live_logo_300.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 52532, '2013-05-31 13:12:32', 'IMS Live', '2013-05-31 13:12:32', '2014-10-08 11:56:28', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'innovate-my-school-live-in-kent-july-2nd-2013'),
(138, 'Data Hoarding: a ticking time bomb within your organisation?', 'Recent research shows that the amount of information created by organisations is growing at an ever increasing rate and shows no sign of abating.  Neil Maude, General Manager of Arena’s electronic document management division looks at some of the trends, related issues and what you can do to mitigate your business risk.', '<p class="introduction">The amount of information created by organisations is growing at an ever increasing rate and shows no sign of abating.&nbsp; Meanwhile, legislation around information is becoming tougher and more likely to be enforced.&nbsp; Neil Maude, General Manager of Arena&rsquo;s electronic document management division looks at some of the trends, issues and what you can do to mitigate your business risk.</p>\r\n<h2>Documents and Data are on the rise</h2>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Once upon a time, records meant paper documents.&nbsp; They lived in filing cabinets&hellip;&rdquo;.&nbsp; So starts the introduction to a recent Association of Information and Image Management (AIIM) report on document retention practices.&nbsp; This report highlights that we are keeping more and more information, when actually we shouldn&rsquo;t be.</p>\r\n<p>HMRC rules state that we must keep financial records for the current tax year and preceding 6 years.&nbsp; For many organisations, this leads to an annual chucking out in April. As one year is closed off, the oldest goes in the shredder (I <em>hope</em> it doesn&rsquo;t just go in the bin!)&nbsp; This is as reasonably quick process as you know that the box marked, for instance, &ldquo;2009-10&rdquo; can be destroyed.</p>\r\n<p>However, what about documents that have different dates of retention within the same file?&nbsp; HR records are the classic example &ndash; you may have to keep pension records for a very long time, whilst you are <em>supposed</em> to remove disciplinary records quite quickly (retain only for 1 year).&nbsp; This is a much more onerous task &ndash; weeding out particular documents from some files and retaining others.&nbsp; It is easy to foresee that this painful task might be relegated for a &ldquo;rainy day&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Digital data: out of sight, out of mind</strong></h3>\r\n<p class="font_blue"><em>AIIM found that 29% of organisations are simply buying more disks in response to holding increasing amounts of data.&nbsp; </em></p>\r\n<p>The convenience of digitisation can make the problem worse, rather than better. As the AIIM report states, we used to be able to see the problem &ndash; simply running out of office space could be a compelling reason to do something about it.&nbsp; But digital information is somewhat out of sight and even when the disks get full, it&rsquo;s cheap to add more.&nbsp; In fact, the cost of disk storage space has been halving approximately every 14 months for the last 30 years<a href="#_edn1">[i]</a>. Clearly, e-mail and transactional records can be added to this digital data store, on top of the digitisation of paper records.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>Your company data is predicted to grow at least 4-fold over the next 10 years</strong></h3>\r\n<p>But it seems likely that this situation will get worse.&nbsp; The annual IDC &ldquo;Digital Universe&rdquo; survey has been predicting 50x growth in global data storage in the period 2010-2020<a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a>.&nbsp; And whilst most of this is not related to business (consumer data, YouTube etc), that survey does highlight that 10% of this growth will be structured data and 80% will be related to some organisation or another &ndash; so your company data is predicted to grow at least 4-fold over the next 10 years.</p>\r\n<h3 class="font_blue"><strong>34% of the organisations surveyed had no process for information governance </strong><sup>(AIIM)</sup></h3>\r\n<p>These organisations are not only failing to control the growth of data storage - they&rsquo;re not classifying it or controlling security either.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>The tightening grip of the law</h2>\r\n<p>This deluge of data coincides with increasing levels of legislation and regulation.&nbsp; Increasingly, poor data governance and data &ldquo;leakage&rdquo; is being punished &ndash; particularly for organisations which fall under the jurisdiction of the Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office.&nbsp; It is almost certain that the Data Protection Act will be strengthened by European legislation in the near future. Many industries also carry their own specific codes of practice and regulations, such as those laid down by the Financial Services Authority. Each of these pieces of legislation carries the potential for fines or even removal of the perpetrator&rsquo;s ability to continue trading.</p>\r\n<p>In particular, the Data Protection Act &ndash; as it exists currently &ndash; contains some clear guidance as to how long information should be held.&nbsp; One of the central points is that data about an individual should not be kept longer than the minimum time required for the processing of that data (i.e. the purpose for which it is held in the first place).&nbsp; In my opinion, this is an excellent starting place for information governance &ndash; if you don&rsquo;t need it, don&rsquo;t keep it.</p>\r\n<h2>Risky business</h2>\r\n<p>Besides the cost and the regulation aspect, why wouldn&rsquo;t you keep some information? It might come in useful someday, mightn&rsquo;t it?&nbsp; And why does it need to be &ldquo;governed&rdquo;?</p>\r\n<p>Well, there are some risks around keeping everything forever:</p>\r\n<p><strong class="font_blue">If you don&rsquo;t have a decent structure for your data, you will waste time looking for what you think you might have.</strong>&nbsp; Locating a specific document can be painful if you don&rsquo;t have a good policy to govern where you should be able to find it. Add to that some doubt as to whether the document is there at all (ie; whether it actually exists) and it may be a total waste of time.&nbsp; As your data stores become bigger, this will get worse &ndash; so if you&rsquo;re not organising your data, you might as well not have it.</p>\r\n<p><strong class="font_blue">You might be legally compelled to find some information and that might be costly.</strong>&nbsp; For example, if you are defending a court case, you may be instructed to provide all the information related to a particular transaction or individual.&nbsp; If you have a &ldquo;digital landfill&rdquo; (an AIIM term for an unmanaged bucket of data) this could be very expensive to do &ndash; it may include searching all of your hard drives and even backup tapes in order to find comprehensive documents or to prove the non-existence of data.&nbsp; This might require external experts, who don&rsquo;t work cheaply.</p>\r\n<h2>Steps towards risk mitigation<strong>&nbsp;</strong></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Implement a robust information governance policy and processes</strong>. If your processes are compliant with relevant legislation, then you know where your information is and you cannot be required to provide information which your procedures state you no longer have (ie; you can evidence the non-existence of the data).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Invest in technology. </strong>Implementing an electronic document management solution (EDMS), should allow you to classify information and to apply retention rules for different types of information.&nbsp; This can automate your processes for disposal of digital documents.&nbsp; Noting that AIIM research found that more than half of business documents were &ldquo;born digital&rdquo; (i.e. created on computer and then printed), this can be combined with a reduction in print costs (no more printing copies to file).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Consider e-mail. </strong>Tools are available to capture e-mails and subject them to automated classification and retention. This can be an entirely machine-driven process, taking place behind the scenes and independent of the storage of e-mails against the relevant business transactions &ndash; providing peace of mind without additional labour costs.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Look at what remains. </strong>Once the issues of documents and e-mails are resolved, then what remains is likely to be business transactional data (e.g. sales history in your accounts system).&nbsp; This data is likely to be quite minimal and also less likely to contain the most highly regulated &ldquo;personally identifiable&rdquo; information.&nbsp; So it&rsquo;s less of a problem.&nbsp; Depending on your industry you may also have specific data types to manage &ndash; such as phone recordings.&nbsp; But some of the main challenges will have been tamed by the actions above.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Get started now.</strong> If you are not already actively managing your information, chances are that you will have a large data set to tackle and, as we&rsquo;ve seen, it&rsquo;s getting bigger all the time. Unfortunately, retrospective classification of data is difficult and labour intensive. Automation (e.g. pattern based classification) can get you a part of the way, but chances are that you&rsquo;ll end up holding some of your existing data in a part of your system called &ldquo;archive&rdquo; &ndash; at some point you may be able to get rid of it, but only when you&rsquo;re sure that <em>all</em> of the different types of data stored there are no longer required.&nbsp; So the sooner you start, the less painful this problem becomes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol> </ol>\r\n<h2>Conclusions</h2>\r\n<p>My late Grandfather &ndash; an engineer by profession, who lived through the &ldquo;make do and mend&rdquo; years following the great wars, had a clear rule regarding the items he kept in his workshop.&nbsp; &ldquo;Keep everything for 7 years.&nbsp; If it hasn&rsquo;t come in useful, just keep it for another 7&hellip;&rdquo;.&nbsp; This made him a very useful man to know if you needed a 3/8&rdquo; bolt for your lawnmower &ndash; if you could wait long enough for him to find just the right bolt.&nbsp; But it was his workshop and his bolts.&nbsp; Hoarding didn&rsquo;t create any problems, except an ever decreasing space to actually do any work.</p>\r\n<p>But hoarding information in this way isn&rsquo;t viable for a modern business.&nbsp; Even though the problem is out of sight, it&rsquo;s subject to laws and brings unexpected costs.&nbsp; Fortunately there are tools to solve these problems and the sooner you get started, the less it will cost.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>And you never know, being able to locate information quickly may pay back far more than the investment you make to keep it organised.&nbsp; After all, this is why we keep information in the first place.</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of  experience in the electronic document management industry, working with  both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s <a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">EDM business</a>.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div><br /> \r\n<hr size="1" />\r\n<div>\r\n<h6><a href="#_ednref1">[i]</a> <a href="http://www.mkomo.com/cost-per-gigabyte">http://www.mkomo.com/cost-per-gigabyte</a> - disk space per unit cost doubles every 14 months.</h6>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<h6><a href="#_ednref2">[ii]</a> <a href="http://www.emc.com/leadership/programs/digital-universe.htm">http://www.emc.com/leadership/programs/digital-universe.htm</a></h6>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', '2013-05-31', 'iStock_000004287555Medium.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 507303, '2013-05-31 14:31:56', 'paper stacks', '2013-05-31 14:31:58', '2015-08-26 07:40:43', 3, 7, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'data-hoarding-a-ticking-time-bomb-within-your-organisation'),
(139, 'INFOGRAPHIC: Print Control in Pictures', 'An infographic which explains how our print control solution can reduce your bills by 10% and more!', '<p class="introduction">Reduce waste and unnecessary printing. With our tailored print control solution it is proven that you can reduce your bills by 10% and more! The infographic below explains the process and benefits behind Arena Print Control Service.</p>\r\n<h5><em>Click the image below to enlarge it.</em></h5>\r\n<h3>Related Pages:</h3>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/copy-and-print">Print and Copy </a>| <a href="../page/managed-document-service" target="_blank"></a><a href="../../../page/print-the-hidden-costs">The Hidden Costs<em> </em><em>&nbsp;</em></a><em><br /></em></p>\r\n<p><a style="padding-left: 0; background: none;" href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/56_Print control infographic (web).pdf?1371766251" target="_blank"><img src="../../../images/Print-control-infographic-620w.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="620" /></a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/2gJFpbadJOI" width="560" height="315"></iframe></p>', '2013-08-08', 'Infographic.png', 'image/png', 1633608, '2014-02-03 09:27:44', '', '2013-06-07 10:21:22', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 6, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'infographic-print-control-in-pictures'),
(140, 'Capture Plus – mailroom processing speed upgrade', 'The mstore product suite contains a “digital mailroom”.  This set of components allows the fast processing of incoming documents, getting key information the right people in the shortest time.\r\nA recent upgrade has more than quadrupled the throughput capability of the most complex elements of this system, making the Arena product significantly faster than the competition.\r\n', '<p><span class="introduction">The mstore product suite contains a &ldquo;digital mailroom&rdquo;. This set of components allows the fast processing of incoming documents, getting key information the right people in the shortest time</span><br /><br />A recent upgrade has more than quadrupled the throughput capability of the most complex elements of this system, making the Arena product significantly faster than the competition.</p>\r\n<h2>What is digital mailroom?</h2>\r\n<p><br />A digital mailroom is a process of scanning incoming post and routing it onwards within an organisation. This replaces the traditional post-room functions of mail sorting and physical delivery.<br /><br />A digital mailroom process will consist of some or all of the following:<br /><br />1) Opening of the post and sorting for scanning: This may be done by bulk opening of mail and scanning via high-speed stack-fed scanners, or as an integrated process using specialist scanners which include mail opening devices.<br /><br />2) OCR: The captured images are passed through an optical character recognition process (OCR). This reads the content of each page and stores it as a searchable database (a &ldquo;full text index&rdquo;). This is fully automated.<br /><br />3) Classification: An additional stage of automated processing then interprets the content of documents according to business rules &ndash; extracting names, account codes etc. This &ldquo;classification&rdquo; process can incorporate lookups into other corporate data sources (e.g. customer databases) for validation and to allow rules-based decision making.<br /><br />4) Finally, the post item is released to a user or a business process &ndash; this could be the first stage of an <strong>m</strong>store workflow which routes particular types of work to the most relevant parts of the business.</p>\r\n<h2>Benefits of going digital</h2>\r\n<p>The digital mailroom brings several benefits over the traditional process &ndash; not only in improved speed of delivery but also in sending items to those best placed to take action. In addition, the OCR and subsequent stages can be used to consolidate incoming fax and e-mail documents into the same stream as incoming post.</p>\r\n<h2>Capture Plus speed upgrade</h2>\r\n<p>Whilst the OCR and subsequent stages are highly automated, system throughput is a key consideration. Modern scanning equipment will have scanning rates in excess of 200+ images per minute - even allowing for stop/start/refill operations found in real-world processes, we would expect to be producing 50+ images per minute. This means that typical OCR times of around 3 seconds per image (20 pages per minute) will create a bottleneck in the system, as the scanners produce images faster than the OCR &ldquo;engine&rdquo; can process them.<br /><br />Arena&rsquo;s new &ldquo;Capture Plus&rdquo; element can process at up to 90 images per minute<sup>[1]</sup>. This allows the OCR process &ndash; the most time-consuming stage in the mailroom process &ndash; to take place at speeds faster than the scanning input. This removes the processing bottleneck.<br /><br />Further, the Capture Plus engine is designed to allow parallel processing. In scenarios of large quantities of mail &ndash; which may include peak periods &ndash; multiple Capture Plus engines can be used to provide very high throughput capability, constrained only by the availability of computing resources.<br /><br />Finally, the Capture Plus engine can be used simply as a component of an <strong>m</strong>store electronic document management system (EDMS), even without the implementation of digital mailroom. In this scenario, the OCR process is used to provide a searchable index of all documents in the EDMS &ndash; helping to unlock the value of that organisational information.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">More about mstore</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../../case_studies/15" target="_blank">Digital mailroom client: Leeds Building Society</a></p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000; font-size: small;"> </span></p>\r\n<div>\r\n<hr size="1" />\r\n<br /><span style="color: #000000; font-size: small;"> </span>\r\n<div>\r\n<h6><sup><a href="../../../javascripts/admin/tiny_mce/plugins/paste/pasteword.htm?1294418335#_ftnref1"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><span style="color: #0066cc;">[1]</span></span></a></sup><span style="font-size: x-small;"><span style="color: #000000;"><sup> </sup>Based on a sample of &gt;1000 images from a genuine customer scenario and on a representative hardware platform &ndash; also verified independently by customer testing.  Throughput in a specific scenario may vary depending on document content.</span></span></h6>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', '2013-06-14', 'Actions-document-find-icon.png', 'image/png', 9393, '2013-06-14 09:45:33', 'Document find icon', '2013-06-14 07:48:42', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 7, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'capture-plus-–-mailroom-processing-speed-upgrade'),
(141, 'mstore Code-Free Integration - linking software and systems', 'Arena''s mstore software for electronic document management can now link to other applications without any custom integration. This includes bespoke packages and sector specific applications - giving you access to documents stored anywhere across your network, via mstore''s interface.', '<p class="introduction">The Code-Free Integration (CFI) module allows mstore to link to other Windows applications running on the same PC as the mstore client, and to use data held on screen in those applications to be used for searching or indexing within mstore.</p>\r\n<p>The CFI module extends the functionality in the <strong>m</strong>store System Tray module. Template configurations are created for specific screens in the third party application, allowing CFI to detect when the appropriate screen is displayed and where to locate the required information within that screen. The information held on that screen can then be used to launch searches in <strong>m</strong>store or to provide indexing reference data when filing documents in the system.</p>\r\n<h2>The benefits from the use of Code-Free Integration include the following:</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Faster operation - placing documents at your fingertips:</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Because the CFI component is configured for the screens in the third party application, <strong>m</strong>store knows exactly which fields in that application contain relevant data. This removes the need for search terms to be copied to the Windows clipboard (as is the case with the<strong> m</strong>store System Tray module alone), providing a further saving in search time for common operations.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Rich indexing for fast and flexible searches</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Templates for indexing purposes can be configured to capture many elements of indexing data in a single operation, allowing for rich indexing of documents in <strong>m</strong>store (and therefore highly flexible searching for those documents at a later date) without requiring time-consuming and expensive indexing operations.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Dual screen efficiency</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These operations can be used together to great effect on dual-screen systems, where <strong>m</strong>store can be open for document functions on one screen and the third party application can be open on the other screen for normal business activity (eg accounting, ERP).?</p>\r\n<h2>Hassle free implementation</h2>\r\n<p>Importantly, <strong>m</strong>store can be linked to any third party application to gain operational efficiencies, without any need for expensive integration work. It is not necessary to make any change in the third party application  and there is no requirement to provide access to the third party  application database.</p>\r\n<p>This is of particular benefit where the third party application may be a &lsquo;closed&rsquo; application which does not allow access for other systems and integration would not otherwise be possible.</p>', '2013-06-20', 'iStock_000008610202Medium.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 252820, '2013-06-20 08:08:08', '', '2013-06-20 08:04:34', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 7, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'mstore-code-free-integration-linking-software-and-systems'),
(143, 'WIN: Yorkshire County Cricket Goodies Up For Grabs!', 'Meet players and take home a signed shirt! Have your photograph taken with the players as they present you with your prize!', '<p class="introduction">In collaboration with Yorkshire County Cricket Club, we are offering one lucky winner the chance to win a signed shirt and a photo with two current 1st team players.</p>\r\n<h2>How to enter</h2>\r\n<p>To be in with a chance of winning, simply follow the instructions below:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Join our Twitter following <a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank">@ArenaGroup </a>and respond to a competition tweet. Don&rsquo;t forget to include <strong>#YCCC</strong> in your tweet to ensure we spot it.</li>\r\n<p>AND/OR:</p>\r\n<li>Follow our <a href="http://www.linkedin.com/company/253008?trk=tyah" target="_blank">LinkedIN</a> company page and share/like our competition post.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Do both to double your chances of winning!</p>\r\n<p>Once you are following us, keep your eye out for some excellent articles including tips on how to build a winning team.</p>\r\n<h2>Entry deadline</h2>\r\n<p>The competition closes at midday on the <strong>31/08/2013</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>You must be available for the prize presentation on the <strong>16/09/2013</strong> and by entering you agree to our competition <a href="../../assets/stored_documents/original/58_Competition Terms and Conditions_YCCC_July2013v2.pdf" target="_blank">terms and conditions</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Many thanks to Yorkshire County Cricket Club for their support.</p>\r\n<h3>Follow Us on Twitter: <a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank">@ArenaGroup</a></h3>\r\n<h3>Check out our LinkedIN page: <a href="http://www.linkedin.com/company/253008?trk=tyah" target="_blank">LinkedIN</a></h3>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2013-07-25', 'Campaign_Image_7.png', 'image/png', 1010313, '2013-07-23 13:31:07', 'YCCC', '2013-07-16 15:16:17', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 7, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'win-yorkshire-county-cricket-goodies-up-for-grabs');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `headline`, `summary`, `main_content`, `date`, `image_file_name`, `image_content_type`, `image_file_size`, `image_updated_at`, `image_alt`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `created_by`, `updated_by`, `recycled`, `recycled_at`, `display`, `position`, `highlight`, `cached_slug`) VALUES
(144, 'Views from the top: How to Build a Winning Team', 'Comparing the highs and lows in business to those of the sports arena reveals many similarities in the ways success is created and maintained. A special feature from Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, featuring expert contributions Adam Kelly and Elliot Newall of www.thesportinmind.com', '<p class="introduction">A special feature by Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, alongside Adam Kelly and Elliot Newall of www.thesportinmind.com</p>\r\n<h3>By Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, alongside expert insights from Adam Kelly and Elliott Newell of <a href="http://www.thesportinmind.com">www.thesportinmind.com</a>.</h3>\r\n<p>As a huge sports fan from Yorkshire I have to say I was delighted when we recently confirmed our sponsorship of Yorkshire County Cricket Club (YCCC), especially because the deal included an opportunity for friends of Arena to meet some Yorkshire cricketers.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">Often I find myself comparing the highs and lows in business to those of the sports arena (much to the delight of my team!) and I see many similarities in the ways success is created and maintained. I also think there is a lot that the business and sporting worlds can learn from each other.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">So, with this in mind and as part of our activity with YCCC we have called on a few experts to shed light on what makes a strong team, how to keep team members motivated and how to drive positive morale.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">In the first of this series we turn to sports science specialists from www.thesportinmind.com as we address ways to train a winning team. Please let us know what you think of this piece on Twitter <a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank">@ArenaGroup</a> &ndash; we would love to hear about your own experiences too.</p>\r\n<h2 class="FreeForm"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/e97a9dd5d459_219_GetRealSign.jpg?1374666961" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="150" align="right" />Ditch the Training Drills, Get Real</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeForm">Adam Kelly, ex-county cricketer, PhD researcher and Sports Scientist at <a href="http://www.thesportinmind/">www.thesportinmind</a> suggestes a key element of success is training your team for real life scenarios, and that training drills outside of true match conditions are limited in their impact. Sporting professionals identify the correct stimuli quicker and produce faster, more accurate and correct responses. After all, the purpose of training is to improve skill execution and this occurs by recognising the correct stimuli.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">I can see that this makes sense in business. We often send staff on courses to update their skills but the benefit is not delivered until the learned theory is put into practice back in the workplace. Possibly the most successful development we see is from our apprentices. This is undoubtedly because they have real life situations to experience and test their responses on, whereas less hands-on training is about taking in information, digesting it, and hoping it&rsquo;s still there to call upon when you need it.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">Similarly, the above applies to experience. For example; the more we experience a particular business situation, the better our execution and outcomes generally become. This further accentuates the benefit of on the job experience in business.</p>\r\n<h2 class="FreeFormA">There&rsquo;s no &lsquo;I&rsquo; in team</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/8bd30c157e16_220_ruggascrum.jpg?1374668062" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="150" align="right" />Ok, so this is an overused saying but one that is key to developing a successful team. The greater good has to be appreciated by the team as a whole, even on the occasions when decisions don&rsquo;t sit well with individuals. Elliott Newall, an Applied Sports and Performance Psychologist from sportsinmind.com said: &ldquo;A truly cohesive team becomes more than just individuals, and their combined performance equates to more than they could give individually.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">From a business perspective I think this comes back to communicating a strong philosophy and earning the team&rsquo;s commitment. Regular reviews bring attention back to the bigger picture and the results of their combined efforts, encouraging individuals to hit their own targets towards the shared goal.</p>\r\n<h2 class="FreeFormA">Faith or Fact?</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">Newall believes that in order to establish how to best support the team it&rsquo;s important to determine your role clearly. As a supporting influence, are you there to enhance the unwavering faith of the team&rsquo;s capabilities, or are you better off delivering the brutal facts about their present state? Choosing an approach largely depends on the state of play but we must be prepared to do both.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/ddc83092e7fa_221_Cricket_huddle.jpg?1374668298" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="150" align="right" />He also stresses the importance of adapting to individuals, to be able to deal with multiple types of character and bring them together in one direction. A comment I particularly resonated with was; &ldquo;Remember you&rsquo;re trying to get people on the same page, but that a page is a lot bigger than you might realise - they don&rsquo;t have to be on the same word or letter, just part of the same narrative&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">This makes total sense to me as a company director. In good times and bad, a consistent and fair leadership style, combined with an ability to inspire in your team with your own vision, desire and passion to achieve is rewarded time after time by hard work and top class performance.</p>\r\n<h2 class="FreeFormA">Lead to win, even when you&rsquo;re losing</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/19fbc12a9dfc_223_successSign.jpg?1374670263" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="150" align="right" />A question we asked of Newall is whether it&rsquo;s right to change your leadership style in response to poor results. He recommends avoiding knee-jerk reactions - why uproot your tried and tested systems, processes and ingrained ideology, just because things didn&rsquo;t work out this time? Obviously, if your losing streak continues then alarm bells should ring; review your fundamentals, commit to what you believe in and refine your approach.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">From a business perspective, we could relate this to the loss of a sale, which can make you question everything. Is our pricing out? Is our offer wrong? I&rsquo;d say; probably not if a similar approach has previously succeeded. I do believe that both business and sports leadership require a strong faith, some perspective and confidence in the systems and people you are working with.</p>\r\n<h2 class="FreeFormA">Is it all about being the best?</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeForm"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/80328eaf15d2_224_arrows.jpg?1374670430" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="150" align="right" />Often in business and in sport our focus is on &lsquo;being the best&rsquo; and this is instilled in the mentality of team members as the ultimate goal. Newall believes that this attitude is, in essence, dangerous. He says: &ldquo;In my experience, a high performing team is not necessarily obsessed with being the best full stop; rather they are obsessed with being the best they can be and with the processes that lead to being the best. This is far more controllable and as a result, is far more likely to lead to positive types of motivation and more engaged performance behaviours (like being persistent in the face of challenges, being creative and open to new ideas and being co-operative with other teammates).&rdquo; That makes a lot of sense and I think both sports teams and businesses would do well to bring a little more depth to what success really means to them.</p>\r\n<h2 class="FreeForm">With a truly united team anything is possible.<strong>&nbsp;</strong></h2>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/ce9797d1885d_225_TugoWar.jpg?1374670630" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="150" align="right" />At the end of the interview, Newall concludes on the importance of a cohesive team; &ldquo;a strong sense of team identity can often pull a team through a difficult period. It can motivate and inspire as well as increase effort and determination.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">I agree wholeheartedly with this; Arena certainly couldn&rsquo;t be successful without an amazing set of people on board. I must add that building a team of people who are all pulling in the same direction and driven by the same passion is no mean feat. The role of the leadership team is vital to providing continual inspiration and good communication. Relationships inside and outside of the team, and recognition of great performance are also key.</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">We&rsquo;re looking forward to the success of YCCC this season, and will be  calling on their coaching team for some words of wisdom over the next  few weeks. Watch this space!</p>\r\n<h3 class="FreeFormA"><em><span class="font_blue">Many thanks to</span><span class="font_blue"> our expert contributors Adam Kelly and Elliot Newell of <a href="http://www.thesportinmind.com/" target="_blank">www.thesportinmind.com</a>.</span><span class="font_blue"><a href="http://twitter.com/SportinMind" target="_blank"></a></span></em></h3>\r\n<h2 class="FreeFormA">Join the discussion</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA"><a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/83b9192871c0_218_twitter-icon_ws.png?1374664991" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="50" align="left" />Follow us @ArenaGroup</a>: We would love to hear your thoughts on this feature - why not enter our <a href="../../../articles/143" target="_blank">competition</a> to win YCCC goodies too?!</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>About Adrian Fitzpatrick</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/15ad6e0783c2_217_AdrianF_1.jpg?1374664486" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Managing Director<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000</p>\r\n<p>Adrian is one of two remaining founding partners who established Arena in 1991; he leads a team of over 150 people who are working together towards ambitious expansion goals. A keen sportsman, Adrian particularly loves cycling and cricket.</p>\r\n<div><br /><br /></div>', '2013-07-29', 'iStock_000013127738Medium.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 401358, '2013-07-24 11:42:44', 'Winning Team', '2013-07-24 10:47:53', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'views-from-the-top-how-to-build-a-winning-team'),
(145, 'Arena Engineers pick up Kyocera UK Service Trophies', 'From over 300 Kyocera trained Service Engineers in the UK, 15 made it to the UK heats. Two of Arena''s engineers were amongst the three finalists, taking 1st and 3rd places, respectively. We could not be more proud of their achievement.', '<p class="introduction">From over 300 Kyocera trained Service Engineers in the UK, 15 made it to the UK heats. Two of Arena''s engineers were amongst the three finalists, with <strong class="font_blue">John Crookes</strong> taking first place and winning the UK Service Engineer Trophy for 2013, &pound;500 of Amazon vouchers, and a place in the European finals which will be held in October in Germany.</p>\r\n<p>Next, John will compete with engineers from 11 European countries for a Spring 2014 trip to Japan and a tour of the new Kyocera facilities in Vietnam.<br /><br /><strong>Richard Simms</strong>, another Arena Group engineer was placed third this year. Mick Harrison, Group Service Manager, Arena Group said: &ldquo;This is the third year we&rsquo;ve put our technicians forward for the Kyocera Service Trophy and this year&rsquo;s winner, John, was in the Top 10 last year. Arena Group really approves of competitions where a service engineer can pit himself against his peers and be recognised and rewarded. Having two engineers in the UK Top 3 this year is great news for Arena Group, we promote ourselves on customer and service excellence and this award goes a long way to support our claims.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Technical Support Manager John Crookes''s achievement is even more pertinent to Arena in the year of our appointment as a Leeds Apprenticeship Ambassador and scooping the <a href="../121">Employer of the Year</a> award at the 2013 Leeds Apprenticeship Awards. John joined <a href="../../page/apprenticeship-programme">Arena&rsquo;s Apprenticeship   Academy</a> over 10 years ago straight from school after his GCSEs. He now   supports a team of engineers and is still on the road himself.<br /><br />Steve Trutch, Service Support Manager, Kyocera Document Solutions UK Ltd, explains: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re delighted to celebrate with such worthy winners in Manchester. This year we changed the format for the UK stage of our European Service Engineer heats. We had a very tough online quiz and from the results of that we invited the three highest scorers to Manchester. There the three finalists did a written test created by our German competence centre and a second written test created in the UK to test the engineers on their product knowledge, what they knew about KYOCERA and general technical knowledge.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h5>Pictured (L-R): Richard Bethany, KLM Digital (2nd place), Richard Simms, Arena Group (3rd Place), John Crookes, Arena group (1st place)</h5>', '2013-07-19', 'KyoceraUK_ServiceCompetition_2013.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 31110, '2013-07-25 12:57:00', 'Kyocera UK Service Tropy 2013', '2013-07-25 12:53:38', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'arena-engineers-pick-up-kyocera-uk-service-trophies'),
(146, 'A few new coats for Think Children', 'Arena volunteers have been supporting redecoration efforts at a Nottingham based children''s charity.', '<p class="introduction">Arena Group volunteers have been busy with brushes and paint at&nbsp;<a href="http://www.thinkchildren.org.uk" target="_blank">Think Children</a> in Nottingham.</p>\r\n<p>Two teams have visited the charity this year to support refurbishment efforts by painting interior walls at premises in Newark, Nottingham.</p>\r\n<p>The charity''s Strategy Manager, Sarah Habermass, commented; "Without this donation of time and resources small charities such as ours would struggle to update our offices, as sustaining our work with children is always our priority where funds are concerned. They have done a really fantastic job of helping us to refresh the building and maintain a welcoming environment for our staff and visitors. This would have been a costly challenge without Arena&rsquo;s help.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Founded in 1981, Think Children provides early support to vulnerable young children aged between 4 and 11 years, helping them to manage social, emotional or behavioural issues. The charity has developed into a well-respected service, having helped thousands of local young people to successfully overcome difficulties.</p>\r\n<p>Arena Group employees are encouraged to take two annual days away from their usual jobs to support local charity and community projects. MD, Adrian Fitzpatrick, comments; &ldquo;since we founded Arena in 1991 it&rsquo;s been really important to us to give back to our local communities. Our CSR scheme contributes the time and skills of our people to worthy causes and the Think Children project is precisely the type of task that we love to help out with. Our business is growing and we currently employ over 150 people across the Yorkshire, Lancashire and Lincolnshire regions. We are always on the look-out for initiatives that we can support in this expanding area and we continue to welcome requests for support.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<h2>Do You Need Our CSR Support?</h2>\r\n<p>If you are a charity or community group in need of similar assistance, please contact Arena&rsquo;s CSR Coordinator, Debbie Burnell, on 0844 863 8000.</p>\r\n<h5><em>Pictured (L &ndash; R): Lisa Butterworth, Marketing Manager and Delraj Singh, Professional Services Technician both based at Arena&rsquo;s Wakefield office. Andy Hauton, Field Service Technician serving customers in Lincolnshire, based at Arena&rsquo;s Grantham site.</em></h5>', '2013-07-29', 'ThinkChildren3.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 81776, '2013-07-29 10:08:08', 'CSR Think Children', '2013-07-29 10:08:09', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'a-few-new-coats-for-think-children'),
(147, 'Records Management In Schools #5: Email Management', 'E-mail has become the communication channel of choice for most office workers. It’s quick and cheap, with the convenient benefit that the recipient of your message doesn’t have to be available when you are. This doesn’t change the fact that an e-mail is a formal record, just like any other piece of written communication, subject to the same obligations, duties of care, controls and legislation. Neil Maude explores the rules and common approaches towards compliance.', '<p class="introduction">The Information and Records Management Society (IRMS) curates a regularly updated &ldquo;Records Management Toolkit&rdquo; written specifically to assist UK public sector schools in their compliance with the Freedom of Information Act 2000. In a series of articles, Arena&rsquo;s Neil Maude looks at the practical application of the principles described in this toolkit, using Arena&rsquo;s 20+ years of experience in the provision of document management solutions within and outside of the education sector.</p>\r\n<h1>Part 5: Email Management</h1>\r\n<p>E-mail has become the communication tool of choice for most office workers. It&rsquo;s quick and cheap, with the convenient benefit that the recipient of your message doesn&rsquo;t have to be available when you are.<br /><br />But even though e-mail, like a letter or a memo, is just another way to pass on a message, somehow we treat it differently. For starters, e-mails tend to be written using less formal language, and most people spend less time on the layout of an e-mail than they would if sending the same message in a letter.<br /><br />However, this doesn&rsquo;t change the fact that an e-mail is a formal record, just like any other piece of written communication &ndash; and therefore subject to the same obligations, duties of care, controls and legislation. Although the IRMS toolkit has a separate section for e-mail management, in the same way that this series is discussing e-mails specifically, the same principles apply as for any other paper or electronic documentation.<br /><br />In particular, e-mails sent or received by a school are subject to the same Data Protection Act (1998) and Freedom of Information (2000) legislation as any other information held.</p>\r\n<h2>Where e-mail is different</h2>\r\n<p>Besides the less formal use of e-mail, there are some key points which set it apart from other documents and records.</p>\r\n<h3>An e-mail system comes with the innate ability to store material.</h3>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s very easy to create folders, retain sent messages and so on. Without appropriate policies in place, e-mail can rapidly become an unofficial and unmanaged information repository.</p>\r\n<h3>Email volumes can be high and correspondence can involve large groups of people.</h3>\r\n<p>This can make management of email time-consuming, or even stress-inducing.</p>\r\n<h3>The speedy and informal nature of email can lead to unintended consequences.</h3>\r\n<p>There is far more potential for a recipient to misunderstand a quick e-mail note than would be the case with a carefully crafted letter or a phone call.<br /><br />The IRMS toolkit contains a number of techniques for addressing the second and third points. These include appropriate communication standards, awareness that an e-mail is a communication like any other (and so deserves the same respect) and also a number of techniques for handling e-mail volume &ndash; such as only checking e-mail at set times daily.</p>\r\n<h2>Filing e-mail</h2>\r\n<p>Because e-mail records must be treated with the same care as other documents, it is essential that they are filed in the same way and the same retention rules are applied. In practice, this requires both a clear policy for e-mail storage and the tools to do the job efficiently.<br /><br />The IRMS Toolkit suggests two options: print it out or save it as an electronic file. Both of these methods avoid the e-mail system being used as a long term store, which is sensible, but each presents problems.</p>\r\n<h2>Printing</h2>\r\n<p>Obviously, printing costs money and e-mail is no exception &ndash; doubly so when you then get a reply and have to print that e-mail as well. We often undertake archive conversion projects (digitising an archive) where up to half of the documentation is made up of printed e-mails &ndash; documents which were digital to start with.<br /><br />A further hidden cost is that e-mails typically include some colour (signature lines, URLs, addresses) and if you&rsquo;re not careful this can lead to e-mails being printed as colour documents &ndash; even more expensive. Regardless of this, printing should really only be considered if you have to file emails in existing paper files.</p>\r\n<h2>Electronic filing</h2>\r\n<p>The second alternative suggested by the IRMS is to save e-mails to disk, outside of the e-mail system, using the &lsquo;Save As&rsquo; function. This has the added benefit that the e-mail will be held together with any attachments &ndash; as it should be, to maintain a complete record of the discussion.<br /><br />However, this also has a drawback; saving files in the standard ''.msg'' format (if you use Microsoft Outlook) means that you&rsquo;ll need Outlook to open those files again in the future. This is likely to be fine for a few years but probably not if the record has to be kept for many years &ndash; such as until the former pupil has reached 25 or 30 years of age. When capturing the electronic archives of organisations, we have encountered several cases of obsolete file types used with older programs such as WordPerfect (anyone remember it?) which dates back as far as the mid-1990s.</p>\r\n<h2>The alternative</h2>\r\n<p>A better solution is to make use of an appropriate Electronic Document Management System (EDMS). A good system will provide the following features which are really key to good e-mail management:</p>\r\n<h3>1. Efficient tools for storing e-mails</h3>\r\n<p>Ideally buttons within the e-mail client or quick links from the computer desktop that enable a user to file an email in the correct place within the EDMS very quickly; i.e.; with minimal mouse clicks and typing.</p>\r\n<h3>2. Maintaining integrity of the record</h3>\r\n<p>The e-mail and any attachments should be held together.</p>\r\n<h3>3. Management of file formats</h3>\r\n<p>Emails are converted to a long-term archive format, such as PDF/A standard. This will avoid creating a store of information which you can&rsquo;t read in the future.<br /><br />And of course, use of an EDMS will bring the same benefits as those enjoyed for scanned information. A proper document classification policy allows retention rules to be implemented and the e-mail is managed for the whole of its relevant lifecycle. In this way, e-mails regarding students are managed according to the rules for that type of content, as are financial records and all the other types of record created by the school.<br /><br />Whichever option you choose, it&rsquo;s crucial to enforce a robust <a href="../113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">records management policy</a>, to ensure that emails are treated in the same way as other document types, and filed outside of the personal inboxes of your employees.</p>\r\n<h2>Monitoring</h2>\r\n<p>Because e-mail is an IT application, it is possible to monitor how it is being used and even to automatically create an indexed copy of all e-mail traffic to allow searching and analysis. Doing this provides the school with the capability to protect against a number of risks.<br /><br />However, it is essential to clearly document how this monitoring will be done and how the information may be used, in order to enable the school to evidence that it has the consent of staff, students and everyone else using the e-mail system. This can be a sensitive subject which introduces an associated &lsquo;Big Brother&rsquo; perception. However, it is the best practice and there is an excellent guide from the Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office (ICO) as to how to do this in an appropriate and compliant manner.<br /><br />Another potential use of e-mail monitoring is to tackle cyber-bullying. With a captured archive of e-mail, it is a simple matter to create a searchable text-index of all the e-mails which were sent or received by your student e-mail server. This archive can then be interrogated for key phrases or messages between particular individuals.</p>\r\n<h2>Three ways to reduce e-mail dependence</h2>\r\n<p>As mentioned earlier, large amounts of e-mail (like the 80-100 items I receive on an average day) can be a source of stress. I&rsquo;d like to share a few simple tactics I&rsquo;ve used to manage e-mail in an efficient way.</p>\r\n<h3>1. E-mail is an &ldquo;asynchronous&rdquo; tool</h3>\r\n<p>There is no need to respond immediately. Turn off or ignore the pop-up icons and deal with your e-mails at a few set times each day. Interruptions are terrible for productivity, so don&rsquo;t create them by reading each e-mail as it arrives. If there is something really vital, the sender should really be phoning you &ndash; I&rsquo;ve put this to the test and the &ldquo;red exclamation&rdquo; e-mails are always followed up by a phone call if they really are that urgent! But do set aside some time to respond to e-mail in a timely fashion.</p>\r\n<h3>2. Consider if e-mail is the best form of communication.</h3>\r\n<p>Would a phone call be better? Or even a face-to-face meeting? Often, one conversation can take the place of several e-mails.</p>\r\n<h3>3. When sending an e-mail, clarify your preferred response.</h3>\r\n<p>At Arena we have a standard of starting the subject line with &ldquo;Action&rdquo;, &ldquo;Feedback&rdquo;, &ldquo;Info&rdquo; or &ldquo;Recreational&rdquo;, which gives a clear steer as to the expected next step.<br /><br />However, please do consider your organisational culture before following this guidance!</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of  experience in the electronic document management industry, working with  both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school">IRMS Records Management Toolkit for Schools Version 4</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">Document management software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../case_studies?tag=Education">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/63_Papers on Rec Mment Education 102013v1_WebsiteVersion.pdf" target="_blank">Complete compliance guide: records management in schools</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Other papers in this series:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">#1: Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">#2: Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">#3: Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/136">#4: Information disposal</a></li>\r\n<a href="../../../articles/150">\r\n<li>#6: Risk and disaster recovery</li>\r\n</a> \r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-08-01', 'iStock_000018520140Medium.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 341491, '2013-07-30 15:04:00', 'Email Button', '2013-07-30 15:02:33', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'records-management-in-schools-5-email-management'),
(148, 'Views from the top: Keeping Your Team Motivated', 'In the second of our series, Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, and former England cricketer and Yorkshire captain Antony McGrath muse on the comparisons that can be drawn between sports and business teams.', '<p class="introduction">In the second feature of our series, Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, and former England cricketer and retired Yorkshire CCC captain Antony McGrath muse on the comparisons that can be drawn between sports and business teams.</p>\r\n<h3>By Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, alongside comments from former England cricketer and Yorkshire captain Antony McGrath, now retired.<strong><br /></strong></h3>\r\n<p>This week we chatted to former England cricketer and retired Yorkshire County Cricket Club captain <strong><a href="http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/4/4532/4532.html" target="_blank">Anthony McGrath</a></strong> (pictured) who shares his thoughts on how to keep a team motivated, in good times and bad.</p>\r\n<p><img style="float: right;" src="../../../assets/articles/148/contained_images/d31e3bba1022_229_anthony_mcgrath.jpg?1376296948" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" />Join our Twitter discussion <a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup">@ArenaGroup</a> using <strong>#YCCC</strong> &ndash; we would love to hear about your own experiences too - enter our <a href="../../../articles/143" target="_blank">competition</a> to win YCCC goodies!</p>\r\n<h2>Teaming up Individuals</h2>\r\n<p>In business and sport alike, a positive mentality is vital throughout a team but ensuring everyone is on the same wavelength isn&rsquo;t as simple as it may seem. Whilst a team is united by a common cause, ultimately everyone, as an individual, thinks differently to a certain degree. Renowned sportsman, Anthony McGrath explains how important it is to recognise this.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I think the biggest mistake you can make is to treat everyone in the same way&rdquo;, said Anthony. As a previous captain of the Yorkshire team, he&rsquo;s seen the power of effective communication, which leads to team members delivering to their full potential.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s important to recognise that people have different drivers - different triggers that help them perform. Some players are driven by receiving praise, some by admiration from their colleagues, some by financial gain and others by trophies and awards. As a captain it&rsquo;s key to recognise this and appreciate that everyone&rsquo;s input is individual, that each person needs to be motivated in a way they will respond to, in order to make the team work effectively overall. A &lsquo;one size fits all&rsquo; approach is destined to fail so commitment to treating team members as individuals is absolutely crucial.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>This is of course also true in business. Whilst everyone is working towards achieving the goals of our 5 year plan at Arena, each person in the business has a different role to play in that and naturally each person also has their own individual drivers for being a part of it. What&rsquo;s important to me is that we unite as a team and keep each other focused, whatever our personal motivations may be.</p>\r\n<h2>Praise for Progress</h2>\r\n<p>We all know that it makes sense to give praise when great achievements have been made - but how often do we offer praise for the little things? McGrath says; &ldquo;as a leader it is very important to give praise and feedback on a regular basis, to reinforce a positive mentality and maintain motivation.&rdquo; He also believes this helps to keep people driven towards their ultimate goal, as it focuses the mind on being able to achieve success through continuing to perform well.</p>\r\n<p>At Arena we work hard on this and sometimes just a manager&rsquo;s effort to say a quiet thank you goes a very long way in terms of motivation. Other ways include sharing of internal news bulletins to acknowledge and encourage best practice across the business; and team celebrations of success that take the form of a mention in a meeting or a special event. I&rsquo;d agree that praise shown in a variety of ways certainly contributes towards team motivation.</p>\r\n<h2>Cut the Criticism</h2>\r\n<p>This is obviously all well and good when things are going well, but what about when things take a downward turn...?</p>\r\n<p>McGrath&rsquo;s advice on this is clear - it&rsquo;s still about unity and teamwork and as a leader you must be seen to support the whole team, even if it appears that there is an individual with whom you could lay some blame; &ldquo;if something needs to be addressed with an individual team member then do it privately. Never, ever single someone out publicly with a criticism&rdquo;, he says.</p>\r\n<p>He also suggests laying down some non-negotiable rules for the team to follow, which will result in the team pulling together and being motivated as one. &ldquo;By taking time out to put these rules into action, players get a feeling of belonging, trust and appreciation from their management.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>This is certainly similar in business and a set of rules means everyone works to the same standards and expectations are clear and understood.</p>\r\n<p>If the team as a whole is under performing this is a different matter, and McGrath then advises an approach based on reviewing and refining. &ldquo;No team can perform flawlessly 100% of the time. There will also be times when things don&rsquo;t go to plan due to factors out of your control. This is when strong belief comes in and you need that unity and focus on the end goal to pick things up&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<h2>Keeping your head up</h2>\r\n<p>In times of trouble a strong leader remains consistent with actions, words and behaviours whilst always appearing calm and collected. McGrath&rsquo;s sporting experience re-iterates this. &ldquo;If you become too emotional you can make a rash decision or say something you will later regret. Portraying a calm exterior even when inside you feel completely different shows a rational approach&nbsp;to your team. This will help them stay motivated and maintain their faith that everything will work out in the end&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Anthony believes that it&rsquo;s also not always necessary to dissect every detail when things go wrong. &ldquo;After a loss, if you have the right environment, players will analyse themselves and learn from the bad performance. Dedicated team members will perform their own mini reviews and make their own conclusions as to how they can improve. Guide but don&rsquo;t push too much, as change led by the team can be more powerful than change led from the top.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>I am a true believer in keeping a positive attitude in business when things aren&rsquo;t going your way. This is not easy but when you&rsquo;re in a team, people do look to the top for inspiration, guidance and reassurance that things are on track. I recognise the commitment needed from the management team; if we appear frustrated then why should anyone else feel different?</p>\r\n<h2>The Power of the Team Talk</h2>\r\n<p>Sometimes the only thing for it is a strong team talk to boost morale.</p>\r\n<p>McGrath advises to never end things on a negative note. &ldquo;You have to provide an outcome, a way out, a positive motivator for the team to focus on&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>In business I believe the same holds true. I&rsquo;ve found that the best approach to take with a motivational team talk is to be honest, speak from the heart and say something people can really identify with. This way you&rsquo;re not trying to railroad staff with a &lsquo;speech&rsquo; as such, but you&rsquo;re engaging them with real feelings and emotions.</p>\r\n<p>McGrath recalls his favourite motivational team talk when he played for Yorkshire County Cricket Club, when the team were on the brink of winning the Championship for the first time since 1968:</p>\r\n<h3><em><span class="font_blue">"The 11 guys in this room are about to go into the history books, you represent&nbsp;everything Yorkshire cricket stands for. Anyone who loves Yorkshire cricket would give anything to swap places with you now. We have been the best team all season because we have stuck to our processes and believed in each other. If we do the same today no one can deny us. Express yourselves, show how good you are and look out for each other. Let&rsquo;s go!"</span></em></h3>\r\n<p>For McGrath, this speech worked as it summed up the mood of the team and reaffirmed the belief that management had in them. Here could lie the secret of tapping into true motivational management - making your team feel valued and a part of something special. I can&rsquo;t argue with that.</p>\r\n<p>Many thanks to Anthony McGrath for his insights, it&rsquo;s great to hear from a Yorkshire sporting legend. We&rsquo;re looking forward to the success of YCCC this season &ndash; and waiting in anticipation to see whether they pull another great championship win out of the bag!</p>\r\n<h3 class="FreeFormA"><em><span class="font_blue">Many thanks to</span><span class="font_blue"> our expert contributor Anthony McGrath.&nbsp;</span><span class="font_blue"><a href="http://twitter.com/SportinMind" target="_blank"></a></span></em></h3>\r\n<h2 class="FreeFormA">Join the discussion</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA"><a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/83b9192871c0_218_twitter-icon_ws.png?1374664991" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="50" align="left" />Follow us @ArenaGroup</a>: We would love to hear your thoughts on this feature - why not enter our <a href="../../../articles/143" target="_blank">competition</a> to win YCCC goodies too?!</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>About Adrian Fitzpatrick</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/15ad6e0783c2_217_AdrianF_1.jpg?1374664486" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Managing Director<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000</p>\r\n<p>Adrian is one of two remaining founding partners who established Arena in 1991; he leads a team of over 150 people who are working together towards ambitious expansion goals. A keen sportsman, Adrian particularly loves cycling and cricket.</p>\r\n<div><br /><br /></div>', '2013-08-07', 'motivation_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 89632, '2014-12-11 17:23:55', '', '2013-08-06 14:22:07', '2014-12-11 17:23:56', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'views-from-the-top-keeping-your-team-motivated'),
(149, 'VIDEO > Records Management in Schools: Compliance', 'A recording of our recent webinar.  Based on Arena’s popular series of papers on records management in UK schools. Practical advice on how to comply with increasingly stringent legislation.', '<p class="introduction">[VIDEO]: Based on <a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/industry-expert-articles/itemlist/user/3169-neilmaude.html" target="_blank">Arena&rsquo;s popular series of papers on records management in UK schools</a>. Practical advice on how to comply with increasingly stringent legislation.</p>\r\n<p>(approx. running time: 30 minutes)</p>\r\n<p>Our records management expert, <strong>Neil Maude</strong>, chats to Arena&rsquo;s <strong>Mike Starkings</strong> about the current rules and regulations surrounding document management in UK schools.</p>\r\n<p>This video is a recording of a recent webinar. The session provided  an end-to-end, whistle-stop guide from creating a  clear records  management policy through information access and security  to compliant  data disposal.</p>\r\n<p><iframe src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/R9gtXEsVSAI" width="560" height="315"></iframe></p>\r\n<h2>Can you afford to miss it?<em><br /></em></h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Do you have a clear and regularly updated records&nbsp;management policy?</li>\r\n<li>Are your security measures compliant with BS10008?</li>\r\n<li>Do you have a crisis recovery plan?</li>\r\n<li>Are you compliant with FOI requests and SDRs?</li>\r\n<li>Are you aware of the penalties for non-compliance?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school" target="_blank">IRMS Records Management Toolkit for Schools v.4</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/industry-expert-articles/itemlist/user/3169-neilmaude.html" target="_blank">Insight: Neil Maude on records management in schools</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/124?tag=Events" target="_blank">VIDEO: Shrinking the Paper Mountain</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank">Electronic document management software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../case_studies?tag=Education" target="_blank">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Related insight articles:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/industry-expert-articles/item/581-records-management-in-schools-information-disposal.html" target="_blank">Information disposal</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/industry-expert-articles/item/616-records-management-in-schools-e-mails.html" target="_blank">Email management</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/industry-expert-articles/item/653-records-management-in-schools-risk-and-disaster-recovery.html" target="_blank">Risk and disaster recovery</a> </li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/117" target="_blank">BSF Schools and the storage space conundrum</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-08-08', 'Kula_Webinar.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 175719, '2013-08-08 11:53:35', '', '2013-08-08 08:40:34', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'video-records-management-in-schools-compliance');
