(150, 'Records Management in Schools #6: Risk and disaster recovery ', 'If you hold personal data you have an obligation to keep it secure from unauthorised access and processing alongside accidental loss, damage to, or destruction of personal data. Arena’s Neil Maude looks at mitigating the risk and what to do when the worst happens.', '<p class="introduction">The IRMS curates a regularly updated toolkit to assist UK public sector schools in their compliance with the Freedom of Information Act (2000).</p>\r\n<p class="introduction">Arena Group''s Neil Maude has written for us a series of articles looking at the practical application of its key principles. In Part 6, Neil looks at disaster recovery planning and risk mitigation.</p>\r\n<h1>Part 6: Risk and Disaster Recovery</h1>\r\n<p>The 7th principle of the Data Protection Act (1998) is quite clear on the obligations with regard to data security and risk: "Appropriate technical and organisational measures shall be taken against unauthorized or unlawful processing of personal data and against accidental loss or destruction of, or damage to, personal data."</p>\r\n<p>The IRMS Toolkit makes the very valid point that: "In the event of a major incident, your school should be able to stay open and will at least have access to its key administrative and teaching records."<br /><br />Clearly, compliance with this legislation requires on-going management of the risks to your information stores and how these risks will be mitigated.<br /><br />These obligations can be covered by appropriate use of technology, but only once the underlying business needs have been appraised. A first step is an information audit, as described in a previous article in this series, upon which risk assessments and mitigation plans can be created.</p>\r\n<h2>Risk assessment</h2>\r\n<h2>Step 1: Three important questions<br /><br /></h2>\r\n<div>A good place to start with risk analysis is to look at each type of information identified in the information audit with three questions in mind:<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h3>1. Event: What might happen to this information?</h3>\r\n<div>Think about how the information is stored. Could it be lost or destroyed in its current form (is paper at risk of fire or flood; could electronic files be lost if the server crashes)? How might the information ''leak'' out of the organisation (theft, USB stick loss, unauthorised disclosure, e-mail to the wrong person)? This question should identify a number of risks against each specific piece of information.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h3>2. Probability: How likely is this to actually happen?</h3>\r\n<div>For example, a fire is a fairly unlikely risk. However, if you store data on USB disks, it is fairly likely that someone will lose one.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h3>3. Impact: What would be the impact?</h3>\r\n<div>Some risks have bigger impacts than others. If you can&rsquo;t locate a permission slip, then you can ask for another to be created &ndash; a low impact event. However, if someone has left an SEN file on the bus, that&rsquo;s a serious problem.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h2>Step 2: Plot your risk priorities</h2>\r\n<div><br /><br />When you have this information, categorise each event by its probability and impact (low, medium or high) and plot each event onto a grid with probability on the x-axis and impact on the y-axis. Key issues will appear in the top-right, giving you a good appreciation of your risk priorities and where to start.<br />&nbsp;<br />Take care not to neglect events which may be unlikely but would have a very serious impact; these &ldquo;Black Swan&rdquo; events will still need some thought, prevention and possibly even a coping strategy.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h2>Step 3: Mitigation plans</h2>\r\n<div><br /><br />The next step is to consider risk mitigation &ndash; what can you do about some of these risks to reduce their impact or remove them altogether?<br /><br />The IRMS toolkit describes a number of mitigations to general IT risks including off-site and secure backups, password policies and having no fragile or sensitive data stored on local PCs or laptops. This is all essential.<br /><br />The Toolkit also discusses the risks associated with loss of paper documents in a flood or fire and the benefits of metal cabinets over open shelves, as well as the need for auditing of paper file locations and clear desk policies. These are, again, all essential if using paper files &ndash; but these steps only mitigate the risks, rather than removing them.<br /><br />The application of an appropriate Electronic Document Management System (EDMS) can remove the risks to physical paperwork, by removing it, and placing the information archive into the protection of IT mitigation procedures. If this is done, information stores such as pupil files are covered by the same processes and policies as any other IT backup &ndash; greatly reducing risks and saving time by covering a multitude of risks together. An EDMS can also provide access security and auditing, thereby removing many information leakage risks.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h2>Continuity planning</h2>\r\n<div><br /><br />Having undertaken a risk management exercise, determined impacts and mitigated as much as possible, the next step is to compile a list of actions which will be taken should the worst happen &ndash; and in what timeframes.<br /><br />Again, this builds on the information audit and the key question is how quickly does each classification of information need to be made available again? Once this is understood, the order of restoring IT systems (typically) can be defined &ndash; and then this should be subject to some real-world thinking as to whether it is practical. For example, if a file server contains information which is required to be made available within 24 hours of a server failure, can the backup be restored to a spare server or does a new server need to be procured?<br /><br />If a new server is required &ndash; maybe the spare server is also likely to be destroyed? &ndash; then there needs to be a plan for how this will be achieved to meet the overall elapsed time requirement.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h2>Test, test and test again&hellip;</h2>\r\n<div><br /><br />A continuity plan is something you hope never to need. But it must be tested &ndash; and that testing should be regularly repeated. Without testing, you have no assurance that the plan is complete, actionable and up-to-date. This can be a painful and time-consuming process but it&rsquo;s just not possible to write a plan which is error-free, and you don&rsquo;t want to meet the problems when you are already in the midst of a crisis.<br /><br /></div>\r\n<h2>When the worst happens</h2>\r\n<div><br /><br />Sadly, we have seen cases where large amounts of paper documents have been lost. Examples include fires destroying buildings used for information storage, floods wiping out basement archives and even leaky roofs causing irreparable damage. We&rsquo;ve also seen a surprising number of servers lost without an up-to-date backup being available. In most of these cases, a major impact has been suffered because a thorough risk assessment and/or regular process checking were not done. Having said this, some events were acknowledged as low-probability/high-impact risks against which the organisation had taken a conscious and calculated risk.<br /><br />The IRMS toolkit states that an individual should be appointed as the "named member of staff to liaise with the Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office in the event that a major information breach needs to be reported". We hope that by following these guidelines, and by using appropriate technology, this named person will have no need to speak to the ICO!</div>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of  experience in the electronic document management industry, working with  both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.irms.org.uk/resources/information-guides/199-rm-toolkit-for-school">IRMS Records Management Toolkit for Schools Version 4</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">Document management software from Arena Group</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../case_studies?tag=Education">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../assets/stored_documents/original/63_Papers on Rec Mment Education 102013v1_WebsiteVersion.pdf" target="_blank">Complete compliance guide: records management in schools</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Other papers in this series:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">#1: Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">#2: Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">#3: Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/136">#4: Information Disposal</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/147?tag=Expert+News">#5: Email Management</a></li>\r\n</ul>', '2013-08-26', 'emergencyStop_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 82927, '2014-12-11 15:43:22', '', '2013-08-12 09:42:14', '2014-12-11 15:43:22', 7, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'records-management-in-schools-6-risk-and-disaster-recovery'),
(151, 'Views from The Top: Coping With Change', 'The third article of our series compares the similarities between the worlds of sport and business in terms of the way we manage change. A special feature by Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, featuring insights from Adam Kelly of www.thesportinmind.com and Kyle McDonald of Competitive Will Mental Training.', '<p class="introduction">The third article of our series looks to sports science gurus once again as we consider how to cope with change.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>By Adrian Fitzpatrick, MD of Arena Group, alongside comments from Adam Kelly of <a href="http://www.thesportinmind.com" target="_blank">www.thesportinmind.com</a> and Kyle McDonald of <a href="http://www.competitivewill.com/Pages/default.aspx" target="_blank">Competitive Will Performance Consulting</a>.</h3>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">In order to effectively cope with change in business we can learn a lot from the sporting world as the two hold many similarities. Both athletes and business execs adopt similar approaches towards creating a positive environment - here we share a few insights.</p>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Please share your views with us by means of our Twitter page <a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank">@ArenaGroup</a>, as we would love to hear about your own experiences too.</p>\r\n<h2 class="BodyText1">See change as a process - not an event</h2>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Adam Kelly, ex-county cricketer, PhD researcher and Sports Scientist at <span class="font_blue">www.thesportinmind.com</span> suggests that in a sports person&rsquo;s career they will come into contact with a variety of pressure situations. &ldquo;These can range from personal worries and anxieties, to situational triggers such as a particularly tough or intimidating opponent&rdquo;. Coping with the stress is vital to overall performance and it&rsquo;s helpful to view these changes as opportunities to develop, rather than major life events. The ability to cope drastically increases with this different mindset.</p>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">This rings particularly true in the business world, where viewing workplace changes as opportunities for our own progression turns them into a welcome challenge. A positive mind will see a way to adapt skills, minimise risks and sustain business performance. This is certainly worth remembering next time you face changes to your budgets, workload, management or job role.</p>\r\n<h2 class="BodyText1">Avoid complacency</h2>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Kyle McDonald, owner of <span class="font_blue">Competitive Will Performance Coaching</span>, explains; &ldquo;we can give many examples of teams or individuals in the sporting world embracing change. For example, Rory McIlroy&rsquo;s&nbsp; move to Nike for equipment, or the decision of Tiger Woods to employ a new coach. In each case these changes were consciously made in order to stay ahead of the game.&rdquo;&nbsp; In simple terms we should always remain on the look-out for changes towards improvement &ndash; even if those changes appear daunting.&nbsp; Kyle adds; &ldquo;strong and committed athletes know the value of change and that in time they will be rewarded. Having said this though, it&rsquo;s important to remember than it takes time to adjust to change and recover success &ndash; it doesn&rsquo;t happen overnight.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Again this draws a variety of parallels with business, where a conscious, logical and proactive attitude towards change beats burying our heads in the sand for fear of rocking the boat. Obviously, there is no value in making change for change&rsquo;s sake but positive reflection and challenging the way things are done can certainly produce new ideas and improve results.</p>\r\n<h2 class="BodyText1">Communicate clearly</h2>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Kelly comments on the huge importance of two-way communication to the overall success of an athlete. &ldquo;In order to effectively cope with high amounts of stress, a strong communicative environment needs to be established through which to express concerns and receive positive feedback. We must create an environment which is supportive and allows the athlete to flourish.&rdquo; Communication and quick action to fix any issues allows us to minimise stress, earn trust and cope productively. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s important to remember that the communication needs to work both ways &ndash; coaches who listen to their teams and act on feedback will earn the trust to make positive changes.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">From a business perspective we can easily relate this to the office environment. &nbsp;Successful communication is fundamental to the creation of trust, which is crucial for a stress free workplace. Much like a sports environment, a workplace needs to be open and supportive, to embrace change and develop talent. Communication also allows office changes and stresses to be dealt with immediately, removing the threat of any negativity brewing. The sharing of rationale, vision, ideas and ultimately business results, all make for a happy and motivated team. I can most definitely vouch for this and believe our strength in this area is what has enabled our business to grow at such a rapid pace without jeopardizing employee engagement.</p>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Most vitally, it could be suggested that much like in the sporting world, effective communication allows for a greater sense of team spirit, allowing all within the work environment to not only hit individual goals but also work effectively towards shared targets.</p>\r\n<h2 class="BodyText1">Make a change to see a change</h2>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Kelly explains that understanding the need to develop and change is a vital characteristic for any athlete, and one that enables them to remove unnecessary stressors. &ldquo;In short, if an athlete takes the time to listen to their coach, understand and act upon the feedback they are given, they stand a chance of making real improvement. Athletes must take on board feedback, in order to remain at the top of their game and stand shoulder to shoulder with competitors.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Similarly, the above applies to business &ndash; we must always look for the gaps in our performance in order to achieve greater results. We can go further and say that sometimes we need to try something different in order to break a negative cycle &ndash; how can we expect a different result, if we don&rsquo;t change our behaviour?&nbsp; Actively seeking ways to improve and testing new ideas will provide a welcome challenge but leads to improvement - which naturally removes stress.</p>\r\n<p class="BodyText1">Finally, being able to share success with your team is a very rewarding feeling, and I cannot advocate enough the importance of making people feel valued, especially in times of stress.</p>\r\n<h3 class="BodyText1"><em class="font_blue">Many thanks to our contributors, Adam Kelly of www.thesportinmind.com and Kyle McDonald of Competitive Will Performance Consulting. </em></h3>\r\n<h2 class="FreeFormA">Join the discussion</h2>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA"><a href="http://twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank"><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/83b9192871c0_218_twitter-icon_ws.png?1374664991" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="50" align="left" />Follow us @ArenaGroup</a>: We would love to hear your thoughts on this feature - why not enter our <a href="../../../articles/143" target="_blank">competition</a> to win YCCC goodies too?!</p>\r\n<p class="FreeFormA">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>About Adrian Fitzpatrick</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/144/contained_images/15ad6e0783c2_217_AdrianF_1.jpg?1374664486" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Managing Director<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000</p>\r\n<p>Adrian is one of two remaining founding partners who established Arena in 1991; he leads a team of over 150 people who are working together towards ambitious expansion goals. A keen sportsman, Adrian particularly loves cycling and cricket.</p>\r\n<div><br /><br /></div>', '2013-08-21', 'changes_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 110334, '2014-12-11 15:57:27', '', '2013-08-21 10:52:23', '2014-12-11 15:57:27', 3, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'views-from-the-top-coping-with-change'),
(152, 'Visit us at the Academies Show - Birmingham ', 'Arena will be at the Academies Show on the 26th of November 2014. Visit us on stand #442, enter our prize draw and see what we can do for you.', '<p class="introduction">On November 26th we will be showcasing our full portfolio of products and services on <strong>stand #442</strong>. This includes technologies to help you implement:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li> Increased compliance </li>\r\n<li>Safeguarding of information </li>\r\n<li>Record keeping best practice </li>\r\n<li>Increased storage space </li>\r\n<li>Reduced print and copy costs</li>\r\n<li>Print and copy transparency and control</li>\r\n<li>Less wasteful and unnecessary printing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Arena has over 20 years of experience in document management, and we work with over 700 education sector clients. Our expertise is already helping academies, schools, colleges and other institutions nationwide to overcome unique sector issues, reduce costs and increase efficiency.</p>\r\n<p>Visit us on <strong><span class="font_blue">stand #442</span></strong> where we will be hosting a <strong>free prize draw</strong> and showcasing the latest technologies in <a href="../../../page/copy-and-print" target="_blank">print, copy</a> and <a href="../../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank">electronic document management</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Ask about our <a href="../../../page/print-the-hidden-costs" target="_blank">Managed Print Service</a> and print control systems that can help you take the hassle and cost out of print and copy whilst reducing wasteful and unnecessary printing.</p>\r\n<p>Legislation is particularly stringent in education, in particular  relating to records governance. Increasingly rigorous  regulation creates new responsibilities  for legal compliance. We will be demonstrating Arena''s own software for electronic document and records management (EDRMS), <strong></strong><a href="../../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank"><strong>m</strong>store for Education</a>, which is already enabling schools across the country to address this issue, liberate storage space and operate more efficiently.</p>\r\n<p>The Academies Show will provide prospective and new academies with a  wealth of relevant, valuable insights, discussions and practical advice. A high level conference with seminar sessions, exhibition, networking  areas and meetings with experts <strong><em>all free of charge</em></strong>. Don''t miss out, register today!</p>\r\n<h2>Special prize draw - stand #442.</h2>\r\n<p>Delegates are invited to visit our stand to leave a business card or complete a prize draw entry form to be in with a chance of winning. We will be drawing a winner after the show.</p>\r\n<h2>We look forward to seeing you!</h2>\r\n<p>November 26th 2014, Birmingham NEC</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.academiesshowbirmingham.co.uk/" target="_blank">Secure your place - it''s free to attend!</a></p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.academiesshowbirmingham.co.uk/exhibitor/arena-group/" target="_blank">Check out our exhibitor profile</a></p>\r\n<p>Join the Discussion&nbsp;<a href="http://https//twitter.com/ArenaGroup" target="_blank">@ArenaGroup</a> using <span class="font_blue">#AGevent</span></p>', '2014-07-07', 'iris-connect-academies-show-birmingham-2014-113.png', 'image/png', 82430, '2014-07-07 10:35:29', '', '2013-08-21 14:18:07', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 7, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'visit-us-at-the-academies-show-birmingham'),
(153, 'Digital Revolution for UK Credit Unions', 'Letting go of paper can release serious competitive advantage. Arena''s Document Solutions Specialist, Dan Lancaster, explores the phenomenon currently sweeping through several UK credit unions.', '<p><span class="introduction">Letting go of paper is releasing serious competitive advantage for several UK credit unions. Arena''s Document Solutions Specialist, Dan Lancaster, explores the impact of digitisation within the sector.</span><br /><br />In response to ever-growing member numbers, several UK credit unions are taking up the challenge of reducing their reliance on paper. Increased storage space, improved legal compliance and many other outcomes are giving them a serious competitive advantage. <br /><br />Many credit unions are dealing with more members as a result of the tough economic climate. This means increasing volumes of documentation that presents a growing challenge. Possibly at the top of the agenda is the need to balance legal requirements relating to the handling of confidential documents and data, with the need to improve customer service levels in response to a more competitive environment. Electronic document management software, often referred to as an EDRMS, is a proven solution that can deliver a surprising number of benefits.</p>\r\n<h2>What is an EDRMS?</h2>\r\n<p>An EDRMS supports the secure storage, sharing, processing and retrieval of documents in digital formats. When a paper document comes into the business it is scanned and all further processing is done electronically. Supported by a robust document management policy and processes, an EDRMS that is aligned with BS10008 enables paper originals to be destroyed.</p>\r\n<h2>What&rsquo;s in it for Credit Unions?</h2>\r\n<p>Taking the paper out of a business has the effect of clearing storage space, which makes for a nicer working environment and happy staff. In addition, there is no need to photocopy paperwork such as proof of identity documents, which are simply scanned into the system. This presents immediate financial savings relating to storage, copying and paper consumption. Eddie Hotham, Finance Manager of Hull and East Yorkshire Credit Union comments; &ldquo;we have saved the cost of document storage and made the set-up of accounts more efficient.&rdquo;<br /><br />As Eddie mentions, an EDRMS places documents, literally, at your fingertips, so there is no need to go searching through paper filing systems and the chaos caused by filing errors is a thing of the past. The direct customer service benefit is that your staff can answer queries immediately, which makes for satisfied members and could even reduce your phone bill. Sharon Walker, Office Manager at Kingdom Credit Union, tells us; &ldquo;our EDRMS is simplifying complex business operations &ndash; we would never go back to traipsing through boxes and boxes of paperwork.&rdquo;<br /><br />There is also a justification in terms of legal compliance and security, as has been found by Nottingham Credit Union. Operations Manager, Ella Ferris confirms; &ldquo;version control prevents documents from being over-written and any changes are logged. Encryption also limits access to confidential files to keep them secure.&rdquo; <br /><br />Sharon explains further, that an EDRMS addresses FSA requirements and offers protection from disasters such as fires and floods. &ldquo;We have total peace of mind that everything is backed up. We can also limit access to the system which is invaluable when you need to retain and protect confidential documents for long periods of time.&rdquo; Good systems also flag documents that have reached their retention expiry date and should be destroyed.</p>\r\n<h2>Top Tips on Functionality and Providers</h2>\r\n<p>We&rsquo;ve listed our top 5 considerations to look out for when choosing an EDRMS.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>References:</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Other credit unions are an obvious first port of call, and systems that are developed to meet the unique challenges faced by your business sector should also be on top of the pile.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Efficiency:</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Seek out a user-friendly system with quick, comprehensive and simple search tools.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Security:</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Be sure you can control who sees, amends and deletes files.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Compliance:</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Check that your system is aligned with BS10008, get advice on producing a sound records management policy and look for EDRMS functionality to audit user activity.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>\r\n<h3>Integration:</h3>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Look out for a system that integrates with your existing software and systems. This will minimise disruption to your current operations whilst you get used to working electronically.</p>\r\n<h3>About Dan Lancaster</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/153/contained_images/b55dbff2646c_262_Dan Lancaster.jpg?1395076109" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Document Solutions Specialist<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:DanielL@arenagroup.net">DanielL@arenagroup.net</a> | <a href="http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/daniel-lancaster/61/82/917" target="_blank">LinkedIN</a></p>\r\n<p>Dan has worked with Arena since 2011, advising customers on ways to increase efficiencies and reduce costs through addressing the way they work with documents. Dan is the key account manager for several UK credit unions who use Arena''s own specialist EDRMS software - <strong>&nbsp;</strong><a href="../../../page/arena-in-credit-unions"><strong>m</strong>store for Credit Unions</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="../../../page/arena-in-credit-unions">About <strong>m</strong>store for Credit Unions</a></p>', '2013-08-07', 'iStock_000020054949Medium.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 338741, '2013-08-28 11:06:05', '', '2013-08-28 10:53:53', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'digital-revolution-for-uk-credit-unions'),
(154, 'Volunteers roll up their sleeves for Herd Farm', 'Our willing volunteers have been hard at work on Herd Farm.', '<p><span class="introduction">Arena Group volunteers have returned to <a href="http://www.herdfarm.co.uk/" target="_blank">Herd Farm Activity Centre </a>to continue their good work.</span></p>\r\n<p>Herd Farm is an educational resource centre offering activities for young people at risk and those with disabilities. The centre is council run and relies on help from volunteers to carry out some of the maintenance work.</p>\r\n<p>Here at Arena we recognise the importance of the centre as a vital community resource. This is the third time a team of volunteers have attended this year to help with groundworks and maintenance.</p>\r\n<p>The team were kept busy, firstly clearing some steps after recent mole activity before working on the mountain biking track. A new section of track was in need of banking to aid cyclists in navigating corners, and resurfacing to ensure it was safe. After digging parts of the course out, our volunteers re-laid the track using materials recycled from elsewhere around the farm.</p>\r\n<p>This year''s work at Herd Farm has included painting, gardening, trench digging, path clearing and the creation of a barbeque area. Arena employees are encouraged to use their two annual days to volunteer in the local community.</p>\r\n<h2>Do you need our CSR support?</h2>\r\n<p>If you are a charity or community group in need of similar assistance, please contact Arena&rsquo;s CSR Coordinator, Debbie Burnell, on 0844 863 8000 or email <a href="mailto:DebbieB@arenagroup.net">DebbieB@arenagroup.net</a>.</p>\r\n<h3>Pictured (L &ndash; R): Mike Alsancak, Marketing Assistant based at Arena&rsquo;s Wakefield office, Damon Grave, Stock Warehouse Controller based at Arena&rsquo;s Garforth, Charlotte Howland, Sales Administrator and Sam Taylor, Document Solutions Specialist, both based at Arena&rsquo;s Wakefield office.</h3>', '2013-08-28', 'IMG_0084.JPG', 'image/jpeg', 139364, '2013-08-28 11:06:40', '', '2013-08-28 11:06:47', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 7, NULL, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'volunteers-roll-up-their-sleeves-for-herd-farm'),
(155, 'Join us at Education Innovation - February 2014', 'Arena will be hosting a stand F20 at the Education Innovation Conference and Exhibition at Manchester Central on February 27th and 28th 2014. Enter our prize draw for a chance to win one of two 3D camcorders!', '<p><span class="introduction">Join us on stand <strong>F20</strong> at the Education Innovation Conference and Exhibition (EICE). Manchester Central, 27th - 28th February 2014. </span></p>\r\n<p>The perfect opportunity to meet members of our team and chat about all things document management.</p>\r\n<p>We will be showcasing our full range of services; from <a href="../../../articles/112" target="_blank">print control software</a>, our <a href="../../../page/print-the-hidden-costs" target="_blank">Managed Print Service</a> (MPS) to <a href="http://http//www.arenagroup.net/page/edm-for-education" target="_blank"><strong>m</strong>store for Education</a>. Speak to our experts about how we can help you to improve efficiencies and reduce costs.</p>\r\n<h2><img style="float: right;" src="../../../assets/articles/155/contained_images/cb564812431f_258_camilioz100.jpg?1390395134" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="206" height="206" />WIN! A 3D Camcorder</h2>\r\n<p><span class="font_blue">Visit our stand and enter our prize draw to get your hands on one of two 3D camcorders from Toshiba.</span></p>\r\n<p>EICE is now in its second year and aims to help education leaders and practitioners to raise levels of achievement by making more effective use of innovation and technology.&nbsp; It will feature over 50 practical workshops and CPD seminars, delivered by some of the most inspiring individuals within education.&nbsp; The event will also include discussion and debate from ministers and sector leaders.</p>\r\n<p>New features will include a dedicated &lsquo;Innovation In Practice&rsquo; centre where teachers, educators, business managers and network managers will showcase the latest ideas and demonstrate how they can be put to practical use to raise achievement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Education Innovation is proud to be co-located with the<a href="http://www.ioe.mmu.ac.uk/business/cie/apple-conference.php" target="_blank"> iThink Therefore iPad 2014</a> conference and the Raspberry Jamboree.</p>\r\n<p>Event manager David Ventris-Field said: <em>&ldquo;Building on the success of last year&rsquo;s Education Innovation, we&rsquo;re really focusing on how innovation can be used to raise achievement with lots of practical, hands-on workshops for teachers and lecturers and more strategic content for education leaders and business managers.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p>Find out more at <a href="http://educationinnovation.co.uk/home/" target="_blank">www.educationinnovation.co.uk</a><br />Follow the show <a href="http://twitter.com/EICEmanchester" target="_blank">@EICEManchester</a> | #EICE</p>', '2014-01-14', 'edu inno.png', 'image/png', 194060, '2013-08-30 10:10:20', '', '2013-08-28 14:12:58', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 7, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'join-us-at-education-innovation-february-2014'),
(156, '£70bn tied up in inefficient government processes', 'This week, government Think Tank, Policy Exchange, published a report claiming that the UK government could save £24bn per year between now and 2020 through increased use of digital technology.', '<p class="introduction">This week, government Think Tank, Policy Exchange, published a report claiming that the UK government could save &pound;24bn per year between now and 2020 through increased use of digital technology.</p>\r\n<p>The report, entitled &ldquo;<em>smaller, better, faster, stronger &ndash; remaking government for the digital age</em>&rdquo;, cites several areas where major savings could be made &ndash; to the tune of &pound;70bn between now and 2020.</p>\r\n<p>Areas for improvement include IT purchasing and website development; but the multitude of paper-led business processes also came in for criticism: <em>The Crown Prosecution Service prints one million sheets of paper every day, while two articulated lorries arrive at the DVLA daily, carrying letters and paperwork. In order to complete a passport application form online, the Passport  Office will print the form out and post it back for the individual to  sign and send back.&nbsp; </em></p>\r\n<p>So, what''s the answer? We chatted to Arena''s Neil Maude and Ian Fox to get their views on the report.<em><br /></em></p>\r\n<h2>Digitising paper-led processes</h2>\r\n<p>Over recent years we will all have noticed local and national government efforts to reduce the paper trail relating to certain processes. For example, applications for vehicle tax renewal can now be completed online.</p>\r\n<p>Arena&rsquo;s Electronic Document Management General Manager, Neil Maude, comments; &ldquo;Policy Exchange is calling for much greater digitisation of government processes." Neil notes that this could require the state to embrace a number of new technologies but, in his view, an electronic document and records management system (EDRMS) should be high on the wish list. "A well thought through print and copy strategy and a good EDRMS is the bedrock of efficienct document management. The technology has been established for several years, is proving itself in a growing number of businesses and is continually developing so these are logical first steps.</p>\r\n<p>Every day we support businesses in taking steps to digitise their processes and often the action is prompted by a desire to reduce paper and improve efficiencies. The transition can take time and is often managed in stages &ndash; especially in cases where a business manages a large number of processes and has a legacy that is deeply paper-led. Supported by a good document management system (EDRMS) and a robust data management policy and processes, there can be so many knock-on benefits. Greater data security, cost reductions relating to consumables, increased efficiency and improved, faster customer service, to name just a few - so it&rsquo;s certainly worthwhile."</p>\r\n<h2>Think before you print</h2>\r\n<p>As mentioned by Neil, the story doesn&rsquo;t stop with digitising processes, and a good print and copy strategy is fundamental.</p>\r\n<p>Arena''s Professional Services Manager, Ian Fox, comments; "it is difficult to imagine a completely paper-free business and very few truly paperless offices exist. There are some documents that we just need to print."</p>\r\n<p>Ian explains that a good starting point is to review your current print and copy strategy, infrastructure and behaviour. Ian continues; "this review might present various options that might include the development of a policy to nurture greater employee awareness. We may also consider a Managed Print Service to simplify the billing and maintenance of your printers. Combining this with technology to increase transparency and reduce wasteful and unnecessary printing can certainly create a &lsquo;less paper office&rsquo; and all the related benefits. &ndash; Cost savings, a smaller carbon footprint, more considerate user behaviour and greater efficiency."</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/publications/category/item/smaller-better-faster-stronger" target="_blank">Policy Exchange report</a></p>\r\n<p><strong></strong><a href="../../page/electronic-document-management" target="_blank"><strong>m</strong>store &ndash; Arena&rsquo;s software for electronic document management (EDRMS)</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../page/copy-and-print" target="_blank">MPS &ndash; controlling print and copy</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../page/print-control" target="_blank">Print control &ndash; tips for reducing wasteful and unnecessary printing</a></p>\r\n<p><a href="../../case_studies" target="_blank">Case studies &ndash; paper reduction through effective document management</a></p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude and Ian Fox</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Neil Maude: Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0844 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of  experience in the electronic document management industry, working with  both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<p><img src="../../..//assets/articles/156/contained_images/14027a085312_276_Ian Fox Jan15 large.jpg?1422352750" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="113" height="113" align="LEFT" />Ian Fox: Professional Services Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:ianF@arenagroup.net">ianF@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Ian Fox joined the Arena Group as a Systems Engineer in 1995. During his time at Arena he has gained a wealth of experience in helping organisations with their document related workflows. He now heads up the Professional Services department, which was formed in January 2011 with the aim of ensuring that existing and future Arena clients receive the best possible advice, solutions and support to enable them to manage and control their documents effectively.</p>', '2013-09-03', 'iStock_000021772861Medium.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 185741, '2013-09-03 09:18:24', 'process efficiency', '2013-09-03 09:18:26', '2015-02-02 10:13:46', 3, 7, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, '70bn-tied-up-in-inefficient-government-processes'),
(157, 'Innovate My School Live in Nottingham: Nov 19th 2013', 'This FREE event will bring together some of the industry’s most established thought-leaders and bright up-and-coming future stars to provide insights into the hottest innovations, trends and developments that will define education for years to come.', '<p class="introduction">In November, Arena''s Paul Grant will be presenting at a special Innovate My School Live event exclusively for members of the Nottingham Association of School Business Managers.</p>\r\n<p>This <strong>FREE event</strong> will bring together some of the  industry&rsquo;s most established  thought-leaders and bright up-and-coming  future stars to Center Parcs in Nottinghamshire, giving delegates an insight into  the hottest innovations  and vital technological trends and developments  that will define  education for years to come.</p>\r\n<p>Arena''s <strong>Paul Grant</strong> will be showcasing our software for electronic document management; <strong></strong><a href="../../page/edm-for-education" target="_blank"><strong>m</strong>store for Education</a>.</p>\r\n<h2>Further Information</h2>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.innovatemyschool.com/live.html" target="_blank">http://www.innovatemyschool.com/live.html </a></p>\r\n<h2>Venue and Date:</h2>\r\n<div class="cparam event-location">\r\n<div id="community-event-data-location" class="cdata">Center Parcs, Nottingham</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="cparam event-created">\r\n<div class="cdata small">19th November 2013, 10am</div>\r\n</div>', '2013-08-31', '205_ims_live_logo_300.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 52532, '2013-09-03 11:25:53', 'IMS Live', '2013-09-03 11:25:53', '2014-10-08 11:56:29', 3, NULL, 0, NULL, 0, 0, NULL, 'innovate-my-school-live-in-nottingham-nov-19th-2013'),
(158, 'ICO Guidance on Data Protection Compliance in Schools', 'Are you compliant with the ever-changing regulations surrounding the way you manage data and documents?', '<p class="introduction">The Information Commissioner&rsquo;s Office (ICO) carried out a survey of 400 schools and their data protection processes. On the whole there was a good awareness of the data protection laws but the ICO concluded that schools needed to work harder to meet the requirements.</p>\r\n<p>Almost a year on, we are re-visiting the ICO guidance on Data Protection, to combine their top tips with some practical advice on compliance.</p>\r\n<h2>The ICO&rsquo;s Guidance</h2>\r\n<p>The ICO&rsquo;s top tips towards compliance are to <strong><em>prepare</em></strong>, <strong><em>notify</em></strong>, <strong><em>be fair</em></strong> and <em><strong>keep it secure</strong></em>.</p>\r\n<h2>Prepare</h2>\r\n<p>To ensure full compliance the ICO recommends the enforcement of clear and practical policies in all areas that affect good information governance. Backing these up with written procedures helps staff to be aware of their responsibilities.  Further to this, ensuring that the relevant employees are correctly trained will reduce errors.</p>\r\n<p>The ICO also recommends involving someone knowledgeable about information rights and record management to ensure compliance with the Data Protection Act.</p>\r\n<p>A document audit is a good first step towards clarifying exactly what information is held and crucially how, why, when and who accesses and processes that data.  From that point of understanding, the creation and maintenance of a clear records management policy becomes the natural next step. (See our separate articles on these practices for further advice).</p>\r\n<p>We would agree that it is vital that the responsibility for compliance lies with a senior manager, to ensure the issue is given the prominence it requires. As the report states, &lsquo;information governance is not optional&rsquo;.</p>\r\n<h2>Notify and be fair</h2>\r\n<p>You must notify the ICO of how you use personal data about parents and pupils. A school is responsible for its own notification and keeping the details updated whenever any new purposes for processing personal data are introduced. For example, a school installing CCTV must update its notification accordingly.</p>\r\n<p>As early as possible; before, or as soon as you obtain their personal information, a &ldquo;fair processing notice&rdquo; should be given to parents and pupils. This details what personal information is being collected and why.</p>\r\n<p>Giving ownership of your records management policy to a senior member of your management team will ensure that these notification rules are kept in mind. The notification will need attention when any new processes or mechanisms are implemented that will impact upon how data is captured, processed or stored.</p>\r\n<h2>Keep it secure</h2>\r\n<p>The report states that fair processing &lsquo;<em>requires that you control access to personal information</em>&rsquo;. Systems need to be put in place to ensure that only those people who need information have access to it; and only when they need it.</p>\r\n<p>An electronic document and records management system (EDRMS) is a good option for managing this. Functionality to set passwords for individual users, and to control which information they can access, can help you to comply. A good EDRMS will also let you report on user activity and evidence that documents are secure.</p>\r\n<p>Data access via personal devices such as laptops, tablets and mobile phones was a key area highlighted by the report. Electronic devices must be kept secure; this is a legal requirement if those devices hold confidential personal data. The ICO advises putting procedures in place to monitor devices being taken out of school and when data is transmitted. In these instances, strong passwords must be used and memory keys; identified in the report as one of the main routes for data loss, should be fully encrypted.</p>\r\n<p>Once again, there are systems on the market that can ensure compliance with these rules. Keeping your data in a secure EDRMS that is accessible via an internet browser, for example, is one way to ensure security and monitor data access, whilst removing the need to transfer data onto any mobile devices.</p>\r\n<p>Following the ICO&rsquo;s recommendations will ensure that you do not fall foul of the changing Data Protection laws. The effort of putting policies and procedures in place and then to stay up to date is far outweighed by the potential damage to a school&rsquo;s reputation, not to mention the financial penalties, that could be incurred by not complying.</p>\r\n<h3>About Neil Maude</h3>\r\n<p><img src="../../assets/articles/113/contained_images/8d9e8419f6d7_180_NeilM_ws.jpg?1359557446" border="0" alt="" hspace="10" vspace="10" width="100" align="left" /></p>\r\n<p>Electronic Document Management General Manager<br />Tel: 0800 863 8000 | Email: <a href="mailto:neilM@arenagroup.net">neilM@arenagroup.net</a></p>\r\n<p>Neil joined the Arena Group in 2006 and has almost 20 years of   experience in the electronic document management industry, working with   both private and public sector customers.&nbsp; Neil sits on Arena&rsquo;s board  of  directors and manages the delivery operations of Arena&rsquo;s EDM  business.&nbsp;  His team spend their time developing software, implementing  solutions  for customers and providing after-sales software support  services, both  in the UK and internationally.</p>\r\n<h2>Further information</h2>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="http://www.ico.org.uk/news/latest_news/2012/~/media/documents/library/Data_Protection/Research_and_reports/report_dp_guidance_for_schools.ashx" target="_blank">View the full ICO report</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../page/electronic-document-management">Electronic document management from Arena Group (EDRMS)</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../case_studies?tag=Education">Case Studies: EDM in Education</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/149?tag=Expert+News">VIDEO: Compliance in Education</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Related articles:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/113?tag=Expert+News" target="_blank">Creating a records management policy</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/120" target="_blank">Conducting a 5 step information audit</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/131" target="_blank">Information access and security</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/136">Information Disposal</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/147?tag=Expert+News">Email Management</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="../../../articles/150" target="_blank">Risk and disaster recovery</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>', '2013-09-09', 'SECURElaptop_ws.jpg', 'image/jpeg', 52805, '2014-12-11 14:43:51', '', '2013-09-05 09:04:51', '2014-12-11 14:43:51', 7, 3, 0, NULL, 1, 0, NULL, 'ico-guidance-on-data-protection-compliance-in-schools');
